window.SCOPE_DATA = {"generatedAt":"2026-07-02T12:40:44.909Z","counts":{"optionA":106,"optionB":158,"doc12":106,"doc13":53},"meta":{"intro":{"A":"One film, launched direct to consumer at full scale. The client's scoping bar: 100,000 concurrent viewers at the launch spike, on web, iOS, Android, Roku, Fire TV, and Samsung TV, streaming up to 4K, paid via one-time pay-per-view (permanent access, no free trial). The user experience is a straight-line conversion: see the film, pay, watch, with pause and resume. No catalog browsing, search, or recommendations; the selection UI is built so it extends to a catalog later.","B":"A browsable streaming platform holding 100 to 500 titles streamable at any given time, with a weekly big release driving a concurrency spike, launched with a marketing push and built to retain viewers across titles. Basic search and genre browse in the style of Apple TV Plus; no recommendation engine. Payment is pay-per-view via Stripe in the base scope; a 2-tier subscription is scoped separately as a variant (epic B-SUB) so it can be priced independently."}},"epics":[{"id":"CAP-ID","title":"Identity and accounts","summaryA":"Viewer identity across every V1 surface (web, iOS, Android, Roku, Fire TV, Samsung Tizen), identical in scope for Option A and Option B: sign-up and sign-in with email and password, Apple, and Google, password reset, TV activation-code pairing, central session and token management, basic account self-service, and access continuity when a paid account's session expires. Option A still requires the full epic because all six surfaces ship in both options (Jul 1 call, John, 42:39). This epic supplies the session and device registry that the concurrent-screens check reads; the check itself is enforced at playback start by CAP-PLAY (Jul 1 call, John, 36:13 + Allion default). It excludes operator console access (owned by CAP-CON), contractual rights management (out of V1 scope, Jul 1 call, John, 16:49), anti-circumvention hardening beyond the basic screens limit (deterrence only, Jul 1 call, John, 36:13), and multi-user profiles under one account, which are excluded from base scope (Assumption - client to confirm); multi-member account concepts appeared only in the Jun 22 subscription-tier discussion (33:15 to 34:46) and are estimated separately under B-SUB. Supersedes the sign-up, login, and reset scope of V1-VS-02.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-ID-01, CAP-ID-02, CAP-ID-03, CAP-ID-04, CAP-ID-05, CAP-ID-06, CAP-ID-07, CAP-ID-08, CAP-ID-09 (all A+B, apply unchanged). This epic has no B-only stories.","resolvedIds":["CAP-ID-01","CAP-ID-02","CAP-ID-03","CAP-ID-04","CAP-ID-05","CAP-ID-06","CAP-ID-07","CAP-ID-08","CAP-ID-09"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-ID-01","CAP-ID-02","CAP-ID-03","CAP-ID-04","CAP-ID-05","CAP-ID-06","CAP-ID-07","CAP-ID-08","CAP-ID-09"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY","title":"Payments and entitlements","summaryA":"This epic covers the full pay-per-view money path for both options: Stripe checkout (card plus the wallet rails Stripe provides), declined-payment handling with clear retry, purchase confirmation and email receipt, a permanent buy-to-own entitlement record, recovery when the app fails mid-purchase, the US-only geo gate at purchase and at playback start, the concurrent-screens limit, US sales tax via Stripe Tax, and refund/chargeback operations run through the Stripe dashboard. Payment starts from day one; there is no free trial. Explicitly excluded: any subscription model (separately estimated as the B-SUB variant epic), rental or expiry windows, in-app refund tooling, VPN countermeasures, and contractual rights management. Supersedes the payment portion of the pre-call backlog (V1-VS-03).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-PAY-01, CAP-PAY-02, CAP-PAY-03, CAP-PAY-04, CAP-PAY-05, CAP-PAY-06, CAP-PAY-07, CAP-PAY-08, CAP-PAY-09 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-PAY-01","CAP-PAY-02","CAP-PAY-03","CAP-PAY-04","CAP-PAY-05","CAP-PAY-06","CAP-PAY-07","CAP-PAY-08","CAP-PAY-09"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-PAY-01","CAP-PAY-02","CAP-PAY-03","CAP-PAY-04","CAP-PAY-05","CAP-PAY-06","CAP-PAY-07","CAP-PAY-08","CAP-PAY-09","CAP-PAY-10"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY","title":"Playback","summaryA":"This epic defines the viewing experience as a platform-agnostic capability shared by both options: stream start with access checks, adaptive quality, player controls, captions, cross-device resume, session heartbeat, and error handling. Per-platform delivery and certification live in the PLAT epics, which reference these capability ACs and add only platform-specific scenarios. Excluded from this epic: DRM license and watermarking mechanics (CAP-DRM), entitlement and screen-limit rule ownership (CAP-PAY), catalog and continue-watching UI (B-DISC), and metering aggregation and unit-economics reporting (CAP-MET). This epic supersedes the capability half of V1-VS-04; the per-platform half is superseded by the PLAT epics.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-PLAY-01, CAP-PLAY-02, CAP-PLAY-03, CAP-PLAY-04, CAP-PLAY-05, CAP-PLAY-06, CAP-PLAY-07, and CAP-PLAY-08 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-PLAY-01","CAP-PLAY-02","CAP-PLAY-03","CAP-PLAY-04","CAP-PLAY-05","CAP-PLAY-06","CAP-PLAY-07","CAP-PLAY-08"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-PLAY-01","CAP-PLAY-02","CAP-PLAY-03","CAP-PLAY-04","CAP-PLAY-05","CAP-PLAY-06","CAP-PLAY-07","CAP-PLAY-08","CAP-PLAY-09"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM","title":"DRM and watermarking","summaryA":"This epic covers anti-piracy protection for both options: multi-DRM content encryption and license delivery (Widevine, FairPlay, PlayReady) through the managed video platform, license service behavior under the premiere load profile, forensic session watermarking, and standard output protection (HDCP) as a platform default. John confirmed on the Jul 1 call (16:49) that anti-piracy is very important, clarifying that the earlier discussion had concerned contractual rights management rather than anti-piracy technology. Explicitly out of scope: contractual rights management (tracking who earns off copyright), which John placed out of scope on the same call, plus VPN countermeasures and any hard anti-circumvention build beyond casual-sharing deterrence, both out of scope for V1 per the calls and Allion scoping decisions.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-DRM-01, CAP-DRM-02, CAP-DRM-03, CAP-DRM-04, CAP-DRM-05, CAP-DRM-06, and CAP-DRM-07 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-DRM-01","CAP-DRM-02","CAP-DRM-03","CAP-DRM-04","CAP-DRM-05","CAP-DRM-06","CAP-DRM-07"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-DRM-01","CAP-DRM-02","CAP-DRM-03","CAP-DRM-04","CAP-DRM-05","CAP-DRM-06","CAP-DRM-07","CAP-DRM-08"]},{"id":"CAP-CON","title":"Content console","summaryA":"This epic covers the single-user internal console that one operator uses to ingest, describe, price, and publish titles in both options (Jun 22 call, John: content is handled by one internal team, with no multi-user roles and no review or approval workflow). Shared A+B stories cover operator login, title drafts, film master upload, encoding status, metadata, artwork, multi-language subtitles, price assignment, and publish control. Option B additions (bulk import of the purchased library, batch progress view, scheduled publish, curated row management) are documented in the Option B document. Explicitly excluded from both options: multi-user admin and roles, content review workflow, external creator marketplace, contractual rights management, auto-generated captions, and viewing analytics (metering is scoped in CAP-MET).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-CON-01, CAP-CON-02, CAP-CON-03, CAP-CON-04, CAP-CON-05, CAP-CON-06, CAP-CON-07, CAP-CON-08, CAP-CON-09 apply unchanged. The stories below are Option B only.","resolvedIds":["CAP-CON-01","CAP-CON-02","CAP-CON-03","CAP-CON-04","CAP-CON-05","CAP-CON-06","CAP-CON-07","CAP-CON-08","CAP-CON-09"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-CON-01","CAP-CON-02","CAP-CON-03","CAP-CON-04","CAP-CON-05","CAP-CON-06","CAP-CON-07","CAP-CON-08","CAP-CON-09","CAP-CON-10","CAP-CON-11","CAP-CON-12","CAP-CON-13"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE","title":"Managed pipeline integration and validation spike","summaryA":"This epic covers integration with a managed video platform for the full media path: master ingest from the content console, encode ladder configuration, secure playback token issuance, CDN delivery, and pulling platform delivery metrics into our observability. It is written vendor-agnostic, with Bunny Stream as the reference platform, and includes a timeboxed validation spike whose output is a go/no-go on the reference platform versus a Mux-class alternative. The managed-platform route was chosen for build time, not unit cost (Jul 1 call, John, 15:48). Explicitly excluded: the operator console UI (CAP-CON), player behaviour and UX (CAP-PLAY), DRM and watermarking configuration (CAP-DRM), full-scale 100K load testing (CAP-INF), and catalog or discovery features (B-DISC).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-PIPE-01, CAP-PIPE-02, CAP-PIPE-03, CAP-PIPE-04, CAP-PIPE-05, CAP-PIPE-06, CAP-PIPE-07, CAP-PIPE-08 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-PIPE-01","CAP-PIPE-02","CAP-PIPE-03","CAP-PIPE-04","CAP-PIPE-05","CAP-PIPE-06","CAP-PIPE-07","CAP-PIPE-08"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-PIPE-01","CAP-PIPE-02","CAP-PIPE-03","CAP-PIPE-04","CAP-PIPE-05","CAP-PIPE-06","CAP-PIPE-07","CAP-PIPE-08","CAP-PIPE-09"]},{"id":"CAP-MET","title":"Metering and unit economics","summaryA":"This epic delivers the minimal metering the client asked for on the Jul 1 call (John, 31:02): enough data to show per-stream unit economics (price charged vs cost to stream) and a variable-vs-fixed split of infrastructure costs, for accounting purposes. It covers playback session records, GB delivered per session and per title, a simple internal cost and revenue view per title, variable-vs-fixed cost tagging, and CSV export for the client's accounting team. It explicitly excludes full product analytics: funnels, cohorts, marketing attribution, recommendation data feeds, and audience dashboards are out of V1 scope and deferred (Jun 22 call, John, 19:49, analytics named as a later bolt-on; pre-call phasing placed the viewing-analytics dashboard in a later phase). All stories in this document are shared across Options A and B. The catalog-wide rollup (CAP-MET-07) is Option B only and appears in the Option B document.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-MET-01, CAP-MET-02, CAP-MET-03, CAP-MET-04, CAP-MET-05, CAP-MET-06 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-MET-01","CAP-MET-02","CAP-MET-03","CAP-MET-04","CAP-MET-05","CAP-MET-06"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-MET-01","CAP-MET-02","CAP-MET-03","CAP-MET-04","CAP-MET-05","CAP-MET-06","CAP-MET-07"]},{"id":"CAP-INF","title":"Platform infrastructure and surge protection","summaryA":"This epic covers back-end platform readiness for a premiere spike: environments, CI/CD, an auto-scaling application backend (catalogue, accounts, entitlements, playback session services), observability, surge protection at the front door, and a load-test environment capable of the 100,000 concurrent full-journey premiere test at month 4 to 5. The load-test environment is a build deliverable in its own right, not just a QA task. It excludes the video encoding, storage, and CDN delivery layer (provided by the managed video platform, see CAP-PIPE), the business metering and unit-economics views (CAP-MET), entitlement business rules (CAP-PAY), and per-platform client performance work (PLAT-* epics). Multi-region infrastructure is out of scope for V1 in both options.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: CAP-INF-01, CAP-INF-02, CAP-INF-03, CAP-INF-04, CAP-INF-05, CAP-INF-06, CAP-INF-07 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["CAP-INF-01","CAP-INF-02","CAP-INF-03","CAP-INF-04","CAP-INF-05","CAP-INF-06","CAP-INF-07"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["CAP-INF-01","CAP-INF-02","CAP-INF-03","CAP-INF-04","CAP-INF-05","CAP-INF-06","CAP-INF-07","CAP-INF-08"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB","title":"Web application","summaryA":"This epic delivers the browser client on Chrome, Edge, Safari, and Firefox, responsive across desktop, tablet, and phone screen sizes. It covers the web pages and flows only: landing, film detail, checkout, player, account, and TV-activation entry. Capability logic (identity, payments and entitlements, playback engine, DRM licensing) lives in CAP-ID, CAP-PAY, CAP-PLAY, and CAP-DRM; stories here reference those ACs and add only web-specific scenarios. Option B adds catalog home, curated rows, genre browse, search, and watchlist surfaces on top of B-DISC (see the Option B additions in doc 13). Native mobile and TV apps (PLAT-IOS, PLAT-AND, PLAT-ROKU, PLAT-FTV, PLAT-SAM) and 100K-concurrent load testing (CAP-INF) are out of this epic.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: PLAT-WEB-01 and PLAT-WEB-03 through PLAT-WEB-08 apply unchanged. PLAT-WEB-02 (single-film landing page) is Option A only; under Option B the web home is the catalog home page (PLAT-WEB-09).","resolvedIds":["PLAT-WEB-01","PLAT-WEB-03","PLAT-WEB-04","PLAT-WEB-05","PLAT-WEB-06","PLAT-WEB-07","PLAT-WEB-08"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-WEB-01","PLAT-WEB-02","PLAT-WEB-03","PLAT-WEB-04","PLAT-WEB-05","PLAT-WEB-06","PLAT-WEB-07","PLAT-WEB-08","PLAT-WEB-09","PLAT-WEB-10","PLAT-WEB-11","PLAT-WEB-12","PLAT-WEB-13"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS","title":"iOS application","summaryA":"Native iOS application delivering the full viewer journey on iOS devices (iPhone-first, with iPad handling an assumption to confirm): install, land on the film, sign in, pay, and watch with FairPlay protection. Option A scope covers the app shell, single-film landing and detail, account, the purchase path (presented as a client scoping decision between Apple In-App Purchase and purchase-on-web), the player, and App Store certification. Option B adds catalog browse, search, curated rows, watchlist, and continue watching on top of the B-DISC capability. This epic excludes the shared backend capabilities (identity, payments, playback, DRM licensing, pipeline, metering), which live in the CAP epics and are referenced rather than restated; it also excludes Apple tvOS (a flagged option line in Option B only) and all V1 exclusions recorded in doc 17 (offline download, recommendation engine, multi-region).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"Shared with Option A, see doc 12: PLAT-IOS-01, PLAT-IOS-02, PLAT-IOS-03, PLAT-IOS-04, PLAT-IOS-05, PLAT-IOS-06 apply unchanged.","resolvedIds":["PLAT-IOS-01","PLAT-IOS-02","PLAT-IOS-03","PLAT-IOS-04","PLAT-IOS-05","PLAT-IOS-06"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-IOS-01","PLAT-IOS-02","PLAT-IOS-03","PLAT-IOS-04","PLAT-IOS-05","PLAT-IOS-06","PLAT-IOS-07","PLAT-IOS-08","PLAT-IOS-09"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND","title":"Android application","summaryA":"This epic delivers the native Android phone application, one of the six V1 delivery surfaces (Jun 22 call; Jul 1 call, 28:12; Jul 1 call, John, 42:39). Option A covers the app shell, landing and film detail, account, the purchase path, Widevine playback, and Google Play certification; Option B adds catalog browse, curated rows, search, watchlist, and continue watching. Shared behavior is defined once in the capability epics (CAP-ID, CAP-PAY, CAP-PLAY, CAP-DRM, CAP-PIPE, CAP-INF); this epic adds only Android-specific scenarios. Explicitly excluded: Android TV and Chromecast casting (not in the V1 device list), offline download (out of scope V1, register item 19), and any operator console surface (CAP-CON, not a mobile deliverable).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"The Option A scope stories for this epic (PLAT-AND-01 to PLAT-AND-07, see doc 12) also apply under Option B; the stories below are the Option B additions.","resolvedIds":["PLAT-AND-01","PLAT-AND-02","PLAT-AND-03","PLAT-AND-04","PLAT-AND-05","PLAT-AND-06","PLAT-AND-07"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-AND-01","PLAT-AND-02","PLAT-AND-03","PLAT-AND-04","PLAT-AND-05","PLAT-AND-06","PLAT-AND-07","PLAT-AND-08","PLAT-AND-09","PLAT-AND-10"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU","title":"Roku channel","summaryA":"This epic delivers the Roku channel (built on Roku SceneGraph) for both options: channel shell, landing and film detail screens, TV activation-code sign-in, remote-control navigation, playback, the purchase path, and Roku certification. Shared behavior (identity, payments and entitlements, playback rules, DRM, geo and stream limits) is defined once in the capability epics; this epic adds only Roku-specific scenarios and references capability ACs rather than restating them. Option B adds catalog rows, genre browse, remote-friendly search, continue-watching, and watchlist on top of the Option A channel (stories listed in the Option B additions document of this pack). Explicitly excluded: other TV platforms (PLAT-FTV, PLAT-SAM), the content console (CAP-CON), the video pipeline (CAP-PIPE), recommendation engine, and offline download (out of scope V1 per both calls).","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"The Option A scope stories for this epic (PLAT-ROKU-01 through PLAT-ROKU-07, see the Option A document) also apply to Option B; the stories below are additions on top of that channel.","resolvedIds":["PLAT-ROKU-01","PLAT-ROKU-02","PLAT-ROKU-03","PLAT-ROKU-04","PLAT-ROKU-05","PLAT-ROKU-06","PLAT-ROKU-07"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-ROKU-01","PLAT-ROKU-02","PLAT-ROKU-03","PLAT-ROKU-04","PLAT-ROKU-05","PLAT-ROKU-06","PLAT-ROKU-07","PLAT-ROKU-08","PLAT-ROKU-09","PLAT-ROKU-10","PLAT-ROKU-11","PLAT-ROKU-12"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV","title":"Fire TV application","summaryA":"This epic covers the Fire TV (Fire OS) delivery surface: the app shell, landing and film detail screens, TV activation-code sign-in, the purchase path, playback, remote navigation, and Amazon Appstore certification for Option A, with catalog rows, genre browse, search, continue watching, and watchlist added under Option B. It delivers the platform-specific layer only: identity, payments, entitlements, playback, DRM, and discovery logic live in the capability epics (CAP-ID, CAP-PAY, CAP-PLAY, CAP-DRM, B-DISC) and are referenced, not restated. Explicitly excluded: other TV platforms (see PLAT-ROKU, PLAT-SAM), offline download, recommendation engine (out of scope in both options), and Alexa voice search (Assumption - client to confirm). One purchase-path policy question is flagged for a client decision inside PLAT-FTV-06; this epic presents both patterns and does not decide.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"The Option A scope stories (PLAT-FTV-01 to PLAT-FTV-07, see doc 12) also apply under Option B; the stories below are the Option B additions for the Fire TV surface, covering catalog rows, genre browse, search, continue watching, and watchlist.","resolvedIds":["PLAT-FTV-01","PLAT-FTV-02","PLAT-FTV-03","PLAT-FTV-04","PLAT-FTV-05","PLAT-FTV-06","PLAT-FTV-07"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-FTV-01","PLAT-FTV-02","PLAT-FTV-03","PLAT-FTV-04","PLAT-FTV-05","PLAT-FTV-06","PLAT-FTV-07","PLAT-FTV-08","PLAT-FTV-09","PLAT-FTV-10","PLAT-FTV-11","PLAT-FTV-12"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM","title":"Samsung TV application","summaryA":"This epic covers the Samsung Tizen TV application for both options: app shell and store packaging, landing and film detail screens, remote-driven navigation, DRM playback (PlayReady, with Widevine where the Tizen model supports it), TV activation-code sign-in, the on-TV purchase path, and Samsung certification. Option B adds the catalog experience on the TV surface: curated rows, genre browse, search, and continue watching plus watchlist (those stories appear in the Option B additions document). It explicitly excludes capability logic (identity, payments, entitlements, playback rules, DRM licensing), which lives in the CAP epics and is referenced here rather than restated, and it excludes other TV platforms (Roku and Fire TV have their own epics; LG webOS and Apple tvOS are a flagged option line under Option B per the decision register and are not scoped here). One open flag runs through this epic: Samsung store billing policy (Samsung Checkout) may apply to in-app purchases, so PLAT-SAM-06 presents both purchase paths with their cost impact and leaves the choice with the client.","summaryB":null,"sharedRef":{"text":"All Option A scope stories in this epic (PLAT-SAM-01 through PLAT-SAM-08, see doc 12) apply unchanged in Option B; the stories below add the catalog experience on the Samsung TV surface.","resolvedIds":["PLAT-SAM-01","PLAT-SAM-02","PLAT-SAM-03","PLAT-SAM-04","PLAT-SAM-05","PLAT-SAM-06","PLAT-SAM-07","PLAT-SAM-08"]},"inA":true,"inB":true,"storyIds":["PLAT-SAM-01","PLAT-SAM-02","PLAT-SAM-03","PLAT-SAM-04","PLAT-SAM-05","PLAT-SAM-06","PLAT-SAM-07","PLAT-SAM-08","PLAT-SAM-09","PLAT-SAM-10","PLAT-SAM-11","PLAT-SAM-12"]},{"id":"B-DISC","title":"Catalog and discovery (Option B only)","summaryA":null,"summaryB":"This epic delivers the discovery layer that makes Option B's 100 to 500 title catalog browsable: the client-facing catalog of published titles, genre browse, basic text search, operator-curated rows, a cross-device continue-watching rail, and a per-account watchlist. It follows John's direction of a basic search and basic browse experience modeled on Apple TV Plus (Jul 1, 39:34). Explicitly out of scope: any recommendation engine and any personalization beyond the viewer's own activity (continue watching and watchlist). This epic has no presence in Option A, which is a single-film straight-line conversion with no catalog to discover.","sharedRef":null,"inA":false,"inB":true,"storyIds":["B-DISC-01","B-DISC-02","B-DISC-03","B-DISC-04","B-DISC-05","B-DISC-06","B-DISC-07","B-DISC-08"]},{"id":"B-SUB","title":"Subscription variant (separately estimated)","summaryA":null,"summaryB":"This epic scopes a two-tier subscription offering layered on top of Option B's pay-per-view base. It is a variant, estimated separately, and is not part of the base scope of either option: both options launch PPV-only (Jul 1 call, John, 23:02; register #4), and this epic exists only if the client decides to add subscription to Option B. It covers two tiers on Stripe recurring billing, baked-in tier entitlement rules, subscribe, upgrade, downgrade and cancel, lapsed-payment handling with dunning, coexistence with PPV purchases, per-tier screen limits, operator tier assignment, a subscriber self-service management view, and subscription metering. It explicitly excludes a dynamic admin control center for managing bundles or rules (Jun 22 call, John, 34:06; per-title tier assignment in the console is the one deliberate carve-out, see B-SUB-08), more than two tiers, and free trials (inherited from the base no-free-trial decision, register #3 and #19; a subscription trial would be a scope change, client to confirm).","sharedRef":null,"inA":false,"inB":true,"storyIds":["B-SUB-01","B-SUB-02","B-SUB-03","B-SUB-04","B-SUB-05","B-SUB-06","B-SUB-07","B-SUB-08","B-SUB-09","B-SUB-10"]}],"stories":[{"id":"CAP-ID-01","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Email and password sign-up and sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to create an account with my email and a password and sign back in later, so that my purchases and playback access are tied to one identity on any device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 21:36) + Jun 22 call (Windana, 25:50)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"None"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build of the core account service; consumed by all six platform surfaces; must hold under the 100K concurrent premiere login storm (load bar owned by CAP-INF, Jul 1 call, John, 29:16 and 35:09)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Password rules","value":"the published password rules are a configurable rule set; baseline default is minimum length 8 characters with no other composition rules (Assumption - client to confirm). CAP-ID-04 and CAP-ID-07 reference this rule set."},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: New viewer creates an account\n  Given a visitor with an email address that is not already registered\n  When they submit that email and a password that meets the published password rules\n  Then an account is created and the viewer is signed in on that surface\n\nScenario: Sign-up blocked for an email already in use\n  Given an account already exists for viewer@example.com\n  When a visitor attempts to sign up with viewer@example.com\n  Then no new account is created and the visitor is offered sign-in and password reset instead\n\nScenario: Sign-up blocked for a non-compliant password\n  Given a visitor on the sign-up form\n  When they submit a password that fails the published password rules\n  Then no account is created and the failed rule is shown\n\nScenario: Returning viewer signs in\n  Given a registered viewer who is signed out\n  When they submit the correct email and password\n  Then they are signed in and their entitlements are available on that surface\n\nScenario: Sign-in rejected for wrong credentials\n  Given a registered viewer\n  When they submit an incorrect password\n  Then sign-in is refused with a generic error and no session is issued\n\nScenario: One account works across surfaces\n  Given a viewer who created an account on the web\n  When they sign in with the same credentials on a mobile app\n  Then the same account, purchases, and settings are available","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-02","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Apple sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to sign up or sign in with my Apple ID, so that I can start watching without creating another password."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (Decision Register, decision 8)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01"},{"label":"Surface scope","value":"native Apple sign-in is delivered on web, iOS, and Android only. TV surfaces (Roku, Fire TV, Samsung Tizen) reach Apple sign-in through the CAP-ID-05 activation page; no Apple sign-in SDK is integrated on TV platforms."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with an external identity provider (Apple) on three surfaces (web, iOS, Android); App Store policy requires Apple sign-in on iOS when other third-party sign-in is offered, so this gates iOS store certification (PLAT-IOS); account-linking rules add edge cases."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: First-time Apple sign-in creates an account\n  Given a visitor with no existing account\n  When they complete Apple sign-in on web, iOS, or Android and Apple returns a verified identity\n  Then an account is created keyed to that Apple identity and the viewer is signed in\n\nScenario: Returning Apple sign-in reaches the same account\n  Given a viewer whose account was created with Apple sign-in\n  When they complete Apple sign-in again on web, iOS, or Android\n  Then they are signed in to the same account with the same entitlements\n\nScenario: TV surfaces reach Apple sign-in via activation code\n  Given a signed-out TV app on Roku, Fire TV, or Samsung Tizen\n  When the viewer pairs the TV using the CAP-ID-05 activation page and signs in there with Apple\n  Then the TV is signed in to that Apple-keyed account with no Apple sign-in flow on the TV itself\n\nScenario: Apple private relay email is accepted\n  Given a visitor who chooses to hide their email during Apple sign-in\n  When Apple returns a private relay address\n  Then the account is created with the relay address and account emails route to it\n\nScenario: Apple email matches an existing email account\n  Given an existing email and password account for viewer@example.com\n  When a visitor completes Apple sign-in and Apple returns viewer@example.com\n  Then the two are linked to a single account only after the viewer confirms ownership (exact linking rule: Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Cancelled Apple sign-in leaves no trace\n  Given a visitor who starts Apple sign-in\n  When they cancel or Apple returns an error\n  Then no account is created and no session is issued","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-03","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Google sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to sign up or sign in with my Google account, so that I can start watching without creating another password."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (Decision Register, decision 8)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01"},{"label":"Surface scope","value":"native Google sign-in is delivered on web, iOS, and Android only. TV surfaces (Roku, Fire TV, Samsung Tizen) reach Google sign-in through the CAP-ID-05 activation page; no Google sign-in SDK is integrated on TV platforms."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with an external identity provider (Google) on three surfaces (web, iOS, Android); offering Google sign-in on iOS triggers the Apple sign-in requirement (see CAP-ID-02); account-linking rules shared with CAP-ID-02."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: First-time Google sign-in creates an account\n  Given a visitor with no existing account\n  When they complete Google sign-in on web, iOS, or Android and Google returns a verified identity\n  Then an account is created keyed to that Google identity and the viewer is signed in\n\nScenario: Returning Google sign-in reaches the same account\n  Given a viewer whose account was created with Google sign-in\n  When they complete Google sign-in again on web, iOS, or Android\n  Then they are signed in to the same account with the same entitlements\n\nScenario: TV surfaces reach Google sign-in via activation code\n  Given a signed-out TV app on Roku, Fire TV, or Samsung Tizen\n  When the viewer pairs the TV using the CAP-ID-05 activation page and signs in there with Google\n  Then the TV is signed in to that Google-keyed account with no Google sign-in flow on the TV itself\n\nScenario: Google email matches an existing email account\n  Given an existing email and password account for viewer@example.com\n  When a visitor completes Google sign-in and Google returns viewer@example.com\n  Then the two are linked to a single account only after the viewer confirms ownership (exact linking rule: Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Cancelled Google sign-in leaves no trace\n  Given a visitor who starts Google sign-in\n  When they cancel or Google returns an error\n  Then no account is created and no session is issued","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-04","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Password reset","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer who has forgotten my password, I want to reset it from a link sent to my email, so that I can get back into my account and my purchases."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 21:36)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01; transactional email delivery (external dependency)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with an email delivery service; low build complexity; reset volume spikes with the premiere login storm (CAP-INF load profile)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Reset link sent to a registered email\n  Given a registered email and password account\n  When the viewer requests a password reset for that email\n  Then a single-use, time-limited reset link is sent to that email\n\nScenario: Unregistered email gets no reset link\n  Given no account exists for the entered email\n  When a password reset is requested for it\n  Then the same on-screen confirmation is shown and no email is sent\n\nScenario: Successful reset\n  Given a viewer opens a valid reset link\n  When they set a new password that meets the password rules defined in CAP-ID-01\n  Then the password is updated and they can sign in with it immediately\n\nScenario: Expired or reused link rejected\n  Given a reset link that has expired or has already been used\n  When the viewer opens it\n  Then the reset is refused and a fresh reset can be requested\n\nScenario: Reset revokes existing sessions\n  Given a viewer with active sessions on more than one device\n  When they complete a password reset\n  Then all existing sessions are revoked and each device requires sign-in on next use (platform default owned by CAP-ID-06)\n\nScenario: Social-only account guided to the right sign-in\n  Given an account created only with Apple or Google sign-in\n  When a password reset is requested for its email\n  Then the email tells the viewer to sign in with Apple or Google instead of setting a password","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-05","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"TV activation-code device pairing","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer setting up a TV app, I want to sign the TV in by entering a short code on my phone or computer, so that I never have to type my password with a remote."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (Decision Register, decision 8); TV surfaces confirmed Jul 1 call (John, 42:39)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01, CAP-ID-02, CAP-ID-03 (any sign-in method usable on the pairing page, which runs on web and mobile), CAP-ID-06 (session issuance)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (code issuance, expiry, and pairing handshake); consumed by three TV platforms (PLAT-ROKU, PLAT-FTV, PLAT-SAM add platform-specific scenarios and reference these ACs); the only route to Apple and Google sign-in on TV surfaces (see CAP-ID-02 and CAP-ID-03); premiere-night activation surge (CAP-INF load profile)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: TV app displays an activation code\n  Given a signed-out TV app on any supported TV platform\n  When the viewer chooses to sign in\n  Then the TV displays a short activation code and the web address where it can be entered\n\nScenario: Code entry signs the TV in\n  Given a viewer signed in on the activation page on a phone or computer\n  When they enter the code currently shown on the TV\n  Then the TV is signed in to that viewer's account with no password entry on the TV\n\nScenario: Signed-out helper signs in first\n  Given a viewer who opens the activation page while signed out\n  When they enter a valid code\n  Then they complete any supported sign-in method first and the pairing then completes\n\nScenario: Expired code refused\n  Given an activation code older than the configured expiry (default 15 minutes, Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the viewer enters it\n  Then pairing is refused and the TV can request a fresh code\n\nScenario: Invalid code refused\n  Given a code that was never issued or has already been used\n  When it is entered on the activation page\n  Then pairing is refused and no session is created\n\nScenario: Paired TV appears in the device list\n  Given a TV signed in by activation code\n  When the viewer opens their device list in account settings\n  Then the TV is listed with its platform and last-used time","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-06","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Session and token management","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want sessions and tokens issued, refreshed, and revoked centrally for every surface, so that access behaves consistently everywhere and a revoked device loses access promptly."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (implied by decision 8 auth scope and decision 9 device registry); session and device registry supports the concurrent-screens check, Jul 1 call (John, 36:13); token lifetimes are Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01; consumed by CAP-PLAY (concurrent-screens check at playback start) and CAP-PAY (entitlement lookup)"},{"label":"Revocation default","value":"password reset revokes all existing sessions for the account (Assumption - client to confirm). This story owns that assumption; CAP-ID-04 references it."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build of a core shared service; every surface and every other epic depends on it; must hold at the 100K concurrent premiere profile including login storm, quit-and-return, and kicked-out re-entry (Jul 1 call, John, 35:09)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Session survives an app restart\n  Given a signed-in viewer on any surface\n  When they close and reopen the app or browser within the session lifetime\n  Then they remain signed in without re-entering credentials\n\nScenario: Tokens refresh silently\n  Given a signed-in session whose access token is near expiry\n  When the app presents a valid refresh token\n  Then a new access token is issued without interrupting the viewer\n\nScenario: Expired session prompts a clean re-entry\n  Given a session past its lifetime (lifetime defaults: Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the viewer next takes an action\n  Then they are asked to sign in again and are returned to a sensible resume point defined per PLAT epic\n\nScenario: Revocation takes effect promptly\n  Given a session revoked by device sign-out or by password reset (reset revocation per the default above)\n  When the revoked device next contacts the platform\n  Then the request is refused and the device is returned to the sign-in screen\n\nScenario: Sessions are countable per account\n  Given a viewer signed in on several devices\n  When the concurrent-screens check runs at playback start (enforced by CAP-PLAY)\n  Then the session registry returns an accurate list of that account's active sessions and devices","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-07","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Account self-service","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a signed-in viewer, I want to view my account details, change my password, and sign out of devices, so that I can manage my own access without contacting support."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (implied by decision 8 auth scope and decision 9 device registry); device sign-out supports the screens limit, Jul 1 call (John, 36:13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01, CAP-ID-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Mostly new build on top of the session registry; UI delivered per surface by the PLAT epics; low external dependency."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: View account\n  Given a signed-in viewer\n  When they open account settings\n  Then they see their email, their active sign-in methods, and their signed-in devices with platform and last-used time\n\nScenario: Change password\n  Given a signed-in viewer with an email and password account\n  When they enter their current password and a new password that meets the password rules defined in CAP-ID-01\n  Then the password is changed and a confirmation email is sent\n\nScenario: Wrong current password blocks the change\n  Given a signed-in viewer changing their password\n  When they enter an incorrect current password\n  Then the password is not changed\n\nScenario: Sign out of the current device\n  Given a signed-in viewer on any surface\n  When they choose sign out\n  Then the current session is revoked and the surface returns to the signed-out state\n\nScenario: Sign out of one device\n  Given a viewer with sessions on more than one device\n  When they sign out a specific device from account settings\n  Then that device's session is revoked, it requires sign-in on next use, and it no longer counts toward the concurrent-screens limit (limit enforced by CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Sign out everywhere\n  Given a signed-in viewer\n  When they choose to sign out of all devices\n  Then every session for the account is revoked, including the current one (Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-08","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Access continuity after session expiry on a paid account","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer who has paid for a film, I want my access to survive session expiry, sign-outs, and password resets, so that once I sign back in I can always watch what I own."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal and John, 25:59 to 26:12, permanent buy-to-own access) + Jul 1 call (John, 35:09, kicked-out-of-account case)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-06, CAP-PAY (entitlement records), CAP-PLAY (resume behaviour)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration between identity and entitlements rather than new build; edge cases concentrate at the premiere spike when payments and session churn peak (CAP-INF load profile)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitlements survive session expiry\n  Given a viewer who purchased a film and whose session has since expired\n  When they sign back in with any of their sign-in methods\n  Then the purchased film is still available to watch\n\nScenario: Kicked out mid-film, back in without loss\n  Given a viewer watching a purchased film whose session expires or is revoked during playback\n  When they sign back in\n  Then the film is playable again and resume position is honoured (resume behaviour defined in CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Purchase completes as the session lapses\n  Given a payment that completes successfully just as the viewer's session expires\n  When the viewer signs back in\n  Then the entitlement is attached to the account and the film is watchable, with no second charge\n\nScenario: Password reset never touches purchases\n  Given a viewer who completes a password reset\n  When they sign in with the new password\n  Then all previously purchased films remain available\n\nScenario: No inactivity forfeiture\n  Given a viewer who has not signed in for an extended period\n  When they sign back in\n  Then all purchased films remain available, with no expiry of purchased access","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-ID-09","epicId":"CAP-ID","doc":12,"title":"Account deletion request","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to request deletion of my account and personal data, so that I can exercise my privacy rights as a US consumer."},{"label":"Source","value":"App Store policy requires in-app account deletion for apps that offer account creation, so this story gates iOS store certification (PLAT-IOS). Wider US state privacy law obligations for a consumer service holding personal and payment-linked data: Assumption - client to confirm (not raised on either call)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID-01, CAP-PAY (payment record retention)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build with a data-handling policy dependency; certification gate for PLAT-IOS (in-app account deletion is required where account creation is offered); retention rules for payment and tax records are a client and legal decision, not a build decision."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Deletion is explained before it happens\n  Given a signed-in viewer on the account deletion screen\n  When they review the confirmation step\n  Then they are told deletion is permanent and that access to purchased films cannot be restored afterwards\n\nScenario: Deletion requires confirmation\n  Given a signed-in viewer requesting account deletion\n  When they re-authenticate and confirm the request\n  Then the request is accepted and confirmed on screen and by email\n\nScenario: Deleted account cannot sign in\n  Given a completed account deletion\n  When sign-in is attempted with any of the account's former sign-in methods\n  Then sign-in is refused\n\nScenario: Personal data removed, required records retained\n  Given a completed account deletion\n  When the platform processes the request\n  Then personal data is deleted or anonymised and only records required for payment and tax compliance are retained (retention rules: Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-01","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Stripe pay-per-view checkout","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to buy a film with a one-time Stripe payment using my card or a supported wallet, so that I can start watching immediately without a subscription."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02; John and Mishal, 25:59-26:12; free trial excluded per John, 37:09-37:14). Wallet rails limited to what Stripe checkout provides: Allion scoping decision."},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (signed-in account required), CAP-CON (per-title price configuration)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration, not new build (Stripe Checkout / Payment Element); purchase burst at premiere is a load factor (load profile owned by CAP-INF). Assumption - client to confirm: on mobile and TV storefronts where store billing policy prohibits Stripe checkout for digital goods, purchase is completed on the web surface and the entitlement syncs to the device (CAP-PAY-04); per-storefront policy rulings are an open question that affects both estimates."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Successful card purchase\n  Given a signed-in viewer in the US viewing a published film they do not own\n  When they complete Stripe checkout with a valid card\n  Then the payment is confirmed and an entitlement for that film is created\n  And the viewer can start playback immediately\n\nScenario: Successful wallet purchase\n  Given the viewer's surface supports a Stripe-provided wallet (for example Apple Pay or Google Pay)\n  When they complete checkout using that wallet\n  Then the payment is confirmed, an entitlement for that film is created, and the viewer can start playback immediately\n\nScenario: Price shown matches the configured price\n  Given the operator has set a price for the film in the content console\n  When the viewer opens checkout\n  Then the price displayed matches the configured price plus applicable tax (see CAP-PAY-08)\n\nScenario: No card data stored on the platform\n  Given a completed purchase\n  When platform data stores are inspected\n  Then no card number, CVC, or expiry data exists outside Stripe\n\nScenario: No free trial path\n  Given a viewer without an entitlement for a film\n  When they attempt to start playback\n  Then no trial or preview-access option is offered and playback requires a completed purchase\n\nScenario: Repeat purchase prevented\n  Given a viewer who already owns the film\n  When they open the film page\n  Then the purchase option is replaced by a watch action and no second charge can be made for that film","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-02","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Declined and failed payment handling with clear retry","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer whose payment fails, I want a clear explanation and an easy retry, so that a declined card does not end my purchase attempt."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 35:09, failed payments named as part of the premiere load profile; John, 37:46-39:04, \"pay and play always works\" success bar)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01"},{"label":"Scope note","value":"interrupted and unknown payment outcomes (crash, dropped connection, delayed result) are handled by CAP-PAY-05, not here."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (mapping Stripe decline codes to viewer-safe messages); decline volume at premiere spike is a load factor (CAP-INF)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Card declined\n  Given a viewer in Stripe checkout\n  When Stripe declines the payment\n  Then no entitlement is created and no access is granted\n  And the viewer sees a clear, non-technical message with a retry option\n\nScenario: Retry after a decline succeeds\n  Given a viewer whose previous attempt was declined\n  When they retry with a valid payment method\n  Then the purchase completes with exactly one charge and one entitlement\n\nScenario: Checkout cancelled by the viewer\n  Given a viewer in Stripe checkout\n  When they cancel or abandon checkout before paying\n  Then no charge is made, no entitlement is created, and they return to the film page\n\nScenario: Failure never grants access\n  Given any failed, declined, or cancelled payment\n  When the viewer attempts playback of the film\n  Then playback is refused","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-03","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Purchase confirmation and email receipt","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want an on-screen confirmation and an email receipt after buying a film, so that I have proof of purchase and confidence the payment went through."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (standard commerce behaviour supporting the Jul 1 \"pay and play always works\" bar; receipt delivery via Stripe's built-in receipt capability)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (Stripe receipt emails); low new build (confirmation screen per surface)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: On-screen confirmation\n  Given a viewer completes a purchase\n  When payment is confirmed\n  Then a confirmation is shown with the film title and amount paid, and a direct path to start watching\n\nScenario: Email receipt sent\n  Given a successful purchase\n  When the payment is confirmed\n  Then exactly one receipt email is sent to the account email address\n  And it shows the film title, purchase date, amount, and tax\n\nScenario: No receipt on failure\n  Given a declined or cancelled payment\n  When the attempt ends\n  Then no receipt email is sent","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-04","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Permanent buy-to-own entitlement record","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a purchased film to stay in my account permanently, so that I can watch it again at any time without rental windows or expiry."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal and John, 25:59-26:12, \"added to our library forever\", no rental model)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (access-rules portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01, CAP-ID (entitlement tied to the account across devices)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (entitlement service shared by every surface); data model must serve both one title (A) and hundreds of titles (B); read volume at playback start is a load factor."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Access is permanent\n  Given a viewer purchased a film\n  When they return at any later date and sign in\n  Then the film is still playable with no expiry applied\n\nScenario: No expiry data exists\n  Given any pay-per-view entitlement record\n  When the record is inspected\n  Then it carries no rental window or expiry date\n\nScenario: Entitlement works across devices\n  Given a viewer purchased a film on one surface (for example web)\n  When they sign in on any other supported surface (for example a TV app)\n  Then the entitlement is recognised and the film is playable there\n\nScenario: Owned state is visible\n  Given a viewer who owns a film\n  When they view that film's page\n  Then it shows a purchased state and a watch action instead of a purchase action\n\nScenario: No entitlement means no playback\n  Given a signed-in viewer without an entitlement for a film\n  When they attempt to start playback\n  Then playback is refused and the purchase path is offered\n\nScenario: Unpublished title remains playable for owners (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a viewer owns a film that the operator later unpublishes from the catalog\n  When the viewer opens their purchased film\n  Then playback still works for that owner","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-05","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Purchase recovery after crash or interruption","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer whose app crashed or connection dropped right after paying, I want my purchase to be honoured when I come back, so that I am never charged without getting the film."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 35:09, quit-the-app and kicked-out cases named in the load profile; John, 37:46-39:04, no user story hits a wall). Server-side confirmation as source of truth: Allion scoping decision."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01, CAP-PAY-04"},{"label":"Scope note","value":"this story owns all reconciliation of interrupted and unknown payment outcomes; CAP-PAY-02 covers only declines, failures, and cancellations with a known result."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (webhook-driven entitlement creation, idempotency, pending-state UX); external dependency on Stripe event delivery; premiere-scale event volume."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitlement survives an app crash\n  Given a viewer's payment succeeded but the app closed before confirmation was shown\n  When the viewer reopens the app and signs in\n  Then the entitlement is present, the film is playable, and no second charge exists\n\nScenario: Server record created without client acknowledgement\n  Given Stripe confirms a payment\n  When the viewer's device never acknowledges the result\n  Then the entitlement is still created from the server-side Stripe confirmation\n\nScenario: Duplicate events create one entitlement\n  Given Stripe delivers the same payment event more than once\n  When the events are processed\n  Then exactly one entitlement and one charge exist for that purchase\n\nScenario: Pending state is visible and resolves\n  Given a payment whose outcome is briefly delayed\n  When the viewer views the film page\n  Then a clear pending-payment state is shown\n  And the final state appears within the assumed payment-confirm target of 10 seconds (Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-06","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"US-only geo gate at purchase and at playback start","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want purchase and playback restricted to viewers in the US by geo-IP, so that the service matches its US-only launch scope."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Asiri, 16:00; John, 18:20, \"let's stick to the US\"). Gate at both purchase and playback start, geo-IP only, no VPN countermeasures: Allion scoping decision."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01 (purchase gate), CAP-PLAY (playback-start hook)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (geo-IP lookup service); the check sits on the playback-start hot path at 100K concurrent, so lookup latency matters."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Purchase allowed from a US location\n  Given a viewer whose IP resolves to a US location\n  When they start checkout\n  Then the purchase proceeds normally\n\nScenario: Purchase blocked outside the US\n  Given a viewer whose IP resolves to a non-US location\n  When they attempt checkout\n  Then the purchase is blocked and a clear message states the service is available in the US only\n\nScenario: Playback blocked outside the US even with a valid entitlement\n  Given a viewer who owns a film but whose IP currently resolves to a non-US location\n  When they attempt to start playback\n  Then playback is refused with a clear US-only message\n\nScenario: Geo check runs at every playback start\n  Given any playback attempt\n  When the session is requested\n  Then the geo-IP check is evaluated before the stream is served\n\nScenario: No VPN countermeasures\n  Given a viewer whose IP resolves to a US location via a VPN\n  When they purchase or play\n  Then they are treated as a US viewer and no additional circumvention checks are applied","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-07","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Concurrent-screens limit at playback start","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want a configurable per-account limit on simultaneous streams, enforced as a simple pass/fail check at playback start, so that casual account sharing is deterred without heavy anti-circumvention build."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 36:13, configurable limit, pass/fail only, deter casual sharing). Default value of 2: Allion scoping default; final value is a client decision. Session-timeout default of 2 minutes: Assumption - client to confirm."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-04 (account entitlements), CAP-PLAY (playback session lifecycle)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (active-session tracking and release across all surfaces); accuracy of session release (stop, crash, timeout) drives viewer experience; check sits on the playback-start hot path at premiere scale. Excluded by design: device deregistration, fingerprinting, and any anti-circumvention mechanisms (pass/fail check only, per the Jul 1 call)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Stream starts under the limit\n  Given an account with the limit set to 2 and one active stream\n  When a second device starts playback\n  Then playback starts normally\n\nScenario: Stream blocked at the limit\n  Given an account with the limit set to 2 and two active streams\n  When a third device attempts playback\n  Then playback is refused with a clear message stating the screen limit has been reached\n\nScenario: Slot frees when a stream stops\n  Given an account at its screen limit\n  When one active stream is stopped by the viewer\n  Then a new device can start playback\n\nScenario: Abandoned session times out and frees the slot\n  Given an account at its screen limit and one stream that has stopped sending playback heartbeats (for example after a device crash or network loss)\n  When the configurable session timeout elapses (default 2 minutes, Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Then that session is released and a new device can start playback\n\nScenario: Limit is configurable without a code change\n  Given the screen-limit or session-timeout value is changed in configuration\n  When the next playback attempt is evaluated\n  Then the new value is enforced without a redeploy\n\nScenario: Default value applies\n  Given no custom value has been set\n  When the limit is evaluated\n  Then the default of 2 applies (final value: client to confirm)","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-08","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"US sales tax via Stripe Tax","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want US sales tax calculated and collected through Stripe Tax at checkout, so that purchases are tax-compliant without building a tax engine."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (register decision: US sales tax via Stripe Tax carried as an assumption)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration only (Stripe Tax on the existing checkout); tax registration and remittance setup are client-side business tasks, not platform build."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Tax calculated at checkout\n  Given a viewer in a US state where tax applies\n  When they reach checkout\n  Then Stripe Tax calculates the applicable sales tax for their location\n\nScenario: Total shown before payment\n  Given tax has been calculated\n  When the viewer confirms payment\n  Then the total including tax was displayed before the charge was made\n\nScenario: Receipt itemises tax\n  Given a completed purchase with tax applied\n  When the receipt is issued\n  Then the tax amount appears as a separate line","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["assumption","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-09","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":12,"title":"Refunds and chargebacks operated through the Stripe dashboard","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want refunds and chargebacks handled in the Stripe dashboard with the platform reacting to the outcome, so that no in-app refund tooling is built for V1."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (register carries refund/chargeback handling via Stripe dashboard, no in-app refund build, as an assumption). Entitlement revocation on refund: Assumption - client to confirm."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-04, CAP-PAY-05 (shared Stripe event handling)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (refund and dispute webhooks feeding entitlement updates); no viewer-facing UI build; low volume expected but events must be processed reliably."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Refund revokes the entitlement (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a purchase refunded in the Stripe dashboard\n  When the refund event is received\n  Then the film's entitlement is revoked and the film is no longer playable for that account\n\nScenario: Chargeback revokes the entitlement (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a chargeback is raised on a purchase\n  When the dispute event is received\n  Then the entitlement is revoked and the event is recorded against the account\n\nScenario: No self-serve refund in the app\n  Given any viewer surface\n  When a viewer looks for a refund option\n  Then no in-app refund flow exists; refund requests are handled outside the app\n\nScenario: Refund events processed once\n  Given the same refund event is delivered more than once\n  When the events are processed\n  Then the entitlement state changes exactly once","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-01","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Stream start with entitlement and policy checks","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want playback to start only after the platform confirms my access, so that paid content stays protected and my own purchase always plays."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 37:46-39:04, \"if somebody wants to watch it and they want to pay us, we better take their money and play them the film\"); Jul 1 call (John, 36:13, screen limit); Jun 22 call (US-only scope)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (authenticated session), CAP-PAY (entitlement record and screen-limit rule), CAP-DRM (license issuance), CAP-PIPE (stream URL issuance)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the managed platform's token or signed-URL mechanism, not new build; check sequencing (entitlement, geo, screen limit) must complete in a single start call; must hold at the 100K concurrent start surge defined in the premiere load profile"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitled viewer starts a stream\n  Given a signed-in viewer with a valid entitlement for a title\n  When the viewer starts playback\n  Then the stream starts and a playback session is created\n\nScenario: Viewer without entitlement is blocked\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no entitlement for a title\n  When the viewer attempts to start playback\n  Then no stream manifest or license is issued\n  And the viewer is routed to the purchase path\n\nScenario: Signed-out viewer is blocked\n  Given a viewer who is not signed in\n  When the viewer attempts to start playback\n  Then playback does not start and the viewer is prompted to sign in\n\nScenario: All checks complete before the stream is served\n  Given any playback start request\n  When the request is processed\n  Then the entitlement check, US geo-IP check, and screen-limit check all pass before the manifest and license are released\n\nScenario: Screen limit enforced as pass or fail at start\n  Given an account already streaming on its configured screen limit (default 2, assumption, client to confirm)\n  When an additional device on the same account requests playback\n  Then the new playback request is refused at start\n  And streams already in progress are not interrupted","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-02","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Adaptive bitrate ladder with automatic step-down","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the film to play at the best quality my device and network support, so that viewing stays smooth without me managing settings."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 7:39 and 23:34, 4K supported, majority delivery 1080p, network step-down; unchallenged by John); Jun 22 call (Craig, 4K target); step-up on network recovery is standard adaptive behavior, Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE (ladder renditions produced by the managed platform)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Managed-platform configuration and verification rather than new build; five-tier ladder verified end to end; 4K support on the managed platform is confirmed by the CAP-PIPE validation spike"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Full ladder available for a published title\n  Given a published title\n  When the player requests the rendition manifest\n  Then the manifest contains 4K, 1080p, 720p, 480p, and SD tiers\n\nScenario: 4K playback on a capable device and network\n  Given an entitled viewer on a 4K-capable device with sufficient network throughput\n  When playback runs\n  Then the player serves the 4K rendition\n\nScenario: Automatic step-down on network degradation\n  Given a viewer streaming at a higher rendition\n  When network throughput drops below that rendition's requirement\n  Then the player switches to a lower rendition automatically\n  And playback continues without stopping or viewer action\n\nScenario: Automatic step-up on network recovery\n  Given a viewer streaming at a reduced rendition\n  When network throughput recovers\n  Then the player returns to a higher rendition automatically\n\nScenario: Constrained network still plays\n  Given a viewer whose network supports only the lowest tier\n  When playback runs\n  Then the stream continues at the SD rendition rather than failing","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-03","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Core player controls","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want standard player controls, so that I can control the viewing session on any surface."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 35:09, \"play, play back, pause, rewind 15 seconds\"); forward-15s skip added as Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-01 (active playback session)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Capability defined once, verified per platform in PLAT epics; trick-play actions are part of the 100K concurrent premiere load profile, so control events must be cheap server-side"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Play and pause\n  Given a viewer with an active playback session\n  When the viewer pauses and then resumes\n  Then playback halts and restarts at the same position\n\nScenario: Seek to a position\n  Given a viewer with an active playback session\n  When the viewer seeks to any point in the title\n  Then playback continues from the selected position\n\nScenario: Skip back 15 seconds\n  Given a viewer with an active playback session\n  When the viewer triggers rewind\n  Then the position moves back exactly 15 seconds, or to 0:00 if less than 15 seconds in\n\nScenario: Skip forward 15 seconds\n  Given a viewer with an active playback session\n  When the viewer triggers forward skip\n  Then the position moves forward exactly 15 seconds, and never past the end of the title\n\nScenario: Volume and mute\n  Given a viewer with an active playback session\n  When the viewer adjusts volume or toggles mute\n  Then audio output changes accordingly without interrupting playback","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-04","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Caption and subtitle track selection including SDH","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to choose subtitle and caption tracks, including SDH, so that I can watch in my preferred language and with accessibility support."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 24:54, match the language coverage of an Apple TV Plus new release); Allion scoping decision (operator-supplied subtitle files, no auto-generation, SDH support)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (operator upload of multi-language subtitle files per title), CAP-PIPE (track packaging into the stream)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Track volume benchmark of roughly 30-40 languages per title; sync verification across the ladder; per-platform caption rendering handled in PLAT epics"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Available tracks are listed\n  Given a title with operator-uploaded subtitle files in multiple languages\n  When the viewer opens the caption selector during playback\n  Then every uploaded language track is listed by language name\n\nScenario: Selected track displays in sync\n  Given a viewer has selected a subtitle track\n  When playback runs\n  Then subtitles in the selected language display in sync with the dialogue\n\nScenario: SDH track is selectable\n  Given a title with an SDH file uploaded\n  When the viewer opens the caption selector\n  Then the SDH track is listed and labelled as SDH, and displays when selected\n\nScenario: Captions off\n  Given a viewer with a subtitle track active\n  When the viewer selects off\n  Then no subtitles display for the rest of the session\n\nScenario: Caption preference persists (assumption, client to confirm)\n  Given a viewer who selected a subtitle language in a previous session\n  When the viewer starts a new playback on the same account\n  Then the same language track is pre-selected","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-05","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Resume points saved and honored across devices","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to leave a film partway through and pick it up where I stopped on any of my devices, so that I can finish it later."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"pay for a film and then to watch it and maybe pause it and watch it later and finish later\"); cross-device behavior is a Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-06 (heartbeat supplies position), CAP-ID (account-level storage)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; position write volume at 100K concurrent; simple conflict rule needed when two devices report positions (latest heartbeat wins)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Resume on the same device\n  Given a viewer who exited a film partway through\n  When the viewer reopens the same title on the same device\n  Then playback offers to resume within one heartbeat interval of the exit position\n\nScenario: Resume on a different device\n  Given a viewer who exited a film partway through on device A\n  When the viewer opens the same title on device B under the same account\n  Then playback offers to resume within one heartbeat interval of the exit position\n\nScenario: Start over remains available\n  Given a viewer with a saved resume point for a title\n  When the viewer chooses to start from the beginning\n  Then playback starts at 0:00 and the resume point is replaced as viewing progresses\n\nScenario: Completed title restarts from the beginning\n  Given a viewer who watched a title to the end\n  When the viewer plays that title again\n  Then playback starts from the beginning with no resume prompt\n\nScenario: Resume point updates during viewing\n  Given a viewer watching a title\n  When each heartbeat is recorded\n  Then the stored resume point reflects the most recently reported position","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-06","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Playback session heartbeat","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want every active playback session to report a periodic heartbeat, so that metering, resume points, and the screen-limit check all have reliable session data."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, unit economics need per-stream data; John, 36:13, screen limit); Allion scoping decision (heartbeat design)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-01 (session creation), CAP-MET (consumes session and duration data), CAP-PAY (screen-limit check consumes active-session count)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; heartbeat fan-in at 100K concurrent sessions; interval choice trades freshness against cost; ungraceful exits (app killed, network loss) must be detected by timeout"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Heartbeat starts with the session\n  Given a playback session starts\n  When the first heartbeat is sent\n  Then it carries account ID, title ID, session ID, playback position, and timestamp\n\nScenario: Heartbeat repeats on a configurable interval\n  Given an active playback session\n  When playback continues\n  Then heartbeats are sent on the configured interval (default 60 seconds, assumption, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Graceful stop ends the session\n  Given an active playback session\n  When the viewer stops playback or exits the player\n  Then the session is marked ended with its final position\n\nScenario: Ungraceful exit times out\n  Given an active playback session\n  When the configured number of consecutive heartbeats is missed (default 3 missed heartbeats, assumption, client to confirm)\n  Then the session is marked ended\n  And the account's active-session count for the screen-limit check is reduced\n\nScenario: Active-session count is queryable\n  Given an account with one or more active sessions\n  When the screen-limit check runs at a new playback start\n  Then it receives the current active-session count for that account\n\nScenario: Session data reaches metering\n  Given a completed playback session\n  When CAP-MET queries session records\n  Then the session's title, account, start time, end time, and watched duration are available","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-07","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Graceful playback error states","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a clear message when a stream cannot start or fails, so that I know what happened and what to do next."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 37:46-39:04, no user story hits a wall); Jul 1 call (John, 36:13, screen limit); Jun 22 call (US-only scope); message wording is a Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-01 (start checks), CAP-PAY (purchase path for missing entitlement)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Error copy shared across platforms with per-platform rendering in PLAT epics; failure paths (kicked-out and failed cases) are part of the 100K concurrent premiere load profile"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitlement missing\n  Given a signed-in viewer without an entitlement for a title\n  When they attempt playback\n  Then a message explains the title is not yet purchased and offers the purchase path\n\nScenario: Geo-blocked\n  Given a viewer connecting from a non-US IP address\n  When they attempt playback\n  Then no stream is served and a message states the service is available in the US only\n\nScenario: Screen limit reached\n  Given an account already at its concurrent-screen limit\n  When another device attempts playback\n  Then a message states the screen limit has been reached and playback does not start\n\nScenario: Stream unavailable at start\n  Given the video platform cannot serve a stream\n  When a viewer attempts playback\n  Then a retry message is shown within the configured start timeout (default 10 seconds, assumed target, client to confirm) rather than an indefinite loading state\n\nScenario: Mid-playback failure\n  Given a viewer watching a title\n  When the stream fails and automatic recovery does not succeed\n  Then an error message is shown and the resume point is saved at the last reported position\n\nScenario: No technical detail exposed\n  Given any playback error state\n  When the message is displayed\n  Then it contains plain-language guidance and no raw error codes or technical traces","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-08","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":12,"title":"Playback quality-of-experience targets","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want playback measured against defined quality-of-experience targets, so that the premiere-scale viewing experience is objectively verifiable before launch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (all target values are Allion-proposed, not client-set)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-06 (session data), CAP-MET (measurement), CAP-INF (premiere load profile execution)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Measurement tooling on top of the managed platform's analytics; targets are configurable assumed values pending client confirmation; verification at 100K concurrent runs inside the CAP-INF stress-test window (months 4-5)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Video start time (assumed target)\n  Given the premiere load profile is running\n  When start times are measured across sessions\n  Then video start time is under 4 seconds (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Rebuffer ratio (assumed target)\n  Given the premiere load profile is running\n  When rebuffering is measured across sessions\n  Then the rebuffer ratio is under 1% of watch time (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Playback error rate at peak (assumed target)\n  Given the premiere load profile is running at peak concurrency\n  When playback errors are measured\n  Then the playback error rate is under 0.5% of sessions (assumed target, client to confirm)","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-01","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Multi-DRM packaging and encryption via the managed platform","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want every title encrypted and packaged for multi-DRM (Widevine, FairPlay, PlayReady) by the managed video platform, so that film streams cannot be played outside a licensed player session on any of the six client platforms."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 16:49) + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE (managed platform integration and validation spike), CAP-CON (title ingest)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with managed platform DRM, not a new build; external dependency on the platform's multi-DRM support (confirmed by the CAP-PIPE validation spike); platform multiplier (licenses are consumed on all six client platforms; platform-specific DRM variant scenarios live in the PLAT epics)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Title is encrypted during packaging\n  Given a film master has been ingested into the managed platform\n  When the platform packages the title for streaming\n  Then every rendition in the adaptive ladder (4K down to SD) is encrypted\n  And segment files fetched directly from the CDN are not playable without a license\n\nScenario: All three DRM systems can license the same title\n  Given a packaged title\n  When license requests are made for Widevine, FairPlay, and PlayReady\n  Then each DRM system issues a valid license for that title\n\nScenario: Playback without a license fails\n  Given a stream manifest URL for a protected title\n  When a player attempts playback without obtaining a license\n  Then the content does not decrypt and playback does not start\n\nScenario: Packaging status is exposed for publish control\n  Given a title whose DRM packaging has failed or has not completed\n  When the console queries the title's protection status\n  Then the packaging status (in progress, failed, complete) is reported accurately\n  And the block on publishing unprotected titles is enforced by the owning CAP-CON publish story, which consumes this status","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-02","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Entitlement-gated license delivery at playback start","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer who has paid for a film, I want my player to obtain the DRM license automatically when I press play, so that the film starts with no extra steps while anyone without a valid purchase is refused."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 16:49 and 37:46) + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-01, CAP-PAY (entitlement check), CAP-ID (authenticated session), CAP-PLAY (player integration and the playback-start geo gate story)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration between the platform's license issuance and our entitlement service (the main custom piece in an otherwise managed flow); external dependency on the platform license API; platform multiplier for player-side license handling on six platforms"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitled viewer receives a license silently\n  Given a signed-in viewer with a valid entitlement for a film\n  When the viewer starts playback\n  Then a DRM license is issued for that title and playback begins\n  And the viewer takes no additional action to obtain the license\n\nScenario: Entitlement is permanent\n  Given a viewer who purchased a film at any time in the past\n  When the viewer starts playback\n  Then a license is issued and playback begins\n  And no rental window or entitlement expiry is applied (purchases are buy-to-own with permanent access)\n\nScenario: Viewer without entitlement is refused\n  Given a signed-in viewer who has not purchased the film\n  When the player requests a license for that title\n  Then the license request is refused\n  And playback does not start\n  And the viewer sees a clear prompt to purchase the film\n\nScenario: Invalid or expired session is refused\n  Given a license request carrying an expired or invalid authentication session\n  When the license service evaluates the request\n  Then no license is issued\n\nScenario: License is scoped to the requested title\n  Given a license issued for one title\n  When the same license is presented against a different title\n  Then the other title does not decrypt\n\nScenario: License issuance honors the playback-start geo decision\n  Given a playback request that the CAP-PLAY playback-start geo gate story has cleared for US playback\n  When the player requests a license\n  Then license evaluation proceeds on entitlement and session validity only\n  And geo enforcement itself is owned by the CAP-PLAY playback-start geo gate story, not duplicated here","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-03","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"License service under the premiere load profile","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want license issuance to hold up under the 100,000 concurrent premiere profile, so that DRM never blocks a paying viewer at the moment of highest demand."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16 and 35:09); applying the 100,000 concurrent bar to Option B = Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-02, CAP-INF (surge protection and the pre-launch premiere stress-testing window, which includes license traffic), CAP-PIPE (validation spike confirms platform license capacity)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on managed platform license service capacity; volume factor (100K concurrent license requests inside a short premiere window); retry and error handling under load"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: License issuance holds at premiere start surge\n  Given the premiere load test simulating 100,000 concurrent viewers starting playback\n  When the simulated journeys request licenses\n  Then license issuance stays within the assumed peak error rate target (below 0.5 percent, assumed, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Pause, quit, and resume storm re-licenses correctly\n  Given viewers pausing, quitting the app, and resuming during the premiere surge\n  When their players re-request licenses on resume\n  Then licenses are reissued for entitled viewers without wrongly blocking any of them\n\nScenario: Player degrades gracefully when the license service struggles\n  Given the license service is responding slowly or returning errors\n  When a player's license request fails\n  Then the player retries automatically\n  And the viewer sees a readable message rather than a crash\n\nScenario: Every simulated premiere journey exercises licensing\n  Given the full-journey premiere load test\n  When the test executes\n  Then every simulated playback journey includes a license request\n  And per-request license results are logged for analysis","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-04","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Playback quality tied to device DRM security level","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want stream quality caps tied to each device's DRM security level, so that 4K and HD renditions are only released to devices that meet the corresponding protection level."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (standard multi-DRM practice, extends the confirmed 4K adaptive ladder and multi-DRM scope)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-01, CAP-DRM-02, CAP-PLAY (adaptive ladder)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Configuration on the managed platform rather than new build; platform multiplier (security levels differ by device family); interacts with the 4K-to-SD adaptive ladder"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Hardware-backed device receives up to 4K\n  Given a device reporting a hardware-backed DRM security level\n  When an entitled viewer starts playback\n  Then renditions up to 4K are available to the player\n\nScenario: Software-only device is capped but still plays\n  Given a device reporting a software-only DRM security level\n  When an entitled viewer starts playback\n  Then playback starts at the capped quality for that level\n  And the viewer sees no error (playback proceeds at the capped quality)\n\nScenario: Security-level mapping is configuration, not code\n  Given the platform's default mapping of security levels to quality caps\n  When the mapping is reviewed\n  Then it is documented and adjustable as configuration without a code change","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-05","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Standard output protection (HDCP) as platform default","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the managed platform's standard HDCP output protection enforced on external video outputs, so that casual capture over HDMI is deterred without custom build work."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (managed platform default, supporting the anti-piracy priority from the Jul 1 call, John, 16:49)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-01, CAP-DRM-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Platform default configuration, no new build; per-device output behavior differences (platform multiplier); deliberately no hardening beyond the platform default"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Compliant output plays at full entitled quality\n  Given a device connected to an HDCP-compliant display\n  When an entitled viewer plays a film\n  Then playback runs at the full quality the device and entitlement allow\n\nScenario: Non-compliant output matches the documented default policy\n  Given the platform's default HDCP policy for each DRM system and device platform is documented before testing\n  And a device outputting to a display that does not satisfy the HDCP requirement\n  When the viewer attempts playback\n  Then the observed behavior matches the documented default policy for that DRM system and platform\n  And where playback is blocked the viewer sees a readable explanation\n\nScenario: No custom hardening beyond the default\n  Given the output protection configuration for the platform\n  When it is reviewed\n  Then only the managed platform's default settings are in use\n  And no custom anti-circumvention development is in scope","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-06","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Forensic session watermarking","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want each playback session's video carrying a session-level forensic watermark, so that a leaked copy can be traced to the session that produced it and piracy is deterred."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 16:44, watermarking system referenced; John, 16:49, anti-piracy very important); exact watermarking technology and vendor = Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE (validation spike confirms platform watermark support), CAP-DRM-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (watermarking is a platform or vendor capability, to be confirmed by the CAP-PIPE spike); volume factor (per-session marking at premiere scale); verification effort for imperceptibility and robustness"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Each session carries a unique mark\n  Given two different playback sessions of the same title\n  When output captured from each session is analyzed\n  Then the extracted identifiers differ and each resolves to its own session\n\nScenario: Watermark is imperceptible in normal viewing\n  Given a watermarked stream and its unmarked reference\n  When both are compared in a standard visual QA check\n  Then no visible artifacts attributable to the watermark are observed\n\nScenario: Watermarking does not delay playback start\n  Given a watermarked playback session\n  When the viewer starts a film\n  Then video start time stays within the assumed QoE target (below 4 seconds, assumed, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Mark survives re-encoding\n  Given a re-encoded copy of a watermarked stream\n  When watermark extraction runs on the copy\n  Then the session identifier is still recoverable (robustness bar set at technology selection, assumed, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Mark survives screen capture\n  Given a screen-captured copy of a watermarked stream\n  When watermark extraction runs on the copy\n  Then the session identifier is still recoverable (robustness bar set at technology selection, assumed, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Watermarking holds at premiere scale\n  Given the 100,000 concurrent premiere load test with watermarking active on every session\n  When the test executes\n  Then watermarking does not push playback errors above the assumed peak error rate target","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-07","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":12,"title":"Leak-trace investigation workflow","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want a documented workflow to extract the watermark from a pirated copy and resolve it to an account and session, so that anti-piracy follow-up is possible after launch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (follows from the Jul 1 anti-piracy priority, John, 16:49)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-06, CAP-MET (playback session records)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Mostly process plus vendor tooling, small build; depends on session records retained by CAP-MET; investigation is manual and on request (no automated piracy monitoring in scope)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Extraction identifies the originating session\n  Given a leaked video sample meeting the minimum extraction length for the chosen watermarking technology (minimum length set at technology selection, assumed, client to confirm)\n  When the extraction tooling runs on the sample\n  Then it returns the session identifier embedded in that sample\n\nScenario: Session identifier resolves to an account\n  Given an extracted session identifier\n  When it is looked up against the playback session records\n  Then the lookup returns the account, title, and playback timestamp for that session\n\nScenario: The workflow is documented and repeatable\n  Given the leak-trace investigation workflow\n  When it is reviewed before launch\n  Then a step-by-step runbook exists covering sample intake, extraction, lookup, and result recording","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-01","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Operator console login","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to sign in to the content console with provisioned credentials, so that only the internal team can manage the catalog."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (John, 35:13-36:28, single internal team does all content uploads, no multi-user admin levels)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-01"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"None"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (console shell plus operator authentication); no role model needed (single user); session handling only; operator credential recovery is handled by internal re-provisioning (no self-service reset), deliberately included in this story's estimate"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Successful sign in\n  Given a provisioned operator account exists\n  When the operator signs in with the correct email and password\n  Then the console dashboard is displayed\n\nScenario: Rejected sign in\n  Given a provisioned operator account exists\n  When the operator enters an incorrect password\n  Then access is denied and a non-specific error message is shown\n\nScenario: No self-service registration\n  Given a visitor reaches the console sign-in page\n  When they look for a sign-up option\n  Then no self-service account creation is available (accounts are provisioned internally)\n\nScenario: No self-service password reset\n  Given a visitor reaches the console sign-in page\n  When they look for a password reset option\n  Then no self-service reset is offered (operator credentials are re-provisioned internally)\n\nScenario: Expired session requires re-authentication\n  Given an operator session has passed its expiry window\n  When the operator performs any console action\n  Then they are returned to the sign-in page and no action is executed","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-02","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Create title draft","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to create a new title in draft state, so that I can prepare its assets before anything is visible to viewers."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, operator uploads and manages films before publish) + Allion scoping decision (explicit draft state)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; simple state model (draft, published, unpublished); foundation record every other console story attaches to"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Create a draft title\n  Given the operator is signed in\n  When they create a new title with a working name\n  Then a title record is created in draft state\n\nScenario: Draft is invisible to viewers\n  Given a title exists in draft state\n  When a viewer loads any catalog or detail surface\n  Then the draft title does not appear and cannot be purchased\n\nScenario: Draft appears in the console title list\n  Given one or more titles exist in any state\n  When the operator opens the title list\n  Then every title is listed with its current state (draft, published, unpublished)\n\nScenario: Draft is editable\n  Given a title exists in draft state\n  When the operator changes its working name\n  Then the change is saved and shown in the title list","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-03","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Upload film master","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to upload a film master file for a title, so that the managed video platform can prepare it for adaptive streaming."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, upload the film master and transcode for streaming; John, 15:48, managed third-party pipeline chosen for build time)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-02"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-02, CAP-PIPE (managed pipeline integration)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with managed video platform ingest API (external dependency); large-file handling for multi-GB 4K masters; upload reliability"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Upload a master file\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator uploads a supported master file\n  Then the file is handed to the managed video platform and encoding begins\n\nScenario: Upload progress is visible\n  Given a master upload is in progress\n  When the operator views the title\n  Then upload progress is displayed until hand-off completes\n\nScenario: Unsupported file is rejected\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator uploads a file in an unsupported format\n  Then the upload is rejected with a readable reason and the title is unchanged\n\nScenario: Interrupted upload does not corrupt the title\n  Given a master upload is interrupted before completion\n  When the operator retries the upload\n  Then the retry succeeds without leaving a partial or duplicate master on the title\n\nScenario: Replace a master before publish\n  Given a draft title already has a processed master\n  When the operator uploads a replacement master\n  Then the new master supersedes the old one after processing completes","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-04","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Encoding status visibility","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to see each title's encoding status (in progress, ready, failed), so that I know when a title is safe to publish."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, transcoding may take time so the operator needs to see its status)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-02"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-03, CAP-PIPE (status reported by the managed platform)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (polling or webhook consumption from the managed platform); status mapping to three console states"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: In-progress status shown\n  Given a master has been handed to the managed platform\n  When encoding has not yet completed\n  Then the title shows a status of in progress\n\nScenario: Ready status shown\n  Given encoding for a title completes successfully\n  When the operator views the title list or the title detail\n  Then the title shows a status of ready\n\nScenario: Failed status shows a reason\n  Given encoding for a title fails\n  When the operator views the title\n  Then the title shows a status of failed with a readable reason\n\nScenario: A failed encode does not block other titles\n  Given one title has a failed encode\n  When other titles are uploaded and encoded\n  Then those titles progress to ready independently","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-05","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Metadata entry","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to enter a title's name, description, category, and credits, so that viewers see accurate film information."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, upload metadata alongside the film)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-03"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-02"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build, simple forms; category values feed genre browse in Option B (B-DISC), so the category field must be structured, not free text; category list is a simple operator-managed list in the console (managed-list approach is an Assumption - client to confirm)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Save metadata on a draft\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator enters name, description, category, and credits and saves\n  Then all four fields are stored and redisplayed on reload\n\nScenario: Category is a structured value\n  Given the operator is editing a title\n  When they set the category\n  Then the value comes from a managed category list, not free text\n\nScenario: Operator manages the category list\n  Given the operator is signed in\n  When they add or rename a category in the console category list\n  Then the updated list is available when setting any title's category (simple operator-managed list is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Missing required fields are flagged\n  Given a draft title is missing any required metadata field (required set: name, description, and category; credits are optional; required set is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the operator views the title\n  Then each missing required field is clearly indicated as required before publish\n\nScenario: Edit metadata after publish\n  Given a published title\n  When the operator edits its description and saves\n  Then the updated description is reflected on viewer surfaces","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-06","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Artwork upload","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to upload a thumbnail and a poster for each title, so that the title displays correctly on catalog and detail surfaces."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, upload artwork so the film shows up correctly for viewers)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-03"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-02"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; image validation (format, dimensions); artwork must serve every client surface (web, mobile, TV), so size rules matter"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Upload thumbnail and poster\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator uploads a thumbnail image and a poster image\n  Then both are stored against the title and previewed in the console\n\nScenario: Invalid image rejected\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator uploads an image that fails format or dimension rules\n  Then the upload is rejected with a readable reason\n\nScenario: Replace artwork\n  Given a title already has a poster\n  When the operator uploads a new poster\n  Then the new poster replaces the old one on all surfaces\n\nScenario: Artwork required before publish\n  Given a title is missing its thumbnail or poster\n  When the operator views the title\n  Then the missing artwork is indicated as required before publish","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-07","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Multi-language subtitle upload","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to upload subtitle files in multiple languages per title, so that viewers can watch with captions in their language."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 24:54, support as many subtitle languages as an Apple TV Plus new release) + Allion scoping decision (operator-uploaded files, no auto-generation; benchmark is roughly 30-40 languages per title)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-02, CAP-PLAY (caption selection and SDH display in the player)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Volume factor (tens of language tracks per title); subtitle format validation; sidecar handling through the managed platform"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Upload a subtitle file with a language tag\n  Given a draft or published title exists\n  When the operator uploads a supported subtitle file and selects its language\n  Then the track is stored against the title with that language label\n\nScenario: Many languages on one title\n  Given a title already has subtitle tracks in several languages\n  When the operator uploads additional language tracks up to the benchmark count (roughly 30-40)\n  Then all tracks are listed against the title with no loss or overwrite\n\nScenario: Mark a track as SDH\n  Given the operator is uploading a subtitle track\n  When they flag the track as SDH (subtitles for the deaf and hard of hearing)\n  Then the track is labelled SDH and exposed to the player as such\n\nScenario: Replace a language track\n  Given a title has a subtitle track for a given language\n  When the operator uploads a corrected file for the same language\n  Then the new file replaces the old one for that language\n\nScenario: Invalid subtitle file rejected\n  Given a title exists\n  When the operator uploads a file that fails subtitle format validation\n  Then the upload is rejected with a readable reason and existing tracks are unaffected\n\nScenario: Uploaded tracks are exposed to playback\n  Given a published title has subtitle tracks in multiple languages\n  When the playback service requests the title's track list\n  Then every uploaded track is exposed with its language and SDH labels (caption selection behaviour per CAP-PLAY)","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-08","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Price assignment per title","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to set the one-time purchase price for each title, so that viewers are charged the intended amount at checkout."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, assign the pricing for the film; John, 23:02, pay-per-view; 25:59-26:12, one-time purchase with permanent access, Mishal confirming buy-to-own with John). Price values themselves are a client decision; the console holds a configurable field."},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-03"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-02; the stored price is consumed by CAP-PAY (payments and entitlements)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build, simple field; consistency with Stripe checkout in CAP-PAY; no tier or rental fields in base scope (PPV only)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Set a price on a title\n  Given a draft title exists\n  When the operator enters a price in USD\n  Then the price is saved and displayed on the title\n\nScenario: Price validation\n  Given the operator is setting a price\n  When they enter a zero, negative, or non-numeric value\n  Then the value is rejected with a readable reason\n\nScenario: Price required before publish\n  Given a title has no price set\n  When the operator views the title\n  Then the price is indicated as required before publish\n\nScenario: Price change applies to future purchases only\n  Given a published title has existing purchasers\n  When the operator changes the price\n  Then new checkouts use the new price and existing purchasers keep their permanent access unchanged","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-09","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":12,"title":"Publish and unpublish","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to publish a title when it is ready and unpublish it when needed, so that I control exactly what viewers can see and buy."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12, ability to publish or unpublish a movie); permanent access on unpublish per Jul 1 call (25:59-26:12, Mishal confirming buy-to-own with John)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-03"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-03, CAP-CON-04, CAP-CON-05, CAP-CON-06, CAP-CON-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; readiness gating across encode, metadata, artwork, and price; entitlement interaction on unpublish (permanent access preserved)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Publish blocked until the title is ready\n  Given a title whose encode is not ready, or whose required metadata (per CAP-CON-05: name, description, category), artwork, or price is missing\n  When the operator attempts to publish\n  Then the publish is blocked and the unmet requirements are listed\n\nScenario: Publish a ready title\n  Given a title with a ready encode, complete required metadata (per CAP-CON-05), artwork, and a price\n  When the operator publishes it\n  Then the title becomes visible and purchasable on viewer surfaces\n\nScenario: Unpublish removes the title from sale\n  Given a published title\n  When the operator unpublishes it\n  Then the title disappears from all catalog surfaces and new purchases are blocked\n\nScenario: Unpublish preserves existing purchases\n  Given a viewer purchased a title before it was unpublished\n  When that viewer opens their library\n  Then the title remains playable for them (one-time purchase grants permanent access)\n\nScenario: Republish a title\n  Given an unpublished title that still meets all readiness requirements\n  When the operator publishes it again\n  Then it returns to viewer surfaces and can be purchased","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-01","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Timeboxed platform validation spike (go/no-go before build month 2)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want a timeboxed spike that validates the reference managed platform against our hardest requirements, so that we commit to a platform (or switch to a Mux-class alternative) before month 2 of the build instead of discovering a gap at premiere."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"you can probably use a lot of bunny if bunny can support up to this\"; John, 15:48; John, 29:16 100K concurrent; John, 16:49 anti-piracy and watermarking; John, 24:54 captions) + Allion scoping decision (register #6)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"None (this story gates the rest of the epic)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on vendor documentation, sandbox access, and vendor confirmation of limits; evidence-based testing rather than build work; hard calendar deadline (decision needed before build month 2, within the 4-5 month build window, register #17)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: 4K encode and playback confirmed on the reference platform\n  Given a test master is uploaded to the reference platform sandbox\n  When the platform encodes it with a ladder including a 4K tier (HEVC for the 4K tier, H.264 for tiers up to 1080p)\n  Then 4K playback is demonstrated on at least one web browser and one TV device from the V1 device set\n  And the result is recorded as evidence in the spike report\n\nScenario: Premiere-scale concurrent delivery capacity confirmed\n  Given the premiere profile requires 100,000 concurrent viewers at launch spike\n  When the team obtains the platform's published delivery limits and written vendor confirmation for this concurrency\n  Then the spike report records whether the platform can serve 100,000 concurrent streams, with the evidence source cited\n  And any vendor-imposed rate limits or pre-warming requirements are documented for CAP-INF\n\nScenario: Multi-DRM support confirmed\n  Given multi-DRM (Widevine, FairPlay, PlayReady) is in scope for both options\n  When DRM-protected playback is tested or vendor capability documentation is verified for each of the three DRM systems\n  Then the spike report records pass or fail per DRM system\n\nScenario: Forensic watermarking support confirmed\n  Given forensic watermarking is in scope for both options\n  When the platform's watermarking capability (native or via supported third-party integration) is verified\n  Then the spike report records whether watermarking is supported and by which mechanism\n\nScenario: Caption track support confirmed\n  Given titles must carry multi-language subtitle tracks at an Apple TV Plus new-release benchmark (approximately 30 to 40 languages) plus SDH\n  When multiple subtitle files are attached to the sandbox test title\n  Then the tracks are selectable in playback and the platform's per-title track limit is documented against the benchmark\n\nScenario: Go/no-go decision delivered on time\n  Given the spike is timeboxed to two weeks (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the timebox ends\n  Then a written go/no-go recommendation (reference platform vs a Mux-class alternative) is delivered before build month 2\n  And any requirement that could not be evidenced inside the timebox is listed as an explicit open risk rather than assumed to pass","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-02","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Platform account setup and vendor abstraction layer","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want all managed-platform calls wrapped behind an internal video service interface, so that the spike's go/no-go outcome (or a later platform switch) changes one adapter, not every product service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register #6, vendor-agnostic requirement with Bunny Stream reference)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-01 (platform choice confirmed), CAP-INF (environments and secrets management)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (thin internal service layer); external dependency on vendor API surface; design constraint that no vendor SDK types leak into product-service contracts"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Product services call the internal interface only\n  Given the internal video service interface is in place\n  When any product service needs ingest, playback token, or metrics functionality\n  Then it calls the internal interface and no product service calls the vendor API directly\n  And a static check or code review gate verifies no vendor SDK import outside the adapter\n\nScenario: Platform credentials are environment-separated\n  Given dev, staging, and production environments exist\n  When the adapter authenticates to the managed platform\n  Then each environment uses its own credentials held in the secrets store\n  And no platform credential appears in source control\n\nScenario: Vendor swap is contained to the adapter\n  Given a second adapter implementation (or test double) conforming to the internal interface\n  When the configured platform is switched in a test environment\n  Then all consumer-facing contract tests pass without changes to product services","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-03","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Master upload and ingest API integration","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want a master file I upload from the console to be ingested into the managed platform with clear status feedback, so that I know when a title is safe to publish without handling video formats myself."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 26:12 upload the film master, transcode, see the status; no objection from John) + Jun 22 call (John, 35:13 single internal upload stream) + Assumption - client to confirm (resumable upload and master replacement behaviour, not discussed on either call)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-01 (pipeline ingest and status portion; console upload UI remains under CAP-CON)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-02 (abstraction layer), CAP-CON (console upload screen)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration, not new build; external dependency on vendor ingest API and webhook/callback behaviour; large-file handling for 4K masters (resumable transfer)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Master ingested via the platform API\n  Given an operator starts a master upload from the console\n  When the file transfer completes\n  Then the master is registered with the managed platform via the ingest API\n  And processing begins without further operator action\n\nScenario: Processing status is visible end to end\n  Given a master is being processed by the platform\n  When the operator views the title in the console\n  Then the status shows one of: in progress, ready, or failed\n  And status updates propagate from the platform to the console without a manual refresh of the platform dashboard\n\nScenario: Failed ingest surfaces a readable reason\n  Given the platform rejects or fails to process a master\n  When the failure callback is received\n  Then the console shows a failed status with a human-readable reason\n  And other titles continue to process unaffected\n\nScenario: Interrupted upload can resume (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a large 4K master upload is interrupted mid-transfer\n  When the operator retries the upload\n  Then the transfer resumes or restarts safely without creating a duplicate title on the platform\n\nScenario: Replacing a master (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a title already has a processed master\n  When the operator uploads a replacement master\n  Then the new master supersedes the old one after successful processing\n  And viewers are never served a half-processed replacement","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-04","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Encode ladder configuration (4K down to SD)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want every ingested master encoded to a standard adaptive ladder from 4K down to SD, so that each device plays the best quality its screen and connection allow."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 7:39 majority 1080p, must support 4K; Mishal, 23:34 support 4K for MVP, drop to lower quality on weak networks; no objection from John) (register #2)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-03 (ingest)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Configuration on a managed platform rather than build; codec matrix (H.264 for tiers up to 1080p, HEVC for the 4K tier); per-device ladder verification effort in QA"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Standard ladder produced for every title\n  Given a master completes processing\n  When the encode ladder is inspected\n  Then it contains at minimum 4K, 1080p, 720p, and an SD tier (480p or 360p)\n  And the ladder is applied automatically with no per-title manual configuration\n\nScenario: Codec coverage for the V1 device set\n  Given the ladder is produced\n  When the renditions are inspected\n  Then H.264 renditions exist for ladder tiers up to 1080p\n  And the 4K tier is encoded in HEVC only, with no H.264 4K rendition (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  And each device in the V1 device set either plays the 4K HEVC rendition or is served the 1080p H.264 rendition as its quality ceiling, per a published device capability matrix\n\nScenario: Adaptive step-down under constrained bandwidth\n  Given a viewer is streaming on a connection that cannot sustain 4K\n  When available bandwidth drops\n  Then playback steps down the ladder without stopping the stream\n  And steps back up when bandwidth recovers","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-05","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Caption track ingest and delivery through the pipeline","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want subtitle files I upload per title to be attached to the platform asset and delivered as selectable text tracks, so that viewers can watch with captions in their language on every supported device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 24:54 support as many caption languages as an Apple TV Plus new release) + Allion scoping decision (register #14: operator-uploaded files, no auto-generation)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-03 (ingest), CAP-CON (caption upload screen), CAP-PLAY (player caption selection and SDH display)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration; data/volume factor (approximately 30 to 40 language tracks per title); platform-specific text-track behaviour across six client platforms"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Subtitle file attached to a title\n  Given an operator uploads a subtitle file with a language label for a title\n  When the platform accepts the file\n  Then the track is associated with that title's asset via the platform API\n  And it appears in the stream manifest as a selectable text track\n\nScenario: Benchmark language volume supported\n  Given a title with 35 language tracks (within the 30 to 40 benchmark range)\n  When the title is streamed\n  Then all uploaded tracks are listed and selectable in the player\n  And no platform per-title track limit is exceeded\n\nScenario: SDH track carried through\n  Given an SDH subtitle file is uploaded for a title\n  When a viewer selects the SDH track\n  Then the SDH track is delivered and labelled distinctly from the standard track for the same language\n\nScenario: Invalid caption file rejected with a clear message\n  Given an operator uploads a malformed subtitle file\n  When validation fails\n  Then the operator sees a readable error identifying the file and the problem\n  And previously attached tracks for the title remain intact","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-06","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Secure playback via signed URLs and tokens tied to entitlement","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want playback URLs issued only as short-lived signed tokens after an entitlement check, so that paid content cannot be played by sharing a link or hitting the asset URL directly."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 16:49 copyright and anti-piracy protection is very important) + Allion scoping decision (register #5, #6)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (access-control portion only; player experience remains under CAP-PLAY)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-02 (abstraction layer), CAP-PAY (entitlement service), CAP-ID (authenticated sessions)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with vendor token-auth scheme; security-sensitive path that must hold at premiere concurrency; interaction with geo gate and stream-limit checks at playback start"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Token issued only with a valid entitlement\n  Given a signed-in viewer with a valid purchase for a title\n  When the client requests playback\n  Then the entitlement check passes and a signed playback URL or token is returned\n  And playback starts with that token\n\nScenario: No entitlement, no token\n  Given a signed-in viewer without a purchase for a title\n  When the client requests playback\n  Then no playback token is issued\n  And the viewer receives a clear not-entitled response\n\nScenario: Direct asset access is denied\n  Given the underlying platform asset URL for a title\n  When it is requested without a valid signed token\n  Then the platform CDN refuses to serve the stream\n\nScenario: Tokens expire\n  Given a playback token with the configured time-to-live\n  When the token is used after expiry\n  Then the request is denied and the client must re-request playback through the entitlement check\n\nScenario: Shared link does not grant playback\n  Given a valid playback token issued to viewer A\n  When it is replayed from a different account or session context\n  Then playback is denied per the token binding rules\n\nScenario: Geo gate enforced at playback start\n  Given a viewer whose geo-IP resolves outside the US\n  When the client requests playback\n  Then no token is issued and a clear region message is shown (register #10; no VPN hardening in V1)\n\nScenario: Stream-limit result enforced at token issuance\n  Given an account already at its configured concurrent-screens limit (default 2, register #9)\n  When another playback request is made on the same account\n  Then the pass/fail check fails and no token is issued","scenarioCount":7,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-07","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"CDN delivery integration at premiere scale","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the film delivered from the platform's CDN edge, so that playback starts fast and stays smooth even when the premiere spike hits."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16 set max concurrent to 100,000; John, 39:34) + Allion scoping decision (register #16: 100K premiere bar applied to both options; the Option B bar is an assumption, client to confirm)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-04 (ladder), CAP-PIPE-06 (secure playback), CAP-INF (100K full-journey load test executes against this integration)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration; external dependency on vendor CDN capacity and any pre-warm coordination; premiere spike is the defining load profile, not steady state"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Streams served from the platform CDN\n  Given a published title with a valid playback token\n  When playback starts on any supported device\n  Then video segments are served from the platform's CDN edge, not from origin or our own compute\n\nScenario: Delivery readiness for the premiere concurrency bar\n  Given the premiere profile is 100,000 concurrent viewers (register #16; the Option B bar is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When delivery readiness is reviewed before the CAP-INF load test window (months 4 to 5, register #17)\n  Then CDN delivery configuration for the full encode ladder is complete in the production environment\n  And written vendor confirmation of delivery capacity for 100,000 concurrent streams is on file, extending the CAP-PIPE-01 spike evidence\n  And any vendor pre-warm or capacity-reservation steps are documented as launch runbook items\n  And pass/fail verification at 100,000 concurrent is executed under CAP-INF, which uses this integration as its test target\n\nScenario: QoE measurement hooks in place for the load test\n  Given the assumed QoE targets (video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent, error rate under 0.5 percent at peak; Assumption - client to confirm, register #18)\n  When the delivery integration is complete\n  Then video start time, rebuffer ratio, and delivery error rate are measurable for this integration via the CAP-PIPE-08 metrics feed\n  And the CAP-INF load test can report measured values against each target with pass or fail per target\n\nScenario: Regional delivery scope\n  Given V1 is US-only (register #10)\n  When delivery configuration is reviewed\n  Then CDN delivery is configured and costed for US audiences, and no multi-region delivery commitment is made","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-08","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":12,"title":"Platform QoE and delivery metrics into our observability","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the managed platform's delivery and QoE metrics pulled into our own observability stack, so that we can see problems before viewers do and feed the per-stream unit economics view."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02 unit economics and cost to stream, variable vs fixed costs) + Allion scoping decision (register #15, #18)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-02 (abstraction layer), CAP-MET (consumes GB-delivered and session data), CAP-INF (observability stack and alerting)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration; external dependency on vendor metrics API granularity and freshness; data mapping from vendor metric names to our internal schema"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Core delivery metrics ingested per title\n  Given the metrics integration is running\n  When the platform reports delivery data\n  Then playback sessions and GB delivered per title are available in our observability stack\n  And each metric is attributable to a title and a time window\n\nScenario: QoE signals ingested\n  Given the platform exposes QoE or delivery-quality signals\n  When they are ingested\n  Then video start time, rebuffer ratio, and delivery error rate are queryable in our stack\n  And gaps in what the vendor exposes are documented as spike/report findings, not silently dropped\n\nScenario: Rendition mix per title is reported\n  Given delivery metrics are ingested\n  When the rendition mix for a title is queried\n  Then the share of delivery at each ladder tier is visible per title and time window\n  And the expected 1080p-majority delivery pattern (register #2) can be confirmed against actuals\n\nScenario: Metrics freshness\n  Given the premiere spike is measured in hours, not days\n  When metrics are pulled\n  Then data is available in our stack within 15 minutes of the platform reporting it (Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Feed to unit economics\n  Given CAP-MET builds the cost and revenue view\n  When it queries delivery data\n  Then GB delivered and session counts per title are exposed through a stable internal contract\n  And delivery volume is identifiable as a variable cost input, separate from fixed platform fees\n\nScenario: Alerting on delivery degradation\n  Given assumed QoE thresholds (register #18; Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When a threshold is breached at the title or platform level\n  Then an alert fires to the operations channel defined in CAP-INF","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-01","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"Playback session records","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want every playback session recorded with the account, the title, the timing, the watched duration, and the quality mix, so that delivery usage can be attributed to viewers and titles and unit economics can be built on real data."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, minimal metering for unit economics) + Jun 22 call (Windana, 25:50, capture how long watched). Jun 22 framed broader tracking as a later bolt-on; the Jul 1 call brought minimal metering into V1."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (account identity), CAP-PLAY (player session events), CAP-PIPE (managed platform playback data)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the managed video platform's player events rather than a new build; event consistency across web, mobile, and TV clients; high event volume at premiere scale (handled under CAP-MET-06); heartbeat and abnormal-end handling."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Session record created at playback start\n  Given a viewer with a valid entitlement starts playback of a title\n  When the player begins streaming\n  Then a playback session record is created with account ID, title ID, device platform, and start timestamp\n\nScenario: Session record closed with duration at playback end\n  Given an open playback session\n  When the viewer stops playback or exits the player\n  Then the session record is closed with an end timestamp and total watched duration\n\nScenario: Quality mix captured per session\n  Given a session where the adaptive ladder switched between renditions\n  When the session record is closed\n  Then the record shows time watched at each rendition level (4K, 1080p, 720p, SD)\n  And the rendition times sum to the total watched duration within a 1 percent tolerance (assumed tolerance, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Pause and resume does not double count\n  Given a viewer pauses a film and resumes it later in the same sitting\n  When the session record is closed\n  Then paused time is excluded from watched duration\n  And the resumed viewing is attributed to the same title without duplicate duration\n\nScenario: Abnormal end is finalised automatically\n  Given a session that stops sending player heartbeats (app quit, network drop, device off)\n  When no heartbeat is received for 30 minutes (configurable, assumed value, client to confirm)\n  Then the session is auto-closed using the last known playback position\n  And no session remains open longer than 24 hours after its last heartbeat\n\nScenario: Sessions are queryable\n  Given closed session records exist\n  When the platform team queries sessions by title and date range\n  Then all matching session records are returned with account, duration, platform, and quality mix","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-02","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"GB delivered per session and per title","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the GB delivered recorded per playback session and totalled per title, so that the true variable delivery cost of each stream and each title is known."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, per-GB cost to stream) + Jun 22 call (Shashila, 20:55, delivery metrics per title from the CDN) + Allion scoping decision (monthly reconciliation against vendor-reported usage added as a data-quality control on vendor usage figures)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET-01 (session records), CAP-PIPE (managed platform usage reporting, granularity confirmed by the validation spike)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on the managed platform's usage-data granularity (per-session vs aggregate); fallback estimation from quality-mix bitrates if per-session data is not exposed; reconciliation job against vendor-reported usage."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: GB attributed to a closed session\n  Given a playback session has closed\n  When usage data is processed\n  Then the session record carries a GB delivered value\n  And the value is flagged as measured (from platform data) or estimated (derived from quality mix and rendition bitrates)\n\nScenario: Per-title daily totals\n  Given closed sessions exist for a title\n  When daily aggregation runs\n  Then the title shows total GB delivered per calendar day and cumulative GB to date\n\nScenario: Data available within one day\n  Given streaming occurred on a given day, including a launch day\n  When the operator views usage the following day\n  Then that day's per-title GB totals are available (24 hour maximum latency, assumed value, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Reconciliation against vendor-reported usage\n  Given a completed billing month\n  When monthly title totals are compared with the managed platform's reported account usage\n  Then the difference is within 5 percent (assumed tolerance, client to confirm)\n  And any larger discrepancy is flagged for review\n\nScenario: Sessions without usage data are surfaced\n  Given a closed session for which no measured or estimated GB value could be produced\n  When daily aggregation runs\n  Then the session is counted and flagged as unmetered rather than silently dropped","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-03","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"Variable vs fixed cost line register","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want infrastructure cost lines recorded and tagged as variable or fixed, so that the client's accounting can separate the cost to serve each stream from the standing platform cost."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, \"we need to know which are variable costs versus fixed costs\")"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (console surface, single-operator maintenance)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build but small (a simple configuration register, not a finance system); effective-dated rate history so past periods keep their reported figures; correctness of the variable rate feeds CAP-MET-04; no external integration."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Create a variable cost line\n  Given the operator is signed in to the console\n  When they create a cost line tagged variable with a unit (per GB delivered) and a rate\n  Then the line is saved and available to the cost calculations\n\nScenario: Create a fixed cost line\n  Given the operator is signed in to the console\n  When they create a cost line tagged fixed with a monthly amount\n  Then the line is saved and included in the monthly fixed total\n\nScenario: Seeded default cost lines\n  Given a fresh environment\n  When the cost register is first opened\n  Then it contains seeded lines for delivery per GB (variable) and managed platform base fee (fixed)\n  And the seed list and rates are marked as defaults (assumed seed set, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Rate changes apply from an effective date\n  Given a cost line has an existing per-GB rate\n  When the operator updates the rate with a new effective date\n  Then the cost line stores the new rate alongside its full rate history\n  And usage before the effective date is costed at the rate in effect at the time of delivery\n  And usage on or after the effective date is costed at the new rate\n  And stored usage data is never modified by a rate change\n\nScenario: Historical figures are stable across rate changes\n  Given a closed month has reported delivery cost figures\n  When a rate change with a later effective date is applied\n  Then the closed month's cost figures are unchanged in every view and export\n  And two exports of that month taken before and after the rate change show identical delivery costs\n\nScenario: Variable vs fixed monthly summary\n  Given cost lines and usage data exist for a month\n  When the operator opens the cost split summary\n  Then it shows total variable cost (usage multiplied by the variable rates in effect for the period) and total fixed cost for that month as separate figures","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-04","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"Per-title cost and revenue view (per-stream unit economics)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the internal operator, I want a simple per-title view of delivery cost against pay-per-view revenue, including average cost per stream, so that the client can see per-stream unit economics (for example, what a purchase price of 5.99 costs in delivery per stream)."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, \"if we charge 599 then 18 cents will be the cost to stream\")"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET-02 (GB per title), CAP-MET-03 (variable rate), CAP-PAY (purchase and refund records), CAP-CON (console surface)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration joining Stripe purchase data with delivery usage data; a simple internal screen, not a BI tool; date-range recomputation; all figures internal-only."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Per-title economics summary\n  Given a title with closed sessions and completed purchases\n  When the operator opens the title's cost and revenue view\n  Then it shows total streams, total GB delivered, delivery cost, pay-per-view revenue, and margin for the selected period\n\nScenario: Average cost per stream\n  Given a title with usage and cost data\n  When the view is displayed\n  Then average delivery cost per stream equals total delivery cost divided by total streams for the period\n  And delivery cost equals total GB multiplied by the per-GB rate in effect for the period, from the cost register\n\nScenario: Revenue matches payment records\n  Given completed and refunded purchases exist for a title\n  When the view is displayed\n  Then revenue equals the sum of successful pay-per-view payments minus refunds for the selected period\n  And the figure reconciles with the payment records in CAP-PAY\n\nScenario: Date range filter\n  Given the operator selects a custom date range\n  When the view refreshes\n  Then all figures (streams, GB, cost, revenue, margin) recompute for that range only\n\nScenario: Titles with no activity\n  Given a published title with no sessions or purchases in the selected period\n  When the view is displayed\n  Then the title shows zero values rather than an error\n\nScenario: Prices are shown as data, not configured here\n  Given the view displays revenue figures\n  When the operator uses the view\n  Then no pricing can be set or changed from this screen (pricing is owned by the content console and is a client decision)","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-05","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"CSV export for accounting","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the internal operator, I want to export session, usage, and cost and revenue data as CSV files, so that the client's accounting team can work with the numbers outside the platform."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, \"this is more for accounting's sake\") + Allion scoping decision; CSV as the format and the column sets are an Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET-01 (sessions), CAP-MET-02 (usage), CAP-MET-04 (cost and revenue figures)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Low build complexity; data volume factor for launch-scale session exports; column stability so accounting spreadsheets do not break between exports; pseudonymisation of account references pending US video-privacy review."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Export playback sessions\n  Given closed sessions exist\n  When the operator exports sessions for a date range\n  Then a CSV downloads with one row per session including a pseudonymous account reference, title, start, end, duration, platform, quality mix, and GB delivered\n  And no direct account identifier (email address or name) appears in the file (treatment of account-level identifiers in exports is subject to US video-privacy review, Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Export per-title daily usage\n  Given daily aggregates exist\n  When the operator exports usage for a date range\n  Then a CSV downloads with one row per title per day including streams, GB delivered, and delivery cost\n\nScenario: Export cost and revenue summary\n  Given the per-title cost and revenue view has data\n  When the operator exports the summary for a date range\n  Then a CSV downloads with one row per title including streams, GB, delivery cost, revenue, margin, and average cost per stream\n\nScenario: Stable column layout\n  Given two exports of the same type taken on different days\n  When the files are compared\n  Then the column names and order are identical\n\nScenario: Launch-scale export completes\n  Given a session export covering a premiere day at launch scale\n  When the export is requested\n  Then the file is produced successfully without timeout (delivery may be asynchronous for large ranges)\n\nScenario: Export is operator-only\n  Given a request to an export endpoint without an authenticated operator session\n  When the request is made\n  Then it is rejected and no data is returned","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-06","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":12,"title":"Metering capture at premiere scale","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want metering capture to keep working through the 100,000 concurrent premiere spike without slowing playback, so that the launch window, where most of the revenue lands, is fully captured."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16, 100,000 concurrent; John, 11:23, 50 to 60 percent of lifetime earnings in the first 24 hours) + Allion scoping decision (100K premiere load bar applies to both options; the Option B bar is an assumption, client to confirm)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET-01 (session records), CAP-INF (surge protection and load test profile)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Event ingestion volume at 100K concurrent; asynchronous, non-blocking capture design (buffering and queueing); inclusion in the full-journey load test profile."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Metering never blocks playback\n  Given the metering ingestion service is degraded or unavailable\n  When a viewer with a valid entitlement starts playback\n  Then playback starts normally\n  And metering events are buffered client-side or queued for at least 6 hours and delivered when ingestion recovers (assumed window, client to confirm)\n  And any sessions whose events are lost beyond the buffer window are counted and flagged as unmetered per CAP-MET-02\n\nScenario: Capture completeness under peak load\n  Given a load test simulating 100,000 concurrent full-journey users\n  When the test completes\n  Then at least 99 percent of simulated playback sessions have a complete session record (assumed threshold, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Backlog drains after the spike\n  Given metering events were queued during a load spike\n  When the spike subsides\n  Then the queued events are processed and reflected in usage data within 6 hours (assumed window, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Metering is part of the premiere load test\n  Given the 100K concurrent load test profile defined under CAP-INF\n  When the test plan is reviewed\n  Then session capture, GB attribution, and event ingestion are included as measured components of the test","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-01","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Dev, stage, and production environments","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want separate dev, stage, and production environments for the application backend and console, so that changes can be built and verified without risk to the live service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (delivery scaffolding for the 4-5 month build window, Jul 1 call, John, 33:49)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"None"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (infrastructure as code across three environments); external dependency (managed video platform and Stripe need per-environment configuration, sandbox vs live)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Three isolated environments exist\n  Given the platform infrastructure is provisioned\n  When the environment inventory is reviewed\n  Then dev, stage, and production environments exist as separately addressable deployments\n  And no environment shares databases or user data with another\n\nScenario: Stage mirrors production configuration\n  Given a service is deployed to stage and production\n  When the two configurations are compared\n  Then stage runs the same service versions and infrastructure topology as production, differing only in scale and secrets\n\nScenario: External services are wired per environment\n  Given Stripe and the managed video platform are integrated\n  When a payment or playback call is made from dev or stage\n  Then it reaches the sandbox or test instance of the external service, never the live one\n\nScenario: Environments are reproducible from code\n  Given the infrastructure definitions are stored in version control\n  When an environment is rebuilt from those definitions\n  Then the rebuilt environment passes the same smoke checks as the original","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-02","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"CI/CD pipeline","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want an automated build, test, and deployment pipeline through dev, stage, and production, so that the team can ship changes safely and repeatedly inside the 4-5 month build window."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (delivery scaffolding for the timeline, Jul 1 call, John, 33:16-33:49)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (pipeline per backend service plus console); platform multiplier is limited (client app store pipelines sit in PLAT-* epics)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Commit triggers an automated build and test run\n  Given a developer merges a change to a backend service\n  When the pipeline runs\n  Then the service is built and its automated tests execute\n  And a failing test blocks the change from deploying to any environment\n\nScenario: Promotion through environments is gated\n  Given a build has passed automated tests\n  When it is promoted\n  Then it deploys to dev, then stage, then production in order\n  And promotion to production requires an explicit approval step\n\nScenario: Deployments do not interrupt viewers\n  Given active playback sessions and purchases are in flight in production\n  When a new version is deployed\n  Then in-flight requests complete without error during the rollout\n\nScenario: A bad release can be rolled back\n  Given a production deployment introduces a fault\n  When a rollback is triggered\n  Then the previous known-good version is restored\n  And the rollback completes within an agreed time (target 15 minutes, Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-03","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Auto-scaling application backend","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want the catalogue, account, entitlement, and playback session services to scale horizontally with demand, so that a premiere spike of up to 100,000 concurrent viewers is an incremental cost, not a re-architecture."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (John's scaling question and the horizontal-scaling answer, 18:20-19:49); Jul 1 call (John, 29:16, 100,000 concurrent)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-01; CAP-PIPE (managed platform integration) for the video-layer boundary"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (stateless service design, scaling policies, connection pooling at spike load); data/volume factor (100,000 concurrent full-journey load is the sizing bar for both options; the Option B bar is an Assumption - client to confirm)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Services scale out under rising load\n  Given production-representative load is increasing on the backend services\n  When demand exceeds the current capacity threshold\n  Then additional service instances are added automatically without manual intervention\n  And no downtime occurs during scale-out\n\nScenario: Services scale back in after the spike\n  Given a premiere spike has passed and load has fallen\n  When the scale-in policy evaluates\n  Then instance counts reduce automatically toward the baseline\n  And no active sessions are dropped by scale-in\n\nScenario: Backend holds the premiere concurrency bar\n  Given the load-test environment (CAP-INF-06) drives the premiere profile\n  When 100,000 concurrent simulated viewers are active\n  Then catalogue, account, entitlement, and playback session services keep p95 API response under 500 ms (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: One service failing does not take down the journey\n  Given a single backend service instance fails under load\n  When viewers continue browsing, paying, and starting playback\n  Then requests are served by remaining healthy instances\n  And the platform-wide error rate stays under 0.5 percent (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Database layer sustains spike write and read patterns\n  Given the premiere profile includes a login storm and a purchase burst\n  When the datastore is at peak load\n  Then entitlement writes and session reads complete without exhausting connections or queueing beyond the p95 API target","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-04","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Observability: logs, metrics, alerts, dashboards","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want centralised logs, metrics, alerting, and dashboards across the backend, so that problems are seen and acted on before viewers hit a wall."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision, supporting the technical success bar that no user story hits a wall (Jul 1 call, John, 37:46-39:04)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-01, CAP-INF-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration-heavy (log and metric collection across all backend services plus managed platform delivery signals where the vendor exposes them); alert tuning for spike conditions"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Logs are centralised and searchable\n  Given all backend services are running in production\n  When an engineer searches the logging system for a request identifier\n  Then correlated log entries from every service that handled the request are returned\n\nScenario: Core health metrics are collected\n  Given the platform is serving traffic\n  When the metrics store is queried\n  Then request rate, error rate, latency percentiles, and instance counts are available per service with at most 1 minute lag (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Alerts fire on threshold breach\n  Given alert rules are configured for error rate, latency, and saturation\n  When a service breaches a threshold (for example error rate above 0.5 percent, assumed target, client to confirm)\n  Then an alert notifies the on-call channel within 5 minutes (assumed target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: A premiere dashboard shows the live picture\n  Given a premiere event is underway\n  When the operations dashboard is opened\n  Then concurrent playback sessions, sign-in rate, purchase success and decline rate, and API latency are visible on one screen\n  And a waiting-room queue depth panel is added to the same screen as an increment when the surge controls (CAP-INF-05) deliver\n\nScenario: Observability data is retained for post-event review\n  Given a premiere event has completed\n  When the team reviews the event the following day\n  Then logs and metrics covering the full event window are still available (retention period Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-05","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Surge protection: rate limiting and waiting room","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want rate limiting and a request queueing or waiting-room control in front of the sign-in and purchase paths, so that a premiere-scale rush degrades gracefully instead of failing for everyone."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16 and 35:09, spike behaviour with everything happening at the same time); exact mechanism is an Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (queueing and admission control at the edge of the app backend); external dependency (Stripe capacity on the purchase burst path); user-facing behaviour must stay client-safe and clear"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Per-client rate limits protect the APIs\n  Given rate limits are configured on the public API endpoints\n  When a single client exceeds the allowed request rate\n  Then further requests from that client receive a throttled response with a retry signal\n  And other clients are unaffected\n\nScenario: Waiting room engages above the admission threshold\n  Given demand on sign-in or purchase exceeds the configured admission rate\n  When new viewers arrive\n  Then they are held in a queue or waiting room rather than receiving errors (mechanism Assumption - client to confirm)\n  And each queued viewer sees an in-progress message rather than a failure\n\nScenario: Queued viewers are admitted in order as capacity allows\n  Given viewers are held in the waiting room\n  When backend capacity becomes available\n  Then viewers are admitted in arrival order at a rate the backend sustains without breaching the p95 API target\n\nScenario: Viewers already watching are not disturbed\n  Given the waiting room is active for new arrivals\n  When a viewer with an existing playback session continues watching\n  Then their playback, pause, and resume actions are not routed through the queue\n\nScenario: Surge controls are configurable without a release\n  Given admission thresholds and rate limits are configuration values\n  When an operator adjusts them ahead of a premiere\n  Then the new values take effect without redeploying the services","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-06","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Load-test environment and full-journey simulation harness","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want a dedicated load-test environment and a traffic simulation harness that reproduces the full viewer journey at 100,000 concurrent, so that the premiere stress test at month 4 to 5 is possible to run at all."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 33:16, stress testing at four to five months; 33:49, enough built by month 4 with simulated user actions running by the five-month mark; 35:09, every button the person touches)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-01, CAP-INF-02; CAP-PIPE (managed platform validation, including vendor coordination for high-volume test traffic, Assumption - client to confirm with vendor)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (this is a build deliverable, not just a QA task: environment plus scripted journey harness); data/volume factor (generating 100,000 concurrent full journeys); external dependency (test-mode payment traffic through Stripe, streaming test traffic through the managed platform)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: A production-representative load-test environment exists\n  Given the load-test environment is provisioned\n  When its topology is compared with production\n  Then it runs the same services, scaling policies, and surge controls as production at a scalable capacity\n\nScenario: The harness simulates the full journey, not just streaming\n  Given the simulation scripts are executed\n  When a simulated viewer runs\n  Then the script covers sign-in, purchase (including declined payments), playback start, pause, rewind, quit and resume, and forced sign-out\n  And each action issues real API calls against the environment\n\nScenario: The harness reaches the concurrency bar\n  Given a full-scale run is launched\n  When the harness ramps up\n  Then it sustains 100,000 concurrent simulated viewers across mixed journey states for at least the agreed soak window (duration Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Payment load uses test traffic only\n  Given the purchase burst is simulated\n  When payment calls are made\n  Then all traffic uses the payment provider's test mode and no live charges occur\n\nScenario: The environment can be stood up and torn down on demand\n  Given a test window is scheduled\n  When the environment is created before the run and destroyed after\n  Then the environment is created by a single automated pipeline run and destroyed by a single automated pipeline run\n  And all load-generating and environment compute resources are deprovisioned after teardown (only persistent artefacts such as scripts and result data remain)\n\nScenario: Runs produce comparable reports\n  Given two load-test runs execute on different days\n  When their results are reviewed\n  Then each run reports the same metric set (throughput, latency percentiles, error rates, queue behaviour) so results are comparable run over run","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-07","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":12,"title":"Premiere-profile stress test at month 4 to 5","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want the 100,000 concurrent full-journey premiere test executed against the assumed quality targets in the month 4 to 5 window of the delivery plan, so that launch readiness is proven before the film goes live."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 33:16-33:49, stress testing at four to five months; 35:09, full-journey concurrency); pass thresholds are assumed targets (Assumption - client to confirm)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-05, CAP-INF-06; requires enough of CAP-ID (identity), CAP-PAY (payments and entitlements), and CAP-PLAY (playback) built to exercise the full journey"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration-heavy (exercises every capability epic end to end); schedule-critical (the month 4 to 5 window is anchored to the roughly 6 month timeline discussed on the Jul 1 call; if the Option B timeline lands differently in the estimate, the stress-test window shifts proportionally, Assumption - client to confirm for Option B); retest loop for defects found at scale"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: A full premiere-profile run executes the complete journey mix\n  Given the premiere stress test is launched against the load-test environment\n  When the run ramps to peak\n  Then 100,000 concurrent simulated viewers are sustained at peak\n  And the run includes the login storm, purchase burst with declines, playback surge, trick-play, quit and resume, and forced sign-out mix\n\nScenario: Assumed quality targets are met at peak\n  Given the full premiere profile is at peak load\n  When platform metrics are measured\n  Then video start time is under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent, p95 API under 500 ms, payment confirmation under 10 seconds, and error rate under 0.5 percent (all assumed targets, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: No journey hits a wall\n  Given simulated viewers are running the full journey at peak\n  When results are reviewed\n  Then every simulated viewer who attempts to pay and play either completes or receives a controlled queue or retry response, never a dead end\n\nScenario: Surge controls behave as designed at scale\n  Given demand exceeds the admission threshold during the test\n  When the waiting room engages\n  Then queueing, ordered admission, and protection of in-progress playback all behave as specified in CAP-INF-05\n\nScenario: Defects found at scale are retested\n  Given the run surfaces defects or missed targets\n  When fixes are applied\n  Then a re-run of the affected portion of the profile confirms the fix before launch readiness is declared","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-01","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Responsive web application shell and cross-browser baseline","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the service to work in my desktop or mobile browser without installing anything, so that I can browse, pay, and watch with no friction."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Craig 8:18 web surface; John 18:20 80 percent device coverage) + Jul 1 call (John, 42:39, \"you need to create all of the places that you would expect them to want to... I'll just watch it on my browser\")"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"None"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; four-browser matrix multiplier; responsive breakpoint set (desktop, tablet, phone); foundation for all other PLAT-WEB stories."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Application loads on every supported browser\n  Given a viewer on a current version of Chrome, Edge, Safari, or Firefox\n  When they open the service URL\n  Then the application shell renders with navigation and content area\n  And no plugin, extension, or install step is required\n\nScenario: Layout adapts to viewport size\n  Given the application is open in a supported browser\n  When the viewport is desktop, tablet, or phone width\n  Then the layout reflows to the matching responsive breakpoint\n  And no content or primary action is cut off or unreachable\n\nScenario: Unsupported browser messaging (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a viewer on a browser outside the supported matrix\n  When they open the service URL\n  Then a clear message lists the supported browsers\n  And no broken or partially rendered experience is shown","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-02","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Film landing page (marketing-grade)","options":"A only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer arriving from a poster, post, or link, I want a marketing-grade landing page for the film, so that I immediately understand the film and can start the purchase journey in one straight line."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"a bunch of people who heard about it online or saw a poster to go to the same place to pay for a film and then to watch it... it's a straight line conversion\"; selection UI built \"in the context of having more\" titles) + Allion scoping decision (register decision 7)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (web home, Option A form)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-WEB-01, PLAT-WEB-03, CAP-CON (published film metadata and artwork)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; marketing-grade visual quality bar; page kept cache-friendly in support of the CAP-INF surge-protection approach; layout designed to extend to more titles later."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Arrival from an external link\n  Given a signed-out viewer follows an external link to the landing page\n  When the page loads\n  Then film artwork, title, and the primary purchase call to action are visible without scrolling\n\nScenario: Straight-line conversion entry\n  Given a viewer on the landing page\n  When they select the primary call to action\n  Then they are routed into the film detail and checkout flow with no intermediate browsing step\n\nScenario: Selection UI works with more than one published title\n  Given more than one title is published in a test environment\n  When the landing page loads\n  Then each published title is presented with its own selection entry\n  And the straight-line purchase flow completes for a selected title\n\nScenario: Launch-spike readiness\n  Given the premiere marketing push drives a traffic surge\n  When the landing page is requested at surge volume\n  Then the landing page meets the surge-protection ACs in CAP-INF (CAP-INF-05)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-03","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Film detail page","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a film detail page with trailer, synopsis, and price, so that I can decide to buy and start the purchase from one place."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 7: landing page plus film detail page, pay, watch); trailer element = Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (film metadata presentation, web surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-WEB-01, CAP-CON (published metadata, artwork, pricing), CAP-PAY (entitlement state)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; trailer playback reuses the player component; entitlement-aware state logic."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Film details render\n  Given a published film\n  When a viewer opens its detail page\n  Then title, synopsis, artwork, and price are displayed as set in the content console (full metadata field set per CAP-CON)\n\nScenario: Trailer playback without purchase (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Given a viewer who has not purchased the film\n  When they play the trailer on the detail page\n  Then the trailer streams without any payment or sign-in requirement\n\nScenario: Purchased state\n  Given a signed-in viewer who owns the film (entitlement per CAP-PAY)\n  When they open the detail page\n  Then the price call to action is replaced by a Watch action that opens the player page\n\nScenario: Unpublished film is not reachable\n  Given a film that is unpublished in the content console (per CAP-CON)\n  When any viewer requests its detail page URL\n  Then a not-available response is shown and no metadata is exposed","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-04","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Web checkout flow","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to pay for a film in my browser and get immediate access, so that paying and watching never hits a wall."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02 pay-per-view; 37:46-39:04, \"if somebody wants to watch it and they want to pay us, we better take their money and play them the film\") + register decisions 3 and 10"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (web surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY (Stripe purchase, entitlement, failure, geo-gate, tax ACs), CAP-ID (signed-in session), PLAT-WEB-03, PLAT-WEB-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (Stripe web elements); four-browser rendering multiplier; purchase-burst behavior at launch covered by the CAP-INF load profile."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PAY (purchase, entitlement grant, declined payment, geo-IP gate, tax) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Checkout renders across the browser matrix\n  Given a signed-in viewer on any supported browser\n  When they start checkout for a film\n  Then the Stripe payment form renders and accepts input correctly\n\nScenario: Successful payment lands on playback entry\n  Given a viewer completes payment successfully (per CAP-PAY)\n  When the confirmation is received\n  Then the browser shows a confirmation and a direct Watch now action into the player page\n\nScenario: Failed payment keeps context\n  Given a viewer whose payment is declined (per CAP-PAY)\n  When the failure is returned\n  Then a clear message is shown with a retry action\n  And the viewer remains on the checkout flow without re-entering the film selection\n\nScenario: Refresh during checkout does not duplicate purchase\n  Given a viewer refreshes the browser mid-checkout\n  When the page reloads\n  Then the current order state is restored and no duplicate charge is created (duplicate-event and recovery handling per CAP-PAY-05)\n\nScenario: Geo-blocked viewer messaging\n  Given a viewer outside the US (geo-IP gate per CAP-PAY)\n  When they attempt checkout\n  Then the web page shows a clear US-only availability message","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-05","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Web player page","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to watch my purchased film in the browser with full player controls, so that web playback feels like a premium streaming service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, pay, watch, \"maybe pause it and watch it later and finish later\"; 35:09, play, pause, rewind 15 seconds, quit and return) + register decisions 2, 5, 9, and 14"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (web surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY (playback, adaptive ladder, resume, captions, concurrent-screen ACs), CAP-DRM (license and watermark ACs), CAP-PAY (entitlement), PLAT-WEB-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (managed platform web player); per-browser DRM variant selection from the CAP-DRM multi-DRM set (Widevine, FairPlay, PlayReady), with the exact browser mapping confirmed with the managed platform; accessibility (keyboard control, SDH captions)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY (4K-to-SD adaptive ladder, pause/resume, trick-play, caption selection and SDH, concurrent-screen limit) and CAP-DRM apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Protected playback licenses on every supported browser\n  Given an entitled viewer on each supported browser\n  When playback starts\n  Then the DRM variant defined in CAP-DRM for that browser licenses and plays\n\nScenario: Fullscreen viewing\n  Given a film is playing in the browser\n  When the viewer toggles fullscreen\n  Then playback continues uninterrupted and controls remain reachable in fullscreen\n\nScenario: Keyboard control\n  Given a film is playing on a desktop browser\n  When the viewer uses keyboard controls\n  Then play/pause and the 15-second rewind and forward skip respond without a pointer (trick-play set per CAP-PLAY-03)\n\nScenario: Close tab and resume later\n  Given a viewer closes the browser tab mid-film\n  When they return to the film on the web later\n  Then playback offers resume from the saved position (position tracking per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Caption menu on every supported browser\n  Given a film with multiple subtitle languages (per CAP-PLAY)\n  When the viewer opens the caption menu on any supported browser\n  Then all available languages and the SDH option are selectable and render during playback\n\nScenario: Concurrent-screen limit message\n  Given the account's concurrent-screen limit is already reached (per CAP-PLAY)\n  When the viewer starts playback in the browser\n  Then a clear message explains the limit and playback does not start","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-06","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Account pages","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to create and manage my account and see my purchased films in the browser, so that my access and library are always reachable."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 8, extending Jun 22 email/password) + Jul 1 call (Mishal/John, 25:59-26:12, purchase \"added to our library forever\", buy-to-own)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (web surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (registration, sign-in, social sign-in, password reset ACs), CAP-PAY (purchase records)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (CAP-ID flows surfaced on web); Apple and Google OAuth web redirect handling; responsive form work."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID (credential rules, account lifecycle, password reset, Apple and Google sign-in) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Sign-up and sign-in forms across breakpoints\n  Given a viewer on desktop, tablet, or phone width\n  When they open sign-up or sign-in\n  Then the forms render and submit correctly at that breakpoint\n\nScenario: Apple and Google sign-in on the web\n  Given a viewer chooses Apple or Google sign-in\n  When the provider's web flow completes\n  Then the viewer returns to the page they started from, signed in (account rules per CAP-ID)\n\nScenario: Password reset completes in the browser\n  Given a viewer requests a password reset (per CAP-ID)\n  When they follow the emailed link\n  Then a web form lets them set a new password and sign in\n\nScenario: Library shows owned films\n  Given a signed-in viewer with completed purchases\n  When they open their account library page\n  Then every purchased film is listed with a play entry point (non-expiring entitlement per CAP-PAY)\n\nScenario: Sign out\n  Given a signed-in viewer\n  When they sign out from the account page\n  Then the session ends and entitled content is no longer playable in that browser","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-07","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"TV activation entry page","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer setting up a TV app, I want to enter the code my TV shows on a simple web page, so that I can sign in on TV without typing credentials with a remote."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 8); short URL path = Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (TV activation-code capability, CAP-ID-05), PLAT-WEB-06, PLAT-ROKU / PLAT-FTV / PLAT-SAM (code display on device)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (CAP-ID activation service); small surface but launch-critical for all three TV platforms."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID-05 (code generation, validity window, expiry, device linking) apply. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Activation page reachable by short URL\n  Given a viewer is shown a code and web address on their TV\n  When they open the activation page address in any supported browser\n  Then a code entry form is displayed (short memorable path, Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Signed-out viewer is routed through sign-in\n  Given a signed-out viewer opens the activation page\n  When they sign in or create an account (per CAP-ID)\n  Then they are returned to the code entry form without losing the flow\n\nScenario: Valid code links the TV\n  Given a signed-in viewer enters a valid activation code\n  When the code is confirmed (per CAP-ID-05)\n  Then the web page shows a success confirmation\n\nScenario: Invalid or expired code\n  Given a viewer enters an invalid or expired code\n  When the code is rejected (per CAP-ID-05)\n  Then a clear error explains the code failed and how to get a fresh code on the TV","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-08","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":12,"title":"Browser-matrix certification","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the web app certified across the supported browser matrix before launch, so that no supported viewer hits a wall on launch night."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 37:46-39:04, no user story hits a wall) + Jun 22 call (John, 18:20, cover the top 80 percent of streaming device market share) + register decisions 1 and 20; browser version policy = Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-WEB-01 and PLAT-WEB-03 through PLAT-WEB-07 in both options; PLAT-WEB-02 under Option A; PLAT-WEB-09 through PLAT-WEB-13 under Option B; CAP-DRM (browser DRM variants)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Matrix multiplier (4 browsers x 3 breakpoints); per-browser DRM variants per CAP-DRM; repeat pass needed before the month 4-5 stress-test window (register decision 17)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Full journey passes on every matrix cell\n  Given the certification matrix of Chrome, Edge, Safari, and Firefox at current and previous major versions (version policy: Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the end-to-end journey (land, sign up, pay, play, pause, resume, captions) is executed on each cell\n  Then every step passes with no blocking defect\n\nScenario: DRM verified per browser\n  Given each browser in the matrix\n  When protected playback is certified\n  Then the DRM variant defined in CAP-DRM for that browser licenses and plays\n\nScenario: Responsive breakpoints certified\n  Given each browser in the matrix\n  When desktop, tablet, and phone widths are exercised\n  Then layout and primary actions pass on every breakpoint\n\nScenario: Option B surfaces join the matrix\n  Given Option B is the selected scope\n  When certification runs\n  Then catalog home, curated rows, the continue-watching rail, genre browse, search, and watchlist pages are included in the same matrix\n\nScenario: Certification gates release\n  Given any blocking defect is found in a matrix cell\n  When release readiness is assessed\n  Then launch is blocked until the defect is fixed and the cell re-passes","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-01","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"iOS app shell and foundation","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a native iOS app I can install and open on my iPhone, so that I can watch the film the way I would on any established streaming service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Craig, 8:18) + Jul 1 call (John, 42:39, \"you still got to build the app for them to watch it\")"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF (API environments)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New native build (Swift/SwiftUI or equivalent); platform multiplier (one of six client surfaces); brand and design system applied to a second form factor."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: App installs and launches\n  Given an iPhone running a supported iOS version\n  When the viewer installs the app and opens it\n  Then the app launches to the landing screen without crashes or blocking errors\n\nScenario: Supported iOS versions (assumed, client to confirm)\n  Given the supported-version policy is the current and previous major iOS release (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the app is run on the oldest supported version\n  Then all launch, browse, purchase, and playback flows function\n\nScenario: Network loss on launch\n  Given the device has no network connection\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then a clear offline message is shown and the app recovers automatically when the connection returns\n\nScenario: Cellular and Wi-Fi operation\n  Given the viewer is on a cellular connection\n  When they use any core flow (browse, sign-in, purchase entry, playback)\n  Then the flow completes without requiring Wi-Fi\n\nScenario: iPad handling (assumed, client to confirm)\n  Given iPhone-first delivery with iPad in compatibility mode is an Assumption - client to confirm\n  When the app is opened on an iPad\n  Then all core flows (landing, detail, sign-in, purchase entry, playback) can be completed in iPhone-compatibility mode without truncated or inoperable controls","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-02","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"Single-film landing and film detail","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to land directly on the film and see its details on my iPhone, so that I can go from arrival to purchase with minimal steps."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, one film, selection UI \"in the context of having more\") + Allion scoping decision (register decision 7: landing plus detail, no catalog grid in A)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (iOS delivery aspects)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-01, CAP-CON (published title metadata)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New UI build; low data volume in A but the selection component must be built to scale to multiple titles; artwork rendering across device sizes."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Landing shows the featured film\n  Given one published film exists\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then the landing screen shows the film artwork, title, and a clear call to action\n\nScenario: Selection UI built for more titles\n  Given the landing screen uses a title-selection component\n  When a second published title is added by the operator\n  Then it appears in the same component without an app change\n\nScenario: Film detail screen\n  Given the viewer taps the film\n  When the detail screen opens\n  Then it shows title, description, credits, artwork, price, and the purchase or play action\n\nScenario: Only published titles appear\n  Given a title is unpublished in the content console\n  When the viewer opens the landing screen\n  Then that title is not shown anywhere in the app\n\nScenario: Owned title shows play instead of purchase\n  Given the viewer has already purchased the film\n  When they open the detail screen\n  Then the primary action is Play, not a purchase prompt\n\nScenario: Detail is viewable before sign-in\n  Given a viewer who is not signed in\n  When they open the landing and detail screens\n  Then they can view film information without an account, and are prompted to sign in only when purchasing or playing","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-03","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"Account creation, sign-in, and account management on iOS","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to create and manage my account inside the iOS app, so that my purchases and playback follow me across devices."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 8: email+password, Apple sign-in, Google sign-in, password reset); Sign in with Apple is mandatory under App Store rules when other third-party sign-in options are offered; in-app account deletion is an App Store policy requirement (platform-driven addition, listed in the assumptions register)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (iOS delivery aspects)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-01, CAP-ID"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with CAP-ID rather than new build; external dependency on Apple and Google identity services; App Store policy compliance (Apple sign-in, in-app account deletion)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID apply on this platform. In-app account deletion is driven by App Store policy rather than a client request; the matching backend account-deletion behaviour is required in CAP-ID. iOS-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Sign in with Apple is offered\n  Given the app offers Google sign-in\n  When the viewer reaches any sign-in screen\n  Then Sign in with Apple is presented as an equivalent option, as required by App Store policy\n\nScenario: Google sign-in completes in-app\n  Given a viewer chooses Google sign-in\n  When they complete the Google authentication flow\n  Then they return to the app signed in, with the same account and entitlements as on other platforms\n\nScenario: Session persists across restarts\n  Given a signed-in viewer force-quits the app\n  When they reopen it\n  Then they remain signed in without re-entering credentials\n\nScenario: Password reset reachable in-app\n  Given a viewer has forgotten their password\n  When they start the reset flow from the iOS sign-in screen\n  Then they can complete the CAP-ID reset flow and sign in with the new password\n\nScenario: In-app account deletion (App Store policy requirement, platform-driven addition)\n  Given App Store policy requires account deletion where account creation is offered\n  When a signed-in viewer chooses to delete their account from settings\n  Then the deletion flow can be initiated inside the app and the account is removed by the CAP-ID account-deletion behaviour","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-04","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"Purchase path on iOS (scoping decision: In-App Purchase or purchase on web)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to pay for the film and get immediate permanent access from my iPhone, so that nothing blocks me from watching at launch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02 pay-per-view; 26:11 buy-to-own, no rental); Assumption - client to confirm (App Store purchase-path policy decision below)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (iOS delivery aspects)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-02, PLAT-IOS-03, CAP-PAY, PLAT-WEB purchase path story (a web purchase flow must exist for entitlement recognition on iOS under either path)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on App Store policy for digital content; two mutually exclusive integration paths with different cost profiles; entitlement sync with the shared CAP-PAY service either way."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"App Store policy for paid digital content requires that purchases made inside the app go through Apple In-App Purchase, which carries an Apple commission. The alternative is the established purchase-on-web pattern (used by leading streaming apps), where the iOS app plays already-purchased content only and the purchase itself happens on the web. Both paths are scoped below; the choice is a client scoping decision with direct cost impact (commission on iOS-originated sales versus moving iOS conversion to the web), and this pack does not decide it. Capability ACs from CAP-PAY apply on this platform regardless of path. iOS-specific scenarios:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: In-app purchase completes (applies if the In-App Purchase path is chosen)\n  Given a signed-in viewer in the US on the film detail screen\n  When they complete the purchase through Apple In-App Purchase\n  Then payment is confirmed, the entitlement is recorded in the shared entitlement service, and the film is immediately playable\n\nScenario: Failed in-app purchase grants no access (In-App Purchase path)\n  Given a viewer whose in-app payment fails or is cancelled\n  When they return to the detail screen\n  Then no entitlement exists, no charge stands, and a clear retry message is shown\n\nScenario: No in-app payment offered (applies if the purchase-on-web path is chosen)\n  Given purchases are made on the web only\n  When a viewer without an entitlement views the film detail screen\n  Then no in-app payment control is shown\n\nScenario: Unentitled-viewer copy matches the reviewed wording (purchase-on-web path)\n  Given agreed wording for unentitled viewers exists, owned by the certification story PLAT-IOS-06 as an Apple-review external dependency\n  When a viewer without an entitlement views the film detail screen\n  Then the copy shown matches the agreed reviewed wording exactly\n\nScenario: Web purchase is recognised on iOS (both paths)\n  Given a viewer purchased the film on the web\n  When they sign in to the iOS app with the same account\n  Then the film shows as owned and is immediately playable\n\nScenario: Permanent access after purchase (both paths)\n  Given a viewer purchased the film more than 30 days ago\n  When they open the app and sign in\n  Then the film remains playable with no expiry, per the buy-to-own model","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-05","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"iOS player with FairPlay playback","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the film to play smoothly on my iPhone at the best quality my device and network allow, so that watching feels like a premium streaming service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 16:49 content protection; 23:34 4K with adaptive step-down; 24:54 captions benchmark; 39:34 pause and finish later) + Allion scoping decision (register decisions 2, 5, 14)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (iOS delivery aspects)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-04, CAP-PLAY, CAP-DRM, CAP-PIPE"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration of the managed platform player SDK or native AVFoundation player; FairPlay as the platform DRM variant; adaptive ladder behaviour across a wide iPhone hardware range; interruption handling."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY and CAP-DRM apply on this platform (including entitlement check before playback, adaptive ladder and step-down behaviour, concurrent-screens limit at playback start, geo gate at playback start, caption content, and watermarking). iOS-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: FairPlay license acquired before playback\n  Given an entitled viewer starts the film\n  When playback initialises\n  Then a FairPlay license is acquired and playback starts only with a valid license\n\nScenario: Rendition selection capped at device capability\n  Given the adaptive ladder spans 4K down to SD\n  When the film plays on a given iPhone model\n  Then the player selects renditions no higher than the device display supports, with step-down under constrained bandwidth per the CAP-PLAY adaptive-ladder acceptance criteria\n\nScenario: Captions and SDH through the iOS player\n  Given the title carries multiple subtitle languages and an SDH track\n  When the viewer opens the player caption menu\n  Then they can select any available language or SDH, and rendering honours the iOS system caption appearance settings\n\nScenario: Pause, quit, and resume\n  Given a viewer pauses the film and force-quits the app\n  When they reopen the app and press Play\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position\n\nScenario: Interruption handling\n  Given the film is playing\n  When a phone call or other system audio interruption occurs\n  Then playback pauses automatically and can be resumed from the same position afterwards\n\nScenario: Protected content excluded from screen capture\n  Given FairPlay-protected playback is active\n  When the viewer attempts a screen recording or screenshot of the player\n  Then the protected video frames are not captured","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-06","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":12,"title":"App Store submission and certification (US storefront)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the iOS app approved and live on the US App Store ahead of launch, so that viewers can install it the moment the film is released."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Craig, 8:18, traditional streaming app on mobile) + Jul 1 call (John, 33:16-33:49, stress testing in month 4-5) + Allion scoping decision; US-only per Jun 22 call and register decision 10"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-01, PLAT-IOS-02, PLAT-IOS-03, PLAT-IOS-04, PLAT-IOS-05"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on Apple review timelines and guideline interpretation (notably the purchase path from PLAT-IOS-04, including ownership of the unentitled-viewer wording review if the purchase-on-web path is chosen); privacy disclosure preparation; resubmission cycles are outside our control and need schedule buffer."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Apple approval is the story-level outcome; the scenarios below are limited to what the delivery team controls."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Submission checklist complete and build submitted with buffer\n  Given the app implements the purchase path selected in PLAT-IOS-04\n  When the submission checklist is worked through (purchase-path guideline mapping, Sign in with Apple, privacy labels, US storefront configuration)\n  Then every checklist item is complete and the build is submitted for App Store review with schedule buffer for at least one resubmission cycle\n\nScenario: US storefront only\n  Given V1 is US-only\n  When the app is published\n  Then availability is restricted to the US App Store storefront\n\nScenario: Privacy disclosures are accurate\n  Given the App Store requires privacy labels and a privacy policy link\n  When the store listing is reviewed against the app's actual data collection\n  Then the declared data types match the implementation\n\nScenario: Sign in with Apple present at review\n  Given the app offers Google sign-in\n  When Apple reviews the sign-in options\n  Then Sign in with Apple is present and functional, satisfying the applicable guideline\n\nScenario: Distributable build available for the load-test window\n  Given full-journey stress testing is planned for months 4-5\n  When the test window opens\n  Then a distributable iOS build supporting the complete sign-in, purchase, and playback journey is available to the test team","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-01","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Android app shell and navigation","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a native Android app that installs and opens reliably on my phone, so that I can reach the film and my account from the device I already use."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 42:39 \"You still got to build the app for them to watch it\"); Jun 22 call (device scope)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF (API environments)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New native build (first Android surface); platform multiplier (one of six client surfaces); Android device and OS-version fragmentation"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Note: minimum supported Android version and tablet layout support are Assumption - client to confirm."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Fresh install and first open\n  Given the app is installed from Google Play on a supported device\n  When the viewer opens the app for the first time\n  Then the landing screen is displayed without requiring sign-in\n\nScenario: Minimum OS version support\n  Given a device running the agreed minimum Android version (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the viewer runs the core journey (landing, detail, sign-in, purchase entry, playback)\n  Then every step functions without crash or blocked screen\n\nScenario: Network loss handling\n  Given the app is open on any screen\n  When network connectivity is lost\n  Then a clear offline message with a retry action is shown and the app does not crash\n\nScenario: Rotation and state\n  Given the viewer is on any core screen on a phone\n  When the device is rotated\n  Then the layout adapts and the screen state (scroll position, entered text) is retained","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-02","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Landing and film detail on Android","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to open the app onto a landing screen and view a film detail page, so that I can move from interest to purchase in a straight line."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, selection UI built \"in the context of having more\" titles); Allion scoping decision (register item 7, landing plus detail, no catalog grid in A)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (Android surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-01; PLAT-AND-03 (signed-in purchase entry); CAP-CON (published title metadata and artwork); CAP-PAY (price and ownership state)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New UI build; layout designed to extend to Option B rows without rework; artwork and metadata rendering across screen sizes"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Landing shows the featured film\n  Given one published film exists (Option A)\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then the landing screen shows that film with artwork, title, and synopsis, and only published titles appear\n\nScenario: Film detail page\n  Given the viewer selects the featured film\n  When the detail page opens\n  Then it shows artwork, title, synopsis, credits, price, and the viewer's ownership state for the film\n\nScenario: Owned film shows watch action\n  Given the viewer has already purchased the film (buy-to-own, permanent access)\n  When they open the detail page\n  Then a watch action is shown in place of the price\n\nScenario: Straight-line path to purchase\n  Given a signed-in viewer who does not own the film\n  When they open the detail page and follow the purchase entry point presented for the selected billing path\n  Then the purchase journey defined by that path (PLAT-AND-04) starts with no intermediate dead ends, or, where Play policy does not permit a direct purchase action, the policy-compliant purchase messaging is shown","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-03","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Account on Android","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to create and access my account on my Android phone, so that my purchase and playback follow me on this device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register item 8); Jun 22 call (email and password baseline)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (Android surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-01; CAP-ID"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with CAP-ID services; native Google sign-in integration; Apple sign-in on Android runs as a web-based flow"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID apply on this platform. Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Google sign-in via native flow\n  Given a viewer with a Google account on the device\n  When they choose Google sign-in\n  Then the native Google account flow completes and the viewer is signed in\n\nScenario: Apple sign-in on Android\n  Given a viewer who registered with Apple sign-in on another device\n  When they choose Apple sign-in on Android\n  Then the web-based Apple flow completes and they reach the same account\n\nScenario: Email sign-up and password reset entry\n  Given a new viewer on the sign-up screen\n  When they register with email and password, or request a password reset\n  Then the CAP-ID flows complete from within the app\n\nScenario: Session persists across restarts\n  Given a signed-in viewer force-closes the app\n  When they reopen it\n  Then they remain signed in\n\nScenario: Sign out\n  Given a signed-in viewer\n  When they sign out\n  Then the session is cleared on the device and protected screens require sign-in again","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-04","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Purchase path on Android (billing path open)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to buy the film from my Android phone, so that I can start watching without switching devices."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02 pay-per-view; 25:59-26:12 buy-to-own; 37:09-37:14 no free trial); Assumption - client to confirm (Google Play billing policy path)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (Android surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-03; CAP-PAY"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Google Play policy; Play Billing service on Path 1); entitlement reconciliation between Play purchases and the Stripe-backed entitlement record (Path 1); purchase journey leaves the app (Path 2); geo enforcement mechanism differs by path"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Open decision (client to confirm, both paths scoped, neither selected)","value":"Google Play policy for digital content may require in-app purchases to use Google Play Billing. Both paths below are presented for costing; the choice is a client decision and the policy position must be re-verified against current Play policy at build time."},{"label":"","value":"| Path | What it means | Cost impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1. Google Play Billing in-app | Purchase completes inside the app through Play Billing | Additional integration and reconciliation build; Google service fee applies per transaction (rate per Google's current fee schedule, to confirm); refunds flow through Play as well as Stripe records; geo enforcement shifts from the geo-IP gate at checkout to Play store-country controls, to be validated against the US-only requirement |\n| 2. Web purchase pattern | Purchase completes on the web (Stripe, register item 3); the app detects the entitlement and plays the owned film | Lower app build and no store fee; purchase journey leaves the app (conversion impact); in-app purchase messaging is constrained by Play policy |"},{"label":"","value":"Option B note: under Path 1, Play Billing requires per-title in-app product creation and price management in Play Console for the full catalog and each weekly release, an integration and recurring operating cost beyond the Option A impact. Path 2 has no equivalent per-title store cost."},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PAY apply on this platform as follows. The entitlement, buy-to-own (permanent access), and no-free-trial ACs apply on both paths. The Stripe charge-flow and geo-IP-gate-at-payment ACs apply under Path 2 (web purchase). Under Path 1, Google Play Billing substitutes the charge flow and each Play purchase reconciles to the Stripe-backed entitlement record; geo enforcement under Path 1 relies on Play store-country controls rather than the geo-IP gate at checkout (see the Path 1 cost impact). Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitlement active after purchase on the selected path\n  Given a signed-in viewer without the film\n  When a purchase completes on the selected billing path\n  Then the entitlement is active and the film is playable on this device without reinstalling or re-signing in\n\nScenario: Play Billing purchase success (Path 1, if selected)\n  Given Path 1 is the selected billing path\n  When the viewer completes the Play Billing flow\n  Then the Play purchase is recorded against the platform entitlement record and both stay consistent\n\nScenario: Play Billing purchase declined (Path 1, if selected)\n  Given Path 1 is the selected billing path\n  When the payment is declined in the Play flow\n  Then no entitlement is granted and the viewer sees a clear failure message with a retry option\n\nScenario: Web purchase appears in the app (Path 2, if selected)\n  Given Path 2 is the selected billing path and the viewer purchased the film on the web\n  When they open the app and sign in with the same account\n  Then the film shows as owned and is playable\n\nScenario: Policy-compliant purchase messaging (Path 2, if selected)\n  Given Path 2 is the selected billing path\n  When a viewer without the film views the detail page\n  Then the purchase messaging shown matches the wording approved for Play policy compliance","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-05","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Film playback on Android (Widevine)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the film to play smoothly on my Android phone at the best quality my device supports, so that watching feels like a premium service."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (7:39 and 23:34, quality; John, 16:49 anti-piracy; John, 24:54 captions; John, 39:34 pause and resume); Allion scoping decision (register items 5, 14)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (Android surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY (entitlement record); CAP-PLAY; CAP-DRM; CAP-PIPE"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the managed platform player and SDK (Bunny Stream reference, vendor-agnostic); Widevine security-level variance across the Android device base; adaptive ladder 4K down to SD; interruption and lifecycle handling"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY and CAP-DRM apply on this platform (entitlement check, pause and resume, trick play, caption selection with SDH, concurrent-screens check at playback start, geo-IP check at playback start, forensic watermarking, and the QoE targets, which are assumed pending client confirmation). Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Widevine L1 device reaches the top rendition\n  Given an entitled viewer on a device with Widevine L1\n  And a test network profile that sustains the 4K rendition bitrate (profile per the assumed QoE targets, Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When playback starts\n  Then a Widevine license is issued and the highest rendition delivered is 4K\n\nScenario: Device below Widevine L1 is capped per DRM policy\n  Given an entitled viewer on a device below Widevine L1\n  And the same test network profile\n  When playback starts\n  Then a license is issued and the highest rendition delivered does not exceed the capped level (cap level: Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Secure output enforcement\n  Given playback is in progress\n  When screen capture or an unprotected external display output is attempted\n  Then the protected video is not exposed, per the Widevine output rules\n\nScenario: Incoming call interruption\n  Given playback is in progress\n  When a phone call interrupts the app\n  Then playback pauses, and on return the viewer can resume from the same position\n\nScenario: App backgrounded\n  Given playback is in progress\n  When the app moves to the background\n  Then playback pauses and the position is retained on return\n\nScenario: Network change without failure\n  Given playback is in progress on Wi-Fi\n  When the device switches to cellular\n  Then the adaptive ladder adjusts and playback continues without an error state\n\nScenario: System caption preferences respected\n  Given the viewer has Android system caption settings configured\n  When captions are enabled in the player\n  Then caption rendering honors the system text-size and style preferences","scenarioCount":7,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-06","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Google Play certification and release","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the Android app to pass Google Play review and release in a controlled way, so that launch day is not blocked by a store rejection."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal and John, 42:21-42:39, app must be released through the store); Assumption - client to confirm (store policy requirements as at submission time)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-01 to PLAT-AND-05 (Option A); plus PLAT-AND-08 to PLAT-AND-10 under Option B"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Google review timelines and policy changes); release engineering (signing, test tracks, staged rollout); billing-path compliance linked to PLAT-AND-04"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Google review approval itself is Google's decision; it is tracked as the release milestone rather than a pass/fail acceptance criterion. The scenarios below cover what the team can verify before and after submission."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Pre-submission launch checklist passes\n  Given a release candidate build prepared for submission\n  When the pre-submission Play launch checklist is completed (policy compliance, data safety form, content rating, target API level, billing declaration)\n  Then every checklist item passes and the build is submitted to Google review\n\nScenario: Store declarations consistent\n  Given the Play Console data safety form and content rating are completed\n  When the submitted build is inspected against them\n  Then the declared data practices and rating match actual app behavior\n\nScenario: Target API level compliance\n  Given the Play target API level requirement current at submission\n  When the release build is checked\n  Then the app meets or exceeds that requirement\n\nScenario: DRM playback on the store-signed build\n  Given the release build signed through Play App Signing\n  When an entitled viewer starts playback on that build\n  Then a Widevine license is issued and playback starts\n\nScenario: Controlled rollout\n  Given a closed testing track release has been validated\n  When the production release begins\n  Then it uses a staged rollout that can be halted before full availability\n\nScenario: Billing path matches the decision\n  Given the client has selected a billing path (PLAT-AND-04)\n  When the build is submitted\n  Then the purchase behavior in the build matches the selected path and its Play policy obligations","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-07","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":12,"title":"Android client readiness for the premiere surge","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the Android app to behave predictably when 100,000 concurrent viewers hit the platform, so that launch-night load does not turn into client-side failures."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16 set the cap to 100,000 concurrent; 35:09 \"every button that the person touches\"); Allion scoping decision (register item 16; applying the 100K bar to Option B is Assumption - client to confirm)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-01 to PLAT-AND-05; CAP-INF (load and surge protection)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Full-journey simulated load profile, not streaming only; client resilience engineering (retry, backoff, error states); coordination with the month 4-5 stress-testing window (register item 17)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"The 100K full-journey load scenarios themselves are defined in CAP-INF. Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Android journeys included in the premiere load profile\n  Given the CAP-INF premiere load simulation\n  When the profile is executed\n  Then Android journeys are represented, including sign-in storm, purchase burst with declines, playback start surge, trick play, quit and resume, and kicked-out sessions\n\nScenario: API failure under surge\n  Given an API call fails or times out during peak load\n  When the app retries\n  Then it uses backoff, shows a readable message if retries are exhausted, and does not enter a crash or retry loop\n\nScenario: Concurrent-screens rejection handled\n  Given the account is already at its concurrent-screens limit (configurable, default 2)\n  When the viewer starts playback on the Android app\n  Then playback is refused with a clear message and the app returns to the detail page in a working state\n\nScenario: Responsive under degraded latency\n  Given API response times degrade during the load window\n  When the viewer navigates the app\n  Then loading states are shown and the app does not freeze or force close","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-01","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Channel shell and foundation","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want a Roku SceneGraph channel shell with app lifecycle, session handling, and platform API connectivity, so that every Roku viewer feature builds on a stable, certifiable foundation."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal, 7:39, Roku named in the top US device set; John, 42:39, \"create all of the places\" a viewer would expect) + Jun 22 call (Craig, 8:18, TV app expectation)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF (environments and APIs), CAP-ID (session model)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build in SceneGraph/BrightScript (specialist skill set); Roku device range includes low-memory hardware; shell must satisfy Roku certification behaviors from the start, including deep-link launch handling if required for this channel type"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Channel launches to the landing screen\n  Given the channel is installed on a supported Roku device\n  When the viewer opens the channel\n  Then the landing screen displays and accepts remote input\n\nScenario: Signed-in session persists across relaunch\n  Given a viewer previously signed in on this Roku device\n  When they exit and relaunch the channel\n  Then they remain signed in without re-entering an activation code (CAP-ID session ACs apply)\n\nScenario: Launch with no network connectivity\n  Given the Roku device has no network connection\n  When the viewer opens the channel\n  Then a readable error with a retry action displays instead of a blank screen or crash\n\nScenario: Platform APIs unreachable\n  Given the channel is open and the platform APIs stop responding\n  When the viewer navigates or retries\n  Then the channel shows a retry state and does not crash or freeze\n\nScenario: Channel launch via a Roku deep link (Assumption - client to confirm whether Roku certification requires deep linking for this channel type)\n  Given the channel is launched through a Roku deep link referencing the film\n  When the channel opens\n  Then the channel launches directly to that film's detail screen and remote navigation works as normal","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-02","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Landing and film detail screens","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a landing screen and a film detail screen on my Roku, so that I can select the film and start the pay-then-watch journey from my TV."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, one film with selection UI \"built in the context of having more\") + Allion scoping decision (landing page plus detail page, no catalog grid in Option A)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (Roku portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-ROKU-01, CAP-CON (published metadata and artwork)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; TV-safe layout and artwork rendering across Roku output resolutions; layout must extend to Option B catalog rows without rework"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Landing screen shows the published film\n  Given a film is published in the console\n  When the viewer opens the channel\n  Then the landing screen shows the film with poster artwork, title, and synopsis from published metadata\n\nScenario: Unpublished films are hidden\n  Given a film is unpublished\n  When the viewer opens the landing screen\n  Then that film does not appear anywhere in the channel\n\nScenario: Detail screen for an unowned film\n  Given the film has not been purchased on this account\n  When the viewer opens the film detail screen\n  Then the detail screen shows the price and a purchase action\n\nScenario: Detail screen for an owned film\n  Given the film is owned on this account\n  When the viewer opens the film detail screen\n  Then the detail screen shows a Watch action and no purchase action\n\nScenario: Focus lands on the primary action\n  Given the viewer arrives on the landing or detail screen\n  When the screen renders\n  Then remote focus sits on the primary action without extra key presses\n\nScenario: Layout renders across Roku output resolutions\n  Given Roku devices outputting 720p, 1080p, and 4K\n  When each renders the landing and detail screens\n  Then artwork and text display without clipping or distortion","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-03","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"TV activation-code sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to sign in on Roku by entering a short code on my phone or computer, so that I do not have to type my email and password with the remote."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (auth set includes TV activation-code flow)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (Roku portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (activation-code capability ACs apply on this platform), PLAT-ROKU-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the CAP-ID activation service; two-device pairing UX on TV; code expiry and retry handling under premiere-night sign-in load (load bar owned by CAP-INF)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Activation code displayed on TV\n  Given a signed-out viewer selects sign in on Roku\n  When the activation screen opens\n  Then a short code and the web address to enter it are displayed on screen\n\nScenario: Channel signs in once the code is confirmed\n  Given the activation code is showing on the TV\n  When the viewer confirms the code on their phone or computer\n  Then the Roku channel signs in automatically without further remote input\n\nScenario: Expired code is replaced\n  Given the activation code has passed its expiry (expiry rules per CAP-ID)\n  When the viewer is still on the activation screen\n  Then a new code is offered and the expired code no longer works\n\nScenario: Sign out from the channel\n  Given a signed-in viewer selects the channel's sign-out action\n  When they confirm sign out\n  Then the session ends on this device and the activation screen is shown on next sign-in","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-04","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Remote-control navigation and focus","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to reach every channel screen and action with the standard Roku remote, so that navigation feels native to my TV."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Craig, 8:18, TV app expectation) + Allion scoping decision (TV navigation baseline). Jul 1 call (John, 35:09) evidences the remote actions that must exist (play, pause, rewind, exit, re-enter); the load dimension of those actions is owned by CAP-INF."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-ROKU-01, PLAT-ROKU-02"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Focus management across all screens; back-stack behavior must follow Roku conventions; navigation behavior is checked at Roku certification"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Every actionable element is reachable by d-pad\n  Given any channel screen\n  When the viewer navigates with the directional pad only\n  Then every actionable element can receive focus and be activated with OK\n\nScenario: Focus is always visible\n  Given the viewer moves focus on any screen\n  When an element gains focus\n  Then a clearly visible focus state distinguishes it from unfocused elements\n\nScenario: Back key follows Roku convention\n  Given the viewer is on a screen below the landing screen\n  When they press Back\n  Then the channel returns to the previous screen\n  And pressing Back on the landing screen follows the Roku exit convention\n\nScenario: No focus traps\n  Given any screen state, including error and loading states\n  When the viewer navigates with the remote\n  Then focus can always be moved away (no state requires a channel restart)\n\nScenario: Home key is never blocked\n  Given any channel state, including active playback\n  When the viewer presses the Home key\n  Then the channel exits immediately per Roku system behavior","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-05","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Film playback on Roku","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to watch my purchased film on Roku with full player and trick-play controls, so that the TV viewing experience matches the premium promise."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, pay then watch, pause and finish later; Mishal + John, 23:34, 4K with adaptive step-down; John, 24:54, captions benchmarked to Apple TV Plus; John, 35:09, trick-play actions under load)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (Roku portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY (capability ACs apply on this platform, including geo gate, concurrent-screens check, and resume), CAP-DRM (Roku-supported DRM variant), CAP-PAY (entitlement check), PLAT-ROKU-03, PLAT-ROKU-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration of the Roku native player with the managed platform streams; DRM variant on Roku hardware; trick-play UX via remote; capability differs across Roku models (4K vs HD-only devices)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY and CAP-DRM apply on this platform. Roku-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: 4K playback on a 4K-capable Roku\n  Given an entitled viewer on a 4K-capable Roku with sufficient bandwidth\n  When playback starts\n  Then the stream reaches 4K and steps down the adaptive ladder when bandwidth drops\n\nScenario: Best available quality on an HD-only Roku\n  Given an entitled viewer on an HD-only Roku model\n  When playback starts\n  Then the film plays at the best rung up to 1080p without error\n\nScenario: Trick-play via the Roku remote\n  Given a film is playing\n  When the viewer uses play/pause, rewind, fast-forward, and instant replay on the remote\n  Then each control responds and the scrub bar shows the current position\n\nScenario: Pause, exit, and resume later on Roku\n  Given a viewer pauses and exits the channel mid-film\n  When they return and select the film\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position (resume rules per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Caption selection and SDH on Roku\n  Given a film with uploaded subtitle tracks (per CAP-CON)\n  When the viewer opens caption options during playback\n  Then available languages and SDH tracks can be selected with the remote\n  And the channel respects the Roku system caption settings\n\nScenario: Protected stream on Roku\n  Given the film is protected per CAP-DRM\n  When playback starts on Roku\n  Then the stream plays only through the Roku-supported DRM variant and is not exposed unprotected","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-06","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Purchase path on Roku (in-channel Roku Pay vs purchase on web, decision open)","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a clear way to buy the film from my Roku, so that I can go from selection to watching without leaving the couch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02, Stripe pay-per-view, buy-to-own; John, 39:34, straight-line pay-then-watch conversion). Roku Pay policy constraint: Assumption - client to confirm."},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (Roku portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY (entitlement capability ACs apply), PLAT-ROKU-02, PLAT-ROKU-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on Roku platform policy; potential second payment integration (Roku Pay alongside Stripe) with entitlement reconciliation; per-sale cost model differs between the two paths"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"","value":"Decision flag (client to decide, not decided here): Roku platform policy generally requires Roku Pay for purchases completed inside a channel (Assumption - client to confirm against current Roku policy at design lock). Two delivery paths are presented:\n- Path 1, in-channel Roku Pay: purchase completes on the TV. Roku is understood to apply a platform revenue share to in-channel transactions (Assumption - rate and applicability to confirm against current Roku terms). Requires reconciling Roku Pay purchases with the Stripe-based entitlement record in CAP-PAY.\n- Path 2, purchase on web, watch on Roku: the channel directs the viewer to the website to buy. Single Stripe integration, no Roku revenue share, but the TV purchase journey gains a device switch.\n- Cost impact: Path 1 adds an integration plus a per-sale platform fee (subject to the revenue-share assumption above); Path 2 keeps one payment stack but lengthens the TV conversion path. Estimate both; the choice sits with the client."},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Entitlement purchased anywhere is honored on Roku (both paths)\n  Given a viewer purchased the film on web or mobile\n  When they sign in and open the film detail screen on Roku\n  Then the film shows as owned and playback can start without a second purchase\n\nScenario: Path 1 - purchase completes through Roku Pay\n  Given the in-channel path is selected and the viewer chooses buy on the detail screen\n  When they confirm the purchase through Roku Pay\n  Then the purchase completes on the TV and playback is available immediately\n\nScenario: Path 1 - Roku Pay purchase reconciles to the account entitlement\n  Given a purchase completed through Roku Pay\n  When the viewer signs in on any other supported device\n  Then the film shows as owned there too (single entitlement record per CAP-PAY)\n\nScenario: Path 1 - failed Roku Pay purchase grants no access\n  Given a Roku Pay purchase fails or is cancelled\n  When the viewer returns to the detail screen\n  Then no access is granted and a readable message explains the outcome\n\nScenario: Path 2 - channel directs the viewer to buy on the web\n  Given the purchase-on-web path is selected and the film is not owned\n  When the viewer opens the detail screen\n  Then clear instructions and the web address for purchase are shown in place of an in-channel payment\n\nScenario: Path 2 - web purchase is reflected on return\n  Given the viewer completes the purchase on the web\n  When they return to the detail screen on Roku\n  Then the film shows as owned and Watch is available without re-signing in","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-07","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":12,"title":"Roku channel certification and store publication","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want the channel to pass Roku certification and publish to the Roku Channel Store ahead of launch, so that store review does not put the premiere date at risk."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 33:16-33:49, six-month launch window, build scoped four to five months). Certification lead times and criteria: Assumption - client to confirm; validated against Roku's current certification checklist at submission."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-ROKU-01 through PLAT-ROKU-06, CAP-INF (premiere load readiness feeds the same launch window)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Roku review timelines and certification criteria sit outside our control); possible resubmission cycles (schedule contingency for at least one resubmission cycle is held in the delivery plan); certification checks performance on the lowest-supported hardware; schedule risk inside the six-month plan"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"","value":"Delivery-plan note: submission scheduling, including contingency for at least one resubmission cycle before launch, is covered in the delivery plan and timeline section of this pack. The acceptance criteria below cover product behavior only."},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Pre-submission certification checks pass\n  Given the channel build is feature-complete for Option A scope\n  When Roku's published certification checks (static analysis, performance, and deep-link handling per PLAT-ROKU-01) are run\n  Then all checks pass before submission to the Channel Store\n\nScenario: Performance on the lowest supported Roku model\n  Given the lowest-specification Roku model in the supported device set (model list: Assumption - client to confirm at design lock)\n  When the channel is launched and a film is played\n  Then the channel runs without crash and playback starts successfully","scenarioCount":2,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-01","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Fire TV app shell and packaging","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a Fire TV app I can install from the Amazon Appstore, so that I can watch on my Fire TV device the same way I use other streaming apps."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Allion recap, 28:12; John, 42:39 \"you still got to build the app for them to watch it if they want it\") + Jun 22 call (device coverage)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF (service endpoints)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New native TV build on Fire OS (Android-based); platform multiplier (one of six V1 surfaces); device fragmentation across Fire TV Stick generations and Fire TV Edition televisions."},{"label":"Assumptions","value":"Supported device baseline: Fire OS versions covering the top-selling Fire TV Stick generations and Fire TV Edition televisions needed to meet the 80 percent US market coverage target (Jun 22 call); the concrete device and OS-version list is to be proposed at estimation. Assumption - client to confirm. PLAT-FTV-04 and PLAT-FTV-07 reference this baseline."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: App installs and launches on supported devices\n  Given a Fire TV device within the supported device baseline (see Assumptions)\n  When the viewer installs the app from the Amazon Appstore and opens it\n  Then the app launches to the landing screen without error\n\nScenario: Cold start performance\n  Given the app is not running\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then the landing screen is interactive within 5 seconds of launch (Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Resume from background\n  Given the app is backgrounded via the Home button\n  When the viewer reopens the app\n  Then the app restores the previous screen and signed-in state\n\nScenario: Network loss on launch\n  Given the device has no internet connection\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then a clear offline message with a retry action is shown instead of a blank screen","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-02","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Landing and film detail screens","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a landing screen and a film detail screen on Fire TV, so that I can see what is available and choose to watch it."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"you still need to build the UI for a person to make a selection, and you can build that in the context of having more\") + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (browse and discovery, Fire TV surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-FTV-01, CAP-CON (published title metadata)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New 10-foot UI build; layout must present one film in Option A while structurally accommodating more titles; integration with catalog service."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Landing shows the available film\n  Given at least one film is published\n  When the viewer reaches the landing screen\n  Then the film is shown with poster, title, and short description in a layout that supports additional titles later\n\nScenario: Only published titles appear\n  Given a film is unpublished in the content console\n  When the viewer views the landing screen\n  Then that film is not shown\n\nScenario: Film detail screen\n  Given the viewer selects a film\n  When the detail screen opens\n  Then title, description, artwork, and price are shown at 10-foot readable sizes\n\nScenario: Detail screen reflects entitlement state\n  Given the viewer has purchased the film\n  When the detail screen opens\n  Then the primary action is Play or Resume instead of a purchase action","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-03","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"TV activation-code sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to sign in on Fire TV by entering a short code on my phone or computer, so that I do not have to type my credentials with a TV remote."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (sign-in, Fire TV surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (TV activation)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the CAP-ID activation service (logic is capability-side); TV presentation and polling behaviour only; fallback on-device entry path."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID (TV activation) apply on this platform. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Activation code displayed\n  Given a signed-out viewer chooses sign in\n  When the activation screen opens\n  Then a short code and the activation web address are displayed clearly at 10-foot sizes\n\nScenario: Automatic sign-in after approval\n  Given the viewer approves the code on another device\n  When approval completes\n  Then the Fire TV app signs in without further remote input and returns to the prior screen\n\nScenario: Expired code refresh\n  Given the displayed code has expired\n  When the viewer is still on the activation screen\n  Then a new code is issued and displayed without restarting the flow\n\nScenario: Fallback on-device sign-in\n  Given the viewer chooses to enter credentials on the TV instead\n  When they use the on-screen keyboard\n  Then email and password sign-in completes per CAP-ID rules\n\nScenario: Sign out on device\n  Given a signed-in viewer opens settings\n  When they choose sign out\n  Then the session ends on this device only","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-04","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Playback on Fire TV","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to watch my purchased film on Fire TV at up to 4K, so that I get the best quality my device and connection support."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal + John, 7:39 and 23:34 on 4K with 1080p majority; John, 16:49 on anti-piracy; John, 39:34 \"pause it and watch it later and finish later\")"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (playback, Fire TV surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY, CAP-DRM, CAP-PIPE (managed platform player support on Fire OS, validation spike), PLAT-FTV-03, PLAT-FTV-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Platform DRM variant on Fire OS (Widevine or PlayReady per the managed platform, to be confirmed in the CAP-PIPE validation spike); 4K capability detection across the supported device baseline (PLAT-FTV-01), where older sticks cap below 4K; dependency on managed platform SDK support for Fire OS; caption rendering at TV sizes."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY (playback, pause/resume, adaptive ladder, concurrent-screen check) and CAP-DRM apply on this platform. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: 4K playback on a 4K-capable device\n  Given an entitled viewer on a 4K-capable Fire TV device from the supported device baseline (PLAT-FTV-01) with sufficient bandwidth\n  When playback starts\n  Then the stream is protected by the platform DRM variant per CAP-DRM and reaches the 4K rendition of the ladder\n\nScenario: Ladder cap on a non-4K device\n  Given an entitled viewer on a Fire TV device from the supported device baseline that does not support 4K output\n  When playback starts\n  Then the stream plays at the highest rendition the device supports without error\n\nScenario: Pause, quit, and resume on the same device\n  Given the viewer pauses and fully exits the app mid-film\n  When they relaunch the app and reopen the film\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position per CAP-PLAY\n\nScenario: Concurrent-screen limit message\n  Given the account has reached its configured concurrent-screens limit\n  When the viewer starts playback on Fire TV\n  Then a clear limit message is shown and the app returns to the detail screen\n\nScenario: Caption selection by remote\n  Given a film with multiple subtitle languages\n  When the viewer opens the caption menu during playback\n  Then languages and SDH options are selectable with the remote and render legibly at TV sizes","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-05","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Remote and focus navigation","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want every screen of the Fire TV app to work with the standard remote, so that I can browse, buy, and control playback without a pointer or touchscreen."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (TV platform baseline); Jul 1 call (John, 35:09) as supporting evidence that these playback control actions must exist"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-FTV-01, PLAT-FTV-02, PLAT-FTV-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Focus-engine work is per-platform by nature; Fire TV remote button conventions and back-stack behaviour; no reuse from pointer-based surfaces."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Full D-pad reachability\n  Given any screen in the app\n  When the viewer navigates with the directional pad\n  Then every interactive element is reachable and shows a visible focus state, with no focus traps\n\nScenario: Back button behaviour\n  Given the viewer is on the film detail screen\n  When they press Back\n  Then the app returns to the landing screen, and pressing Back again exits per Fire TV platform conventions\n\nScenario: Media buttons control playback\n  Given a film is playing\n  When the viewer presses play/pause, rewind, or fast-forward on the remote\n  Then the player responds with the matching action, including short skip back\n\nScenario: Trick-play under load conditions\n  Given playback is in progress\n  When the viewer scrubs, skips, and pauses repeatedly\n  Then playback resumes within 5 seconds without requiring an app restart (recovery time Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-06","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Purchase path on Fire TV","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to buy the film from my Fire TV, so that I can go from seeing the film to watching it without friction."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02 pay-per-view; 25:59-26:12 buy-to-own, no rental) + Assumption - client to confirm (Amazon Appstore monetization policy)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (payment, Fire TV surface)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY (entitlements), PLAT-FTV-02, PLAT-FTV-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency on Amazon Appstore policy for digital goods; two candidate purchase patterns with materially different cost and build profiles; potential second payment rail to reconcile with Stripe-based entitlements."},{"label":"Open point (client decision, both patterns priced in the estimate, this pack does not decide)","value":"- Pattern 1, Amazon In-App Purchasing: purchase completes inside the app using Amazon's billing. Compliant default for digital goods sold in-app. Amazon's revenue share applies to each sale (rate per Amazon's published terms; cost impact carried as a variable-cost line in the estimate). Adds a second entitlement source that CAP-PAY must reconcile with Stripe records.\n- Pattern 2, web purchase: the viewer completes payment on the web through Stripe, and the Fire TV app unlocks the entitlement after sign-in or refresh. Keeps Stripe as the single payment rail with no store revenue share, but adds conversion friction (viewer switches to another device to pay) and is subject to Amazon policy on directing users to external purchase. Policy compliance to be verified during certification (PLAT-FTV-07)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PAY (purchase, entitlement grant, failure handling, geo gate at payment) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific and hold under either pattern unless named."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Purchase unlocks playback on the TV\n  Given a signed-in viewer without an entitlement\n  When their purchase completes through the chosen pattern\n  Then the Fire TV app reflects the entitlement and Play is available without reinstalling or re-signing in\n\nScenario: Amazon In-App Purchasing pattern\n  Given the Amazon In-App Purchasing pattern is selected\n  When the viewer confirms the purchase with the remote\n  Then payment completes inside the app and the entitlement is recorded against the viewer account per CAP-PAY\n\nScenario: Web purchase pattern\n  Given the web purchase pattern is selected\n  When the viewer selects the purchase action on the TV\n  Then the app shows clear instructions for completing payment on the web, and the entitlement appears on the TV once payment succeeds\n\nScenario: Failed or cancelled payment\n  Given a payment fails or is cancelled\n  When the viewer returns to the detail screen\n  Then no access is granted and a clear, non-technical message is shown per CAP-PAY\n\nScenario: Price display consistency\n  Given a film with a configured price\n  When the detail screen is shown\n  Then the price displayed on Fire TV matches the configured price for the active purchase pattern","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-07","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":12,"title":"Amazon Appstore certification and submission","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the Fire TV app to pass Amazon Appstore submission and certification, so that viewers can install it when the film launches."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision + Assumption - client to confirm (Amazon review lead times are outside our control)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-FTV-01, PLAT-FTV-02, PLAT-FTV-03, PLAT-FTV-04, PLAT-FTV-05, PLAT-FTV-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Amazon review cycles and possible resubmission); monetization-policy compliance tied to the PLAT-FTV-06 pattern decision; certification must land inside the roughly 6 month launch window (Jul 1 call)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Submission package accepted\n  Given a release candidate build\n  When the app is submitted to the Amazon Appstore\n  Then the submission passes Amazon's automated and manual checks without policy findings\n\nScenario: Purchase-pattern policy compliance\n  Given the purchase pattern selected in PLAT-FTV-06\n  When Amazon reviews the app's monetization\n  Then the implementation is accepted under Amazon's digital-goods policy\n\nScenario: Rejection handling\n  Given Amazon rejects a submission\n  When the finding is received\n  Then the finding, fix, and resubmission are tracked so schedule impact against the launch window is visible\n\nScenario: Published listing\n  Given certification passes\n  When the listing goes live\n  Then the app is installable in the US storefront on the supported device baseline defined in PLAT-FTV-01","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-01","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Tizen app shell and store packaging","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the service available as an installable app on my Samsung TV, so that I can watch on the biggest screen in my home without extra hardware."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 42:39, \"you need to create all of the places that you would expect them to want to\"); Jun 22 call (Craig, 8:18, TV as a core surface); register decision 1 (Samsung Tizen in V1 device set)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF (platform APIs and environments)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (Tizen web app shell); platform multiplier (one of six V1 surfaces); Samsung packaging and signing toolchain as an external dependency"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Install from the Samsung app store\n  Given a Samsung TV on a supported Tizen version\n  When the viewer searches the Samsung app store and installs the app\n  Then the app installs and launches to the landing screen\n\nScenario: Cold start\n  Given the app is installed and the TV has a working connection\n  When the viewer launches the app from the Samsung home ribbon\n  Then the landing screen is interactive within 5 seconds of launch (Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: UI renders correctly on TV resolutions\n  Given the app is running on a 4K Samsung TV\n  When any screen in the app is displayed\n  Then layout, artwork, and text render without clipping or distortion at TV viewing distance\n\nScenario: Exit and relaunch\n  Given the viewer is anywhere in the app\n  When they press the remote Exit key and later relaunch the app\n  Then the app closes cleanly and relaunches without error","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-02","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Landing and film detail screens","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a landing screen and a film detail screen on my Samsung TV, so that I can find the film, see what it is, and start the purchase or playback journey."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, one film, selection UI \"in the context of having more\", no sorting or discovery in Option A); register decision 7 (landing page plus film detail page, no catalog grid in A)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (Samsung TV portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-01, CAP-CON (published title metadata and artwork)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (TV layouts); integration with catalog service; UI designed to extend to multiple titles without rework"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Landing screen presents the film\n  Given at least one published film exists\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then the landing screen shows the film with poster artwork, title, and a focused primary action\n\nScenario: Film detail screen\n  Given the viewer selects the film from the landing screen\n  When the detail screen opens\n  Then it shows poster, title, synopsis, price, and caption availability from the catalog service\n\nScenario: Unpublished titles are hidden\n  Given a title is unpublished in the content console\n  When the viewer uses the app\n  Then that title does not appear anywhere in the Samsung app\n\nScenario: Purchased state\n  Given the viewer already owns the film (entitlement per CAP-PAY)\n  When they open the film detail screen\n  Then the primary action is Play, and no price or purchase prompt is shown\n\nScenario: Layout holds with more titles\n  Given more than one published film exists\n  When the landing screen renders\n  Then each film is selectable and the layout extends without redesign","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-03","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"TV activation-code sign-in","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to sign in on my Samsung TV by entering a short code on my phone or computer, so that I do not have to type my full credentials with the remote."},{"label":"Source","value":"Register decision 8 (Allion scoping decision: TV activation-code flow); Jun 22 call (email and password baseline)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-02 (Samsung TV portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-01, CAP-ID (TV activation capability)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (capability ACs from CAP-ID apply; this story adds only the Tizen client); platform multiplier (same flow on Roku and Fire TV)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-ID (activation-code issue, expiry, and confirmation) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Activation code shown on the TV\n  Given the viewer chooses Sign in on the Samsung app\n  When the sign-in screen loads\n  Then a short activation code and its companion URL are displayed legibly at TV distance\n\nScenario: TV completes sign-in after activation\n  Given the viewer confirms the code on another device\n  When the activation is completed\n  Then the Samsung app signs in automatically without further remote input\n\nScenario: Fallback manual sign-in\n  Given the viewer prefers not to use a second device\n  When they choose manual sign-in\n  Then they can enter email and password with the on-screen keyboard (per CAP-ID credential rules)\n\nScenario: Session persists across restarts\n  Given a signed-in viewer closes the app or powers off the TV\n  When the app is next launched\n  Then the viewer is still signed in\n\nScenario: Sign out\n  Given a signed-in viewer opens settings\n  When they choose Sign out\n  Then the session ends on this TV and the sign-in screen is shown","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-04","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Remote and focus navigation","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want every screen in the Samsung app to work with the standard TV remote, so that I can do everything with directional keys, Enter, and Back."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (TV navigation must feel native to the device); Jul 1 call (John, 35:09, every button the person touches must work under load)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (focus management across all screens); platform-specific remote key mapping; QA effort across the full screen set"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Full reachability by D-pad\n  Given any screen in the app\n  When the viewer navigates with up, down, left, right, and Enter\n  Then every interactive element is reachable and there are no focus traps\n\nScenario: Visible focus state\n  Given the viewer moves focus between elements\n  When focus lands on an element\n  Then the focused element is clearly highlighted and legible at TV distance\n\nScenario: Back key behavior\n  Given the viewer is on any screen below the landing screen\n  When they press the remote Back key\n  Then the app returns one level, and from the landing screen Back follows the Samsung exit convention\n\nScenario: Player controls by remote\n  Given a film is playing\n  When the viewer presses Enter or the media keys\n  Then the control overlay appears and play, pause, and seek are all operable by remote","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-05","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Playback with platform DRM on Tizen","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to play my purchased film on my Samsung TV in the best quality my TV and connection support, so that the premiere experience works on the living-room screen."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 16:49, anti-piracy protection is very important; 39:34, watch, pause, finish later); register decision 2 (4K with adaptive ladder, Jul 1, 7:39 and 23:34); register decisions 5, 9, 10, 14"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-04 (Samsung TV portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-02, CAP-PLAY (playback capability), CAP-DRM (licensing and watermarking), CAP-PIPE (managed platform player support on Tizen)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (managed platform player on Tizen); external dependency (PlayReady is the native Tizen DRM, Widevine support varies by model year, to validate under the CAP-PIPE spike); platform multiplier; 4K ladder on TV hardware"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY (start, pause, resume, seek, adaptive ladder, caption behavior) and CAP-DRM (license issue and watermarking) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: DRM license on Tizen\n  Given an entitled, signed-in viewer starts playback\n  When the player requests a license\n  Then a PlayReady license is issued and playback starts (Widevine used where the Tizen model supports it, per the CAP-PIPE validation spike)\n\nScenario: 4K on a capable model\n  Given a 4K Samsung TV with sufficient bandwidth\n  When playback runs\n  Then the stream reaches the 4K rung and steps down the ladder gracefully when bandwidth drops\n\nScenario: Pause and resume on the TV\n  Given the viewer pauses the film and exits the app\n  When they relaunch the app and press Play on the same title\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position (position rules per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Captions by remote\n  Given caption tracks exist for the title (per CAP-CON upload)\n  When the viewer opens the caption menu from the player overlay\n  Then they can select a language or SDH track using the remote and it renders on screen\n\nScenario: Stream-limit rejection message\n  Given the account is already at its concurrent-screens limit (default 2, configurable, per CAP-PLAY)\n  When the viewer presses Play on the Samsung TV\n  Then playback is refused with a clear on-TV message and no stream starts\n\nScenario: Geographic restriction message\n  Given the geo check at playback start fails (per CAP-PLAY, US-only)\n  When the viewer presses Play\n  Then playback is refused with a clear on-TV message","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-06","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Purchase path on Samsung TV","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to buy the film from my Samsung TV, so that I can go from seeing the film to watching it without leaving the couch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 23:02, pay-per-view through Stripe; 26:12, buy-to-own, no rental; 35:09, failed payments under load); Assumption - client to confirm (Samsung store billing policy: Samsung Checkout may be required for in-app purchases on Tizen; both paths presented below, decision is the client's)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (Samsung TV portion)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-03, CAP-PAY (payments and entitlements)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Samsung billing policy determines the path; Samsung Checkout is expected to carry a platform commission, rate to be confirmed against Samsung's current published terms, Assumption - client to confirm, while the Stripe path carries standard processing fees, so the two paths have different per-sale cost, to be reflected in unit economics); integration either way; certification impact (path choice is reviewed at certification)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PAY (purchase, entitlement grant, decline handling, geo gate at payment, tax) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only. Path A and Path B are alternatives; the client selects one before build."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Path A, Stripe purchase initiated from the TV\n  Given Samsung policy permits an off-store payment flow for this app category (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the viewer starts a purchase on the TV and completes payment through the Stripe-backed flow\n  Then the entitlement is granted to their account and Play is available on the TV within 10 seconds (assumed payment-confirm target, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Path B, Samsung Checkout purchase\n  Given Samsung Checkout is the required billing route\n  When the viewer completes the purchase through Samsung Checkout on the TV\n  Then the purchase is confirmed back to the platform and the same account entitlement is granted as on any other surface\n\nScenario: Declined payment on the TV\n  Given a payment is declined on the selected path\n  When the flow completes\n  Then no access is granted, a clear on-TV message is shown, and the viewer can retry\n\nScenario: Entitlement works across surfaces\n  Given the viewer bought the film on the Samsung TV\n  When they sign in on any other supported device\n  Then the film is available there without paying again (per CAP-PAY)\n\nScenario: Price display is consistent\n  Given a price is set in the content console\n  When the film detail screen renders on the Samsung TV\n  Then the displayed price matches the price charged on the selected path","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-07","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Samsung certification and store release","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the Samsung app to pass Samsung's certification and be live in the Samsung app store before the premiere date, so that launch-night viewers can install and watch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 33:49, six-month launch window with a 4-5 month build); Allion scoping decision (each TV OS carries its own store submission and certification)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-01, PLAT-SAM-02, PLAT-SAM-03, PLAT-SAM-04, PLAT-SAM-05, PLAT-SAM-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"External dependency (Samsung review timeline and outcome are outside the team's control; review cycles must be buffered inside the launch window); process work more than build work; purchase-path choice (PLAT-SAM-06) affects review scope"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Pre-certification checklist pass\n  Given the app is feature-complete for the selected option\n  When the internal pre-certification review runs against Samsung's published app requirements\n  Then all checklist items pass or have documented remediations before submission\n\nScenario: Submission package complete\n  Given the seller account and app listing are prepared\n  When the app is submitted for certification\n  Then the package includes the signed build, store metadata, artwork, and content rating information required by Samsung\n\nScenario: Certification rework loop\n  Given Samsung returns rejection findings\n  When fixes are made and the app is resubmitted\n  Then each finding is tracked to closure and the resubmission is scheduled inside the launch buffer\n\nScenario: Live before premiere\n  Given certification is granted\n  When the release is published\n  Then the app is installable from the Samsung app store ahead of the planned premiere date","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-08","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":12,"title":"Tizen device matrix and premiere readiness","options":"A+B","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"A+B"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the Samsung app validated across a defined Tizen model range and included in the premiere load simulation, so that launch night works on real living-room hardware."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 29:16, 100,000 concurrent; 35:09, every button under load; 33:16, stress testing from month 4-5); register decisions 16, 17, 18; Assumption - client to confirm (supported Tizen version floor, proposed as recent model years covering the large majority of installed Samsung TVs)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-05, CAP-INF (100K full-journey premiere load profile)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (100K concurrent full-journey profile includes Samsung journeys); device diversity (older Tizen models have tighter memory and codec limits); QA lab or device-cloud coverage for physical TVs"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Supported model floor is defined and tested\n  Given the agreed Tizen version floor (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  When the test pass runs on representative models at and above the floor\n  Then install, sign-in, purchase, and playback pass on every model in the matrix\n\nScenario: QoE targets on reference hardware\n  Given the assumed QoE targets (video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent; assumed, client to confirm)\n  When playback runs on a mid-range reference model\n  Then the measured values meet the assumed targets\n\nScenario: Stability over a full film\n  Given a feature-length playback session of about two hours\n  When the film plays end to end on a reference model\n  Then playback completes without a crash, freeze, or memory-driven degradation\n\nScenario: Samsung journeys in the premiere load profile\n  Given the CAP-INF 100K concurrent full-journey simulation (login storm, purchase burst including declines, playback surge, trick-play, quit and resume)\n  When the load profile is executed from month 4-5\n  Then Samsung TV user journeys are represented in the simulated client mix and the app-facing APIs meet the assumed targets under load","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-PAY-10","epicId":"CAP-PAY","doc":13,"title":"Purchased library across the catalog","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer with multiple purchased films, I want a library view of everything I own, so that I can return to any purchased title without searching the catalog."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (Mishal and John, 25:59-26:12, purchases \"added to our library forever\") + Allion scoping decision (dedicated library view is only needed once the catalog holds 100-500 titles; in Option A the owned state on the single film page covers this, see CAP-PAY-04)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PAY-04, B-DISC (catalog and discovery UI surfaces the library view)"},{"label":"Scope note","value":"the purchased-library view is sized here once. B-DISC surfaces this view within the catalog UI and does not carry a separate library story or sizing."},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Low new build (list view over existing entitlement records); platform multiplier (rendered on web, mobile, and TV surfaces)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Library lists all owned titles\n  Given a viewer who has purchased several films\n  When they open their library\n  Then every purchased title is listed and none are missing\n\nScenario: Library entry starts the film\n  Given a viewer viewing their library\n  When they select an owned title\n  Then they can start playback directly\n\nScenario: Library is consistent across devices\n  Given purchases made on different surfaces\n  When the viewer opens the library on any signed-in device\n  Then the same set of owned titles appears\n\nScenario: Empty library state\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no purchases\n  When they open their library\n  Then a clear empty state points them to the catalog","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PLAY-09","epicId":"CAP-PLAY","doc":13,"title":"Resume data feed for continue watching","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer with access to a multi-title catalog, I want my in-progress titles available to the catalog experience, so that I can continue watching from the home screen."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, browsable platform experience); Allion scoping decision (continue-watching rail; the rail UI itself belongs to B-DISC)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY-05 (resume points), B-DISC (continue-watching rail consumes this feed)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"API surface consumed by B-DISC; multiple concurrent in-progress titles per account (Option B catalog of 100-500 titles); small build on top of the resume-point store"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: In-progress titles are returned\n  Given an account with one or more titles partially watched\n  When the continue-watching feed is requested\n  Then each in-progress title is returned with its resume position\n\nScenario: Completed titles drop off\n  Given an account where a title has been watched to the end\n  When the continue-watching feed is requested\n  Then that title is not included\n\nScenario: Ordering by recency\n  Given an account with multiple in-progress titles\n  When the continue-watching feed is requested\n  Then titles are ordered by most recent playback activity first\n\nScenario: Empty state\n  Given an account with no in-progress titles\n  When the continue-watching feed is requested\n  Then an empty list is returned without error\n\nScenario: Feed size cap (assumption, client to confirm)\n  Given an account with more in-progress titles than the configured cap\n  When the continue-watching feed is requested\n  Then only the most recent titles up to the cap are returned (default cap 20)","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-DRM-08","epicId":"CAP-DRM","doc":13,"title":"DRM protection at bulk-import scale","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a content operator, I want DRM packaging and watermark enablement applied automatically to every title in a bulk import, so that the purchased library of 100 to 500 titles is protected without per-title setup."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34) + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-DRM-01, CAP-DRM-06, CAP-CON (bulk import and single-title upload flows)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (hundreds of titles in one batch); integration with the bulk ingest pipeline; per-title failure isolation and reporting"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Every title in a batch is protected\n  Given a bulk import manifest covering multiple titles\n  When the batch import completes\n  Then every successfully ingested title is encrypted and licensable by Widevine, FairPlay, and PlayReady\n\nScenario: A single packaging failure does not block the batch\n  Given one title in the batch fails DRM packaging\n  When the batch completes\n  Then the failure is reported against that title only\n  And the remaining titles complete packaging normally\n\nScenario: Weekly release inherits the same protection\n  Given a single-title upload for a weekly big release\n  When the title is packaged\n  Then the same DRM and watermark settings apply by default with no additional operator steps\n\nScenario: Batch protection is verifiable by spot check\n  Given a completed bulk import\n  When a sample of imported titles is spot-checked\n  Then each sampled title issues licenses correctly and fails unlicensed playback","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-10","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":13,"title":"Bulk import of purchased library via manifest","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to import the purchased library using a manifest file plus batch-delivered media files, so that a 100-500 title catalog can be loaded without one-by-one manual entry."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 18:41, \"go buy a library of 100\"; John, 39:34, 100 to 500 titles streamable at any given time) + Allion scoping decision (manifest CSV/spreadsheet plus batch file delivery). Deep content-ops edge cases are out of scope by scoping decision; edge handling is deliberately light. Assumption - client to confirm: a single operator is accepted as sufficient to run the Option B catalog (100-500 titles plus weekly releases); single-operator risk is flagged per the Jun 22 decision."},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-03, CAP-CON-05 (reuses the single-title ingest and metadata model), CAP-PIPE"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (hundreds of titles per batch); manifest parsing and validation; matching media files to manifest rows; managed-platform throughput on batch encode (external dependency)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Valid manifest accepted\n  Given the operator uploads a manifest file in the agreed CSV/spreadsheet format\n  When the manifest passes structural validation\n  Then a batch import is created and queued for processing\n\nScenario: Manifest rows create draft titles\n  Given a queued batch import with valid rows\n  When the batch is processed\n  Then each valid row creates a draft title populated with the metadata from that row\n\nScenario: Media files matched to manifest rows\n  Given media files have been delivered to the agreed batch location\n  When the batch is processed\n  Then each file is matched to its manifest row by the agreed identifier and handed to the managed platform for encoding\n\nScenario: Invalid rows do not block valid rows\n  Given a manifest containing both valid and invalid rows\n  When the batch is processed\n  Then valid rows import normally and each invalid row is skipped with a recorded reason\n\nScenario: Imported titles are not auto-published\n  Given a batch import has completed\n  When the operator views the imported titles\n  Then every imported title is in draft state until the operator publishes it","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","assumption"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-11","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":13,"title":"Batch progress view with per-item report","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want a progress view for each bulk import showing per-item success or failure, so that I can see what loaded and fix what failed."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (supports the bulk-import route agreed for the Option B purchased library)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-10"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; aggregation across hundreds of items per batch; readable failure reporting kept deliberately light (no deep content-ops tooling)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Batch summary visible\n  Given a batch import is in progress or complete\n  When the operator opens the batch progress view\n  Then totals are shown for items in progress, succeeded, and failed\n\nScenario: Per-item status with reason\n  Given a batch import has processed items\n  When the operator opens the item list for the batch\n  Then each item shows its title identifier, its status, and a readable failure reason where it failed\n\nScenario: Failed item can be corrected and re-imported\n  Given an item failed in a completed batch\n  When the operator re-submits a corrected manifest row and file for that item\n  Then the item is processed again without duplicating previously succeeded items\n\nScenario: Batch history retained\n  Given multiple batch imports have run\n  When the operator opens the batch list\n  Then past batches are listed with their date and summary results","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-12","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":13,"title":"Scheduled publish","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to schedule a title to publish at a set date and time, so that the weekly big release goes live at the announced moment."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, every week there will be a big release that drives the spike; Mishal, 32:23, telling people the movie comes out at 9 p.m.) + Allion scoping decision (scheduling mechanism)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-09 (uses the same readiness gate and publish action)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; time-based job reliability at a moment of peak marketing attention; timezone handling"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Schedule a ready title\n  Given a title that meets all publish readiness requirements\n  When the operator sets a publish date, time, and timezone\n  Then the schedule is saved and shown on the title\n\nScenario: Title publishes at the scheduled time\n  Given a title has a saved publish schedule\n  When the scheduled time is reached\n  Then the title is published automatically within 1 minute of the scheduled time (execution window is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Scheduling blocked for an unready title\n  Given a title that does not meet publish readiness requirements\n  When the operator attempts to set a publish schedule\n  Then the schedule is rejected and the unmet requirements are listed\n\nScenario: Change or cancel a schedule\n  Given a title has a future publish schedule\n  When the operator changes or cancels the schedule before it fires\n  Then the new schedule (or no schedule) takes effect and no unintended publish occurs\n\nScenario: Failed scheduled publish is surfaced\n  Given a scheduled publish fails to execute\n  When the operator opens the console\n  Then the failure is clearly flagged on the title so it can be published manually","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-CON-13","epicId":"CAP-CON","doc":13,"title":"Curated row management","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to create and order curated rows (featured, top 10, new this week), so that the catalog home surface highlights the right titles without a recommendation engine."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"here are like the top 10 things\" plus browse by genre, explicitly no recommendation engine) + Allion scoping decision (operator-curated featured, top 10, and new-this-week rows)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON-09; rows are consumed by B-DISC (catalog and discovery)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; ordering and row-membership model; consistency with the B-DISC catalog surfaces across web, mobile, and TV"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Create a curated row\n  Given the operator is signed in\n  When they create a row with a name and a row type (featured, top 10, or new this week)\n  Then the row is saved and available to the catalog surfaces\n\nScenario: Add, remove, and reorder titles in a row\n  Given a curated row exists\n  When the operator adds published titles, removes one, and changes the order\n  Then the row's membership and order are saved exactly as arranged\n\nScenario: Only published titles appear in rows\n  Given a curated row contains a title that is later unpublished\n  When a viewer loads the catalog\n  Then the unpublished title is automatically hidden from the row without operator action\n\nScenario: Row changes reach viewers promptly\n  Given the operator saves a change to a curated row\n  When a viewer reloads the catalog\n  Then the updated row content is visible within 5 minutes (propagation window is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Rows display in the operator-set order\n  Given multiple curated rows exist\n  When the operator sets the display order of the rows\n  Then catalog surfaces render the rows in that order","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-PIPE-09","epicId":"CAP-PIPE","doc":13,"title":"Bulk library ingest integration for the launch catalog","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want a batch ingest path (manifest plus media files) into the managed platform, so that the purchased library of 100 to 500 titles can be loaded and verified before launch without uploading titles one at a time."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 18:41 buy a library of 100; John, 39:34 100 to 500 titles streamable at any given time, weekly big release) + Allion scoping decision (register #11)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PIPE-03 (single-title ingest is the underlying mechanism), CAP-PIPE-04 (ladder applies per title), CAP-CON (bulk import console and manifest format)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (hundreds of masters plus caption sets); external dependency on vendor bulk or parallel ingest limits; partial-failure handling across a long-running batch"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Batch ingest from a manifest\n  Given an operator submits a manifest (CSV or equivalent) referencing a batch of master files\n  When the batch job runs\n  Then each referenced title is ingested and encoded through the standard pipeline (CAP-PIPE-03, CAP-PIPE-04)\n  And per-title status is reported for the whole batch\n\nScenario: Partial failure does not sink the batch\n  Given one title in a batch fails validation or encoding\n  When the batch continues\n  Then remaining titles process to completion\n  And the failed title is listed with a readable reason for retry\n\nScenario: Batch throughput fits the launch window\n  Given a library at the upper bound of 500 titles\n  When ingest throughput is measured against vendor parallelism limits\n  Then the full 500-title library can be ingested and verified within the 4 weeks before launch (Assumption - client to confirm the 4-week window)\n\nScenario: Weekly release uses the standard single-title flow\n  Given the weekly big release drives the Option B spike\n  When the operator loads a new weekly title\n  Then it uses the single-title ingest flow (CAP-PIPE-03) and is playable end to end before its announced release time","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"CAP-MET-07","epicId":"CAP-MET","doc":13,"title":"Catalog-wide economics rollup","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the internal operator, I want a rollup of streams, GB delivered, delivery cost, revenue, and margin across the full 100 to 500 title catalog, so that the client can see which titles earn and which titles cost, including each weekly release."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, 100 to 500 titles with a weekly big release) + Allion scoping decision (rollup view is an extension of the per-title view to catalog scale)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET-04 (per-title figures), CAP-CON (console surface)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data volume factor across a 100 to 500 title catalog; sorting and pagination; remains a simple internal table, not an analytics product."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: All titles listed with economics figures\n  Given a catalog of published titles with usage and payment data\n  When the operator opens the catalog rollup for a date range\n  Then every published title appears with streams, GB delivered, delivery cost, revenue, and margin for that range\n\nScenario: Sortable columns\n  Given the rollup is displayed\n  When the operator sorts by any column (streams, GB, cost, revenue, margin)\n  Then the title list reorders accordingly\n\nScenario: Weekly release visible from day one\n  Given a new weekly release title receives its first streams\n  When the rollup is opened the following day\n  Then the new title appears in the rollup with its figures to date\n\nScenario: Catalog totals row\n  Given usage and payment data exist for a date range\n  When the operator opens the catalog rollup for that range\n  Then a totals row shows catalog-wide streams, GB, total variable delivery cost, total revenue, and overall margin\n\nScenario: Acceptable load time at full catalog size\n  Given a catalog of 500 titles with usage data\n  When the rollup is opened\n  Then it renders within 5 seconds (assumed target, client to confirm)","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"CAP-INF-08","epicId":"CAP-INF","doc":13,"title":"Recurring weekly release surge readiness","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want the premiere surge posture to be repeatable for a weekly big release, so that every weekly spike is handled with a standard, low-effort routine rather than a one-off event."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, every week there will be a big release that gives you the spike); applying the 100,000 concurrent bar to Option B weekly releases is an Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-INF-05, CAP-INF-07; CAP-CON (content console) for the weekly release publish flow"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Operational build (scheduling and pre-scaling automation on top of existing surge controls); recurring cadence (weekly, so manual effort must be minimal); data/volume factor (spike size per weekly title is unproven, assumed profile)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Pre-release scaling can be scheduled\n  Given a weekly release has a published go-live time\n  When the release window approaches\n  Then backend capacity is scaled up ahead of the window on a schedule, without manual instance management\n\nScenario: Surge controls arm per release\n  Given a release window is configured\n  When the window opens\n  Then rate limits and waiting-room thresholds for that window apply automatically\n  And they return to baseline after the window closes\n\nScenario: A standard release-day dashboard and checklist exist\n  Given a weekly release is underway\n  When the team follows the release routine\n  Then the premiere dashboard (CAP-INF-04) and a documented checklist cover the window with no steps unique to that title\n\nScenario: Each release feeds capacity learning\n  Given a weekly release window has closed\n  When the post-release review runs\n  Then observed peak concurrency and resource usage are recorded per release\n  And scaling schedules for future releases can be adjusted from that record","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-09","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":13,"title":"Catalog home page with title grid","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a browsable home page showing the full catalog, so that I can find something to watch across 100-500 titles."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34-42:21, browsable experience, 100 to 500 titles, Apple TV Plus model) + Allion scoping decision (register decision 13)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01 (web home, Option B form)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (catalog capability), PLAT-WEB-01, PLAT-WEB-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build; data volume (up to 500 titles requires progressive loading); grid UI patterns need the patent-aware design check raised on the Jun 22 call (John on grid-UI patents)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (catalog content and published-only visibility) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Catalog grid renders at volume\n  Given a catalog of up to 500 published titles (per B-DISC)\n  When a viewer opens the home page\n  Then the grid loads progressively without blocking the first screen of content\n\nScenario: Grid responds across breakpoints\n  Given the home page on desktop, tablet, and phone widths\n  When the viewport changes\n  Then grid column counts and row layouts adapt with no unreachable titles\n\nScenario: Tile opens film detail\n  Given any title tile on the home page\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then the film detail page (PLAT-WEB-03) opens for that title\n\nScenario: Only published titles appear\n  Given a mix of published and unpublished titles in the console (per CAP-CON)\n  When the home page renders\n  Then only published titles are shown in the grid","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-10","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":13,"title":"Curated rows and continue-watching rail","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want curated rows (featured, top 10, new) and my continue-watching rail on the home page, so that the front door highlights what to watch next."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34-42:21, \"here are like the top 10 things\") + Allion scoping decision (register decision 13: operator-curated rows, continue-watching rail)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-WEB-09, B-DISC (row curation), CAP-PLAY (resume positions)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (B-DISC row curation plus CAP-PLAY resume positions, two data sources on one surface); horizontal rail interaction across pointer and touch input; row rendering at catalog volume."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (row curation rules) and CAP-PLAY (resume positions) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Curated rows display in operator order\n  Given the operator has curated rows (featured, top 10, new, per B-DISC)\n  When the home page renders\n  Then each row displays in the operator-defined order as a horizontally scrollable rail\n\nScenario: Rails work with pointer and touch\n  Given a curated row wider than the viewport\n  When the viewer scrolls it with mouse, trackpad, or touch\n  Then the row scrolls horizontally and every title in the row is reachable\n\nScenario: Continue-watching rail resumes playback\n  Given a signed-in viewer with partially watched films (positions per CAP-PLAY)\n  When they select an item in the continue-watching rail\n  Then the player page opens and offers resume from the saved position\n\nScenario: Continue-watching rail hidden when empty\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no partially watched films\n  When the home page renders\n  Then the continue-watching rail is not displayed","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-11","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":13,"title":"Genre browse pages","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the catalog by genre, so that I can narrow 100-500 titles to the kind of film I feel like watching."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"I'll browse by genre or something\") + Allion scoping decision (register decision 13); deep-linkable genre page URLs = Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (genre taxonomy and filtering), PLAT-WEB-09"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build on existing grid components; routing per genre; low data complexity."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (genre assignment, filter correctness) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Genre navigation from home\n  Given the home page is displayed\n  When the viewer opens the genre navigation\n  Then all operator-defined genres are listed and selectable\n\nScenario: Genre page lists matching titles\n  Given a viewer selects a genre\n  When the genre page loads\n  Then only published titles assigned to that genre are shown (assignment per B-DISC)\n\nScenario: Genre pages are deep-linkable (Allion scoping decision)\n  Given each genre page has its own URL\n  When a viewer opens that URL directly in a supported browser\n  Then the genre page loads without needing to navigate from home\n\nScenario: Empty genre state\n  Given a genre with no published titles\n  When its page is opened\n  Then a clear empty state is shown instead of a blank grid","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-12","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":13,"title":"Text search UI","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search the catalog by text, so that I can go straight to a title I already have in mind."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"basic search, basic browse... you don't need discovery or recommendation engine\") + register decisions 13 and 19"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (search capability), PLAT-WEB-01, PLAT-WEB-03"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (B-DISC search capability); UI-only build; keyboard accessibility."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (search matching and result rules) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search entry point is always reachable\n  Given a viewer on any main page of the web app\n  When they select the search entry point\n  Then a text input receives focus and accepts a query via keyboard\n\nScenario: Results open film detail\n  Given search results are returned for a query (matching per B-DISC)\n  When the viewer selects a result\n  Then the film detail page (PLAT-WEB-03) opens for that title\n\nScenario: No-results state\n  Given a query with no matching titles\n  When results return empty\n  Then a clear no-results message is shown with the option to amend the query\n\nScenario: No recommendation elements\n  Given the search experience in Option B\n  When results are displayed\n  Then no personalised recommendation content appears (recommendation engine out of scope, register decision 19)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-WEB-13","epicId":"PLAT-WEB","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist page","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to save titles to a watchlist and see them on one page, so that I can come back to films I noticed but did not start."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (watchlist capability), CAP-ID (signed-in account), PLAT-WEB-03, PLAT-WEB-09"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (B-DISC watchlist capability); small UI surface; the watchlist is stored against the account, so the web page must display changes made on other platforms."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (watchlist rules) apply on this platform. Web-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Add to watchlist from film detail\n  Given a signed-in viewer on a film detail page\n  When they select the add-to-watchlist action\n  Then the title is saved (per B-DISC) and the action state changes to added\n\nScenario: Remove from watchlist\n  Given a title already on the viewer's watchlist\n  When the viewer removes it from the detail page or the watchlist page\n  Then it no longer appears on the watchlist page\n\nScenario: Watchlist page lists saved titles\n  Given a signed-in viewer with saved titles\n  When they open the watchlist page\n  Then all saved titles display as tiles that open the film detail page\n\nScenario: Watchlist changes made on another device appear on the web\n  Given a signed-in viewer added or removed a title on another platform\n  When they open or refresh the web watchlist page\n  Then the page reflects the current account-level watchlist (storage per B-DISC)\n\nScenario: Empty watchlist state\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no saved titles\n  When they open the watchlist page\n  Then a clear empty state explains how to add titles","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-07","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":13,"title":"Catalog home, genre browse, and curated rows on iOS","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the catalog on my iPhone through curated rows and genres, so that I can find something to watch across 100-500 titles."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, browsable experience, top 10 and genre browse, Apple TV Plus model) + Allion scoping decision (register decision 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-02, B-DISC"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (catalog up to 500 titles with artwork); scroll performance on older devices; extends rather than replaces the Option A landing components."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC apply on this platform (row curation rules, genre taxonomy, published-only visibility, no recommendation engine). iOS-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Browsable home replaces the single-film landing\n  Given Option B is in effect\n  When the viewer opens the app\n  Then the home screen shows operator-curated rows (featured, top 10, new) with a weekly release surfaced prominently\n\nScenario: Genre browse\n  Given the viewer opens the browse section\n  When they select a genre\n  Then all published titles in that genre are listed and each opens the PLAT-IOS-02 detail screen\n\nScenario: Row scrolling stays responsive at full catalog size\n  Given the catalog holds 500 published titles\n  When the viewer scrolls rows and grids on a supported device\n  Then scrolling remains responsive and artwork loads progressively without blocking the interface\n\nScenario: Detail screen unchanged\n  Given a title is opened from any row, genre list, or search result\n  When the detail screen loads\n  Then the PLAT-IOS-02 detail acceptance criteria apply unchanged","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-08","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":13,"title":"Search on iOS","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search the catalog by text on my iPhone, so that I can go straight to a film I already know I want."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, basic search, no recommendation engine) + Allion scoping decision (register decision 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-07, B-DISC"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the B-DISC search capability; native keyboard and input handling; result rendering at catalog scale."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC apply on this platform (matching rules, published-only results). iOS-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search entry point\n  Given the viewer is anywhere in the main navigation\n  When they open search\n  Then a text field with the native iOS keyboard is presented\n\nScenario: Results open the detail screen\n  Given the viewer types a query matching one or more published titles\n  When results are shown\n  Then tapping a result opens that title's PLAT-IOS-02 detail screen\n\nScenario: Empty result state\n  Given the viewer's query matches no published title\n  When results return\n  Then a clear no-results message is shown with the option to browse by genre instead\n\nScenario: Results refresh after typing pauses (assumed, client to confirm)\n  Given results refreshing automatically once the viewer stops typing is an Assumption - client to confirm (the interaction model affects B-DISC search load)\n  When the viewer edits their query text and pauses\n  Then the result list refreshes to match the current query only","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-IOS-09","epicId":"PLAT-IOS","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist and continue watching on iOS","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want my watchlist and a continue-watching row on my iPhone, so that I can save titles for later and pick up any film where I left off, on any device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 13); resume behaviour per Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, pause and finish later)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-IOS-07, B-DISC, CAP-PLAY"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with shared watchlist and resume-position services; cross-device state sync; row placement and ordering on the home screen."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (watchlist, continue-watching rail) and CAP-PLAY (resume positions) apply on this platform. iOS-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Add and remove from watchlist\n  Given a signed-in viewer on a title's detail screen\n  When they tap the watchlist action\n  Then the title is added to their watchlist, and tapping again removes it, reflected immediately in the watchlist view\n\nScenario: Continue-watching row on home\n  Given the viewer has partially watched one or more owned titles\n  When they open the home screen\n  Then a continue-watching row shows those titles with resume progress, and tapping one resumes playback at the saved position\n\nScenario: Cross-device resume appears on iOS\n  Given the viewer paused a film on another platform\n  When they open the iOS app with the same account\n  Then the continue-watching row reflects the position saved from the other device\n\nScenario: Completed titles leave the row\n  Given the viewer finishes a film\n  When the home screen next refreshes\n  Then that title no longer appears in the continue-watching row","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-08","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":13,"title":"Catalog browse and curated rows on Android","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the full catalog with curated rows and genres on my phone, so that I can find something to watch beyond the big weekly release."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, basic browse, genre, top 10, Apple TV Plus model); Allion scoping decision (register item 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-02; B-DISC"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data and volume factor (100 to 500 streamable titles, artwork loading and scroll performance); extends the Option A landing rather than replacing it; no recommendation engine (out of scope, register item 19)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC apply on this platform (row curation, genre data, publish state). Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Home extends into curated rows\n  Given a catalog of 100 to 500 published titles\n  When the viewer opens the app home\n  Then operator-curated rows (featured, top 10, new) render with artwork loading progressively, and row scroll and rendering meet the assumed QoE targets (register item 18, Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Genre browse\n  Given the viewer selects a genre from the browse entry point\n  When the genre screen opens\n  Then it lists the published titles for that genre\n\nScenario: Tile opens detail\n  Given any title tile in a row, genre list, or search result\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then the film detail page (PLAT-AND-02 layout) opens for that title\n\nScenario: Weekly release surfaced\n  Given the operator has flagged the weekly big release as featured\n  When the viewer opens the app home\n  Then that title leads the featured row","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-09","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":13,"title":"Search on Android","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search the catalog by text on my phone, so that I can go straight to a title I already have in mind."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, basic search); Allion scoping decision (register item 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-08; B-DISC"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the B-DISC search service; on-device input and results rendering; no personalization layer"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC apply on this platform (search behavior, published-only results). Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search entry and input\n  Given the viewer opens search from the app home\n  When they type a query with the on-screen keyboard\n  Then matching published titles are returned\n\nScenario: No results\n  Given a query that matches no published title\n  When the results load\n  Then a clear empty-state message is shown and the viewer can edit the query\n\nScenario: Result opens detail\n  Given a search result\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then the film detail page opens for that title","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-AND-10","epicId":"PLAT-AND","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist and continue watching on Android","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want my watchlist and an in-progress rail on my phone, so that I can come back to titles across sessions and devices."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register item 13, watchlist and continue-watching rail)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-AND-08; B-DISC; CAP-PLAY (resume position)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (cross-device watchlist and position state from B-DISC and CAP-PLAY); rail rendering on the extended home"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC and CAP-PLAY apply on this platform (watchlist state, position tracking). Android-specific scenarios only below."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Add and remove watchlist from detail\n  Given a signed-in viewer on a film detail page\n  When they add the title to, or remove it from, their watchlist\n  Then the watchlist rail on the app home reflects the change\n\nScenario: Continue-watching rail\n  Given the viewer has one or more titles in progress\n  When they open the app home\n  Then a continue-watching rail lists those titles with their progress\n\nScenario: Resume from the rail\n  Given a title in the continue-watching rail, including progress made on another device\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position\n\nScenario: Finished title leaves the rail\n  Given the viewer watches a title to the end\n  When they return to the app home\n  Then that title no longer appears in the continue-watching rail","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-08","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":13,"title":"Catalog home with curated rows","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a browsable home screen with curated rows on Roku, so that I can find something to watch across a 100-500 title catalog."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34-42:21, browsable experience, \"top 10 things\", Apple TV Plus model, 100-500 titles) + Allion scoping decision (operator-curated rows in the Option B discovery set)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (curated-row capability ACs apply), PLAT-ROKU-02, PLAT-ROKU-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Row rendering performance with hundreds of titles on low-memory Roku hardware; artwork loading at TV scale; data/volume factor (catalog size)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC apply on this platform. Roku-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Curated rows render on the Roku home screen\n  Given the operator has curated featured, top 10, and new-release rows (per B-DISC)\n  When the viewer opens the channel home screen\n  Then the rows display in the curated order with the curated contents\n\nScenario: Row traversal remembers position\n  Given the viewer has scrolled within a row and moved to another row\n  When they return to the earlier row\n  Then focus returns to their previous position in that row\n\nScenario: Artwork loads without freezing navigation\n  Given rows containing titles whose artwork has not yet loaded\n  When the viewer scrolls quickly through rows\n  Then placeholders display, artwork fills in progressively, and remote input is never blocked\n\nScenario: Full catalog browses on the lowest supported device\n  Given a catalog of 500 published titles\n  When the viewer browses all rows on the lowest-specification supported Roku model\n  Then the channel does not crash or run out of memory","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-09","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":13,"title":"Genre browse","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the catalog by genre on Roku, so that I can narrow hundreds of titles to what I am in the mood for."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"browse by genre or something\")"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (genre taxonomy and browse capability ACs apply), PLAT-ROKU-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with B-DISC genre data; list rendering at catalog scale on TV"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Genre list reachable from home\n  Given the viewer is on the Roku home screen\n  When they navigate to browse by genre\n  Then the available genres display and are selectable with the remote\n\nScenario: Genre selection filters the catalog\n  Given the viewer selects a genre\n  When the genre screen loads\n  Then only published titles tagged with that genre are shown (tagging rules per B-DISC)\n\nScenario: Empty genre shows a readable state\n  Given a genre currently has no published titles\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then a readable empty state displays instead of a blank screen\n\nScenario: Back returns to the prior browse position\n  Given the viewer entered a genre from the home screen\n  When they press Back\n  Then they return to the home screen with their previous focus position restored","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-10","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":13,"title":"Remote-friendly search","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search for a title with my Roku remote, so that I can jump straight to a film I already know I want."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, basic search) + Allion scoping decision (text search only, no recommendation engine)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (search capability ACs apply), PLAT-ROKU-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"On-screen keyboard input UX with a d-pad; incremental result loading performance on TV hardware"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: On-screen keyboard operable by d-pad\n  Given the viewer opens search on Roku\n  When they use the directional pad and OK button\n  Then they can enter, correct, and clear text using the on-screen keyboard alone\n\nScenario: Results update as the query is entered\n  Given the viewer has typed at least the minimum query length (per B-DISC search rules)\n  When they continue entering characters\n  Then matching published titles update on screen without a separate submit step\n\nScenario: No-results state is readable\n  Given a query matching no published titles\n  When results are returned\n  Then a readable no-results message displays instead of a blank screen\n\nScenario: Selecting a result opens the detail screen\n  Given search results are shown\n  When the viewer selects a title\n  Then the film detail screen opens for that title","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-11","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":13,"title":"Continue-watching rail","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a continue-watching row on the Roku home screen, so that I can resume films I started on this or any other device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (continue-watching rail in the Option B discovery set)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (continue-watching capability ACs apply), CAP-PLAY (cross-device resume positions), PLAT-ROKU-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with cross-device resume data; rail refresh behavior on channel launch"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Partially watched film appears in the rail\n  Given the viewer stopped a film partway through on Roku\n  When they return to the home screen\n  Then the film appears in the continue-watching row with a progress indicator\n\nScenario: Resume from the rail\n  Given a film in the continue-watching row\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then playback resumes from the saved position (resume rules per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Cross-device position shows on Roku\n  Given the viewer started a film on web or mobile\n  When they open the Roku home screen on the same account\n  Then the film appears in the continue-watching row at the position saved from the other device\n\nScenario: Finished film leaves the rail\n  Given the viewer watches a film to completion\n  When the home screen refreshes\n  Then that film no longer appears in the continue-watching row (completion rules per B-DISC)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-ROKU-12","epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist on Roku","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to add films to my watchlist from the Roku detail screen and see that list on the home screen, so that I can save films to watch later."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (watchlist in the Option B discovery set)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (watchlist capability ACs apply), PLAT-ROKU-02, PLAT-ROKU-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with the shared watchlist service; state sync between detail screen and home rows"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Add to watchlist from the detail screen\n  Given a signed-in viewer on a film detail screen\n  When they select add to watchlist with the remote\n  Then the film is added and the detail screen reflects the watchlisted state\n\nScenario: Remove from watchlist\n  Given a film already on the viewer's watchlist\n  When they select remove on the detail screen\n  Then the film is removed and disappears from the watchlist row\n\nScenario: Watchlist row on home reflects changes\n  Given the viewer has added films to their watchlist\n  When they return to the home screen\n  Then the watchlist row shows the current list (sync rules per B-DISC)\n\nScenario: Watchlist syncs across devices\n  Given the viewer added a film to their watchlist on web or mobile\n  When they open the Roku home screen on the same account\n  Then that film appears in the Roku watchlist row\n\nScenario: Empty watchlist state\n  Given a viewer with no watchlisted films\n  When the home screen renders\n  Then the watchlist row is hidden or shows a readable empty state (per B-DISC rules)","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-08","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":13,"title":"Catalog rows on Fire TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse curated rows of titles on my Fire TV, so that I can quickly find something to watch in a catalog of 100 to 500 films."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"here are like the top 10 things, and then I'll browse by genre\") + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (curated rows), PLAT-FTV-02"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Data/volume factor (100-500 titles with artwork at TV sizes); scroll and image performance on low-memory Fire TV sticks; 10-foot row navigation build."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (row curation, ordering, content rules) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Rows render on the home screen\n  Given operator-curated rows exist (featured, top 10, new)\n  When the viewer opens the Fire TV home screen\n  Then rows render in the curated order with title artwork legible at 10-foot distance\n\nScenario: Horizontal row navigation\n  Given the viewer is focused on a row\n  When they navigate left and right with the D-pad\n  Then focus moves through titles with a visible focus state and no D-pad presses are lost\n\nScenario: Performance on low-memory devices\n  Given a low-memory Fire TV device from the supported device baseline (PLAT-FTV-01) and a 500-title catalog\n  When the viewer scrolls through all rows\n  Then artwork loads progressively, the app does not crash, and no D-pad presses are lost during scrolling","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-09","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":13,"title":"Genre browse on Fire TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse titles by genre on my Fire TV, so that I can narrow the catalog to what I am in the mood for."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34) + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (genre browse), PLAT-FTV-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Reuses B-DISC genre service (integration, not new logic); TV-specific genre navigation and grid layout."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (genre taxonomy and filtering) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Genre list navigation\n  Given genres exist in the catalog\n  When the viewer opens genre browse\n  Then genres are listed and selectable with the remote\n\nScenario: Filtered results grid\n  Given the viewer selects a genre\n  When results load\n  Then only titles in that genre are shown in a D-pad navigable grid\n\nScenario: Empty genre state\n  Given a genre currently has no published titles\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then a clear empty state is shown with a route back to browse","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-10","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":13,"title":"Search on Fire TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search for a title on my Fire TV, so that I can go straight to a film I already have in mind."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"basic search, basic browse\") + Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (text search), PLAT-FTV-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Reuses B-DISC search service; TV on-screen keyboard input build. Alexa voice search is excluded from this scope (Assumption - client to confirm)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (search matching and result rules) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search entry by remote\n  Given the viewer opens search\n  When they enter text using the on-screen keyboard with the D-pad\n  Then results update as the query is entered\n\nScenario: Result selection\n  Given search results are shown\n  When the viewer selects a result\n  Then the film detail screen opens for that title\n\nScenario: No results\n  Given a query matches no published titles\n  When results load\n  Then a clear no-results state is shown and the viewer can edit the query or exit search","scenarioCount":3,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-11","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":13,"title":"Continue watching on Fire TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a continue-watching row on my Fire TV, so that I can pick up films where I left off, including films I started on another device."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (continue-watching rail), CAP-PLAY (resume positions), PLAT-FTV-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration only (rail data and resume positions are capability-side); cross-device state consistency surfaced on the TV."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (rail rules) and CAP-PLAY (resume position) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Rail shows in-progress titles\n  Given the viewer has partially watched one or more entitled films\n  When they open the Fire TV home screen\n  Then a continue-watching row shows those titles with a visible progress indicator\n\nScenario: Resume from the rail\n  Given the viewer selects a title in the continue-watching row\n  When playback starts\n  Then it resumes from the saved position per CAP-PLAY\n\nScenario: Cross-device resume\n  Given the viewer paused a film on another device on the same account\n  When they open the continue-watching row on Fire TV\n  Then the title appears with the position from the other device\n\nScenario: Completed titles drop off\n  Given the viewer finishes a film\n  When the home screen refreshes\n  Then that title no longer appears in the continue-watching row","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-FTV-12","epicId":"PLAT-FTV","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist on Fire TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to add films to a watchlist on my Fire TV and see them in a watchlist row, so that I can save titles now and find them quickly when I am ready to watch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC (watchlist), PLAT-FTV-02, PLAT-FTV-08"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration only (watchlist state is capability-side); TV add/remove interactions on the detail screen and row; cross-device consistency surfaced on the TV."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (watchlist rules) apply. The scenarios below are Fire TV specific."}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Add to watchlist from the detail screen\n  Given a signed-in viewer is on a film detail screen\n  When they select the add-to-watchlist action with the remote\n  Then the title is added to their watchlist and the action changes to a remove state\n\nScenario: Watchlist row on the home screen\n  Given the viewer has one or more titles in their watchlist\n  When they open the Fire TV home screen\n  Then a watchlist row shows those titles and each is selectable to its detail screen\n\nScenario: Remove from watchlist\n  Given a title is in the viewer's watchlist\n  When they select the remove action from the detail screen or the watchlist row\n  Then the title no longer appears in the watchlist row\n\nScenario: Cross-device watchlist consistency\n  Given the viewer added a title to their watchlist on another device on the same account\n  When they open the watchlist row on Fire TV\n  Then that title appears in the row","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["allion"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-09","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":13,"title":"Catalog rows on Samsung TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the Samsung app home screen to show browsable rows of titles, so that I can move from the weekly big release into the wider library."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, browsable experience holding 100-500 titles, Apple TV Plus model, top 10 style rows); register decision 13 (operator-curated rows: featured, top 10, new)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-02, B-DISC (catalog and discovery capability), CAP-CON (row curation)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (TV rail layouts and focus memory); data/volume factor (100-500 titles with artwork on TV hardware); integration with B-DISC row definitions"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (row content, ordering, and curation rules) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Rows render as horizontal rails\n  Given the operator has curated rows in the console\n  When the viewer opens the Samsung app home screen\n  Then each row renders as a horizontally scrollable rail navigable with left and right keys\n\nScenario: Focus memory within rows\n  Given the viewer moves from a row into a detail screen\n  When they press Back\n  Then focus returns to the same title in the same row position\n\nScenario: Artwork loads smoothly at catalog scale\n  Given a catalog of several hundred published titles\n  When the viewer scrolls quickly through rows\n  Then artwork loads progressively without freezing navigation\n\nScenario: Empty rows are hidden\n  Given a curated row currently has no published titles\n  When the home screen renders\n  Then that row does not appear","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-10","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":13,"title":"Genre browse on Samsung TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the library by genre on my Samsung TV, so that I can find something to watch without a search box."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, \"browse by genre or something\", no recommendation engine); register decision 13"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-09, B-DISC (genre taxonomy and browse capability)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (genre data from B-DISC); TV grid layout and paging at 100-500 titles; no recommendation logic (explicitly excluded)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (genre assignment and filtering) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Genre entry point\n  Given published titles carry genre metadata\n  When the viewer opens Browse from the home screen\n  Then a remote-navigable list of genres is shown\n\nScenario: Genre results grid\n  Given the viewer selects a genre\n  When the results render\n  Then all published titles in that genre are shown in a focus-navigable grid with poster and title\n\nScenario: Paging through a large genre\n  Given a genre contains more titles than fit on one screen\n  When the viewer navigates past the visible set\n  Then further titles load without losing focus position\n\nScenario: Empty genres are hidden\n  Given a genre has no published titles\n  When the genre list renders\n  Then that genre does not appear","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-11","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":13,"title":"Search on Samsung TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search for a title by text on my Samsung TV, so that I can go straight to a film I already know I want."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, basic search, basic browse); register decision 13 (text search, no recommendation engine)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-04, B-DISC (search capability)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (search service from B-DISC); on-screen keyboard input by remote; result rendering performance at catalog scale"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from B-DISC (matching rules, published-only results) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search with the on-screen keyboard\n  Given the viewer opens Search\n  When they enter text using the remote and the on-screen keyboard\n  Then matching published titles appear as a focus-navigable result set\n\nScenario: Results update as the query narrows\n  Given the viewer has typed part of a title\n  When they add more characters\n  Then the result set updates without requiring a separate submit action\n\nScenario: No-results state\n  Given a query matches no published titles\n  When the results render\n  Then a clear no-results message is shown and the viewer can edit the query or back out\n\nScenario: From result to detail\n  Given search results are shown\n  When the viewer selects a result\n  Then the film detail screen opens and Back returns to the same results and query","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"PLAT-SAM-12","epicId":"PLAT-SAM","doc":13,"title":"Continue watching and watchlist on Samsung TV","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a continue-watching rail and a watchlist on my Samsung TV, so that I can pick up unfinished films and queue titles for later."},{"label":"Source","value":"Register decision 13 (continue-watching rail and watchlist, Allion additions to Jul 1 discovery scope); Jul 1 call (John, 39:34, retain viewers across titles)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"PLAT-SAM-09, B-DISC (watchlist capability), CAP-PLAY (resume-position capability)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (resume positions from CAP-PLAY, watchlist from B-DISC); cross-device state sync surfaced on TV; TV rail rendering"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""},{"label":"","value":"Capability ACs from CAP-PLAY (resume positions) and B-DISC (watchlist rules) apply on this platform. Platform-specific scenarios only:"}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Continue-watching rail\n  Given the viewer has one or more partially watched entitled titles\n  When they open the Samsung app home screen\n  Then a continue-watching rail shows those titles with progress indication, and selecting one resumes from the saved position\n\nScenario: Cross-device resume shown on TV\n  Given the viewer paused a film on another device\n  When they open the Samsung app\n  Then the continue-watching rail reflects the latest saved position from the other device\n\nScenario: Add to watchlist by remote\n  Given the viewer is on a film detail screen\n  When they select the watchlist action with the remote\n  Then the title is added to their watchlist and the action toggles to remove\n\nScenario: Watchlist rail\n  Given the viewer has titles on their watchlist\n  When the home screen renders\n  Then a watchlist rail shows those titles in the order defined by B-DISC rules\n\nScenario: Empty states are hidden\n  Given the viewer has no in-progress titles or no watchlist entries\n  When the home screen renders\n  Then the corresponding rail is not shown","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"B-DISC-01","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Browsable catalog of published titles","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse a catalog of published titles and open any title to see its full details, so that I can find and select a film to watch."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 browsable experience; John, 25:29 Apple TV Plus model) + Assumption - client to confirm (catalog browsable before sign-in; title metadata field set)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-01"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (title metadata, artwork, publish state)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (catalog service consumed by all six client platforms); data/volume factor (must present well at 100 to 500 titles, pagination or progressive loading required); integration with CAP-CON publish state."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Published titles appear in the browse catalog\n  Given a title has been published in the content console\n  When a viewer opens the catalog browse view\n  Then the title appears with thumbnail, poster, title name, synopsis, genres, credits, runtime, and release date\n  And the full metadata field set is an Assumption - client to confirm (canonical metadata schema is owned by CAP-CON)\n\nScenario: Unpublished titles are hidden from public discovery\n  Given a title exists in the content console but is not in a published state\n  When a viewer browses, searches, or opens any curated row\n  Then the title does not appear in browse, search, genre views, or curated rows\n\nScenario: Unpublishing removes a title from public discovery\n  Given a published title is visible in the catalog\n  When the operator unpublishes the title\n  Then the title is no longer returned on any public discovery surface (browse, search, genre views, curated rows)\n  And retention in an entitled viewer's continue-watching rail and library is covered in B-DISC-08 (Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Title detail view\n  Given a published title is visible in the catalog\n  When the viewer selects the title\n  Then a detail view shows the full metadata set including synopsis, genres, credits, and runtime\n  And the detail view exposes the purchase or play entry point (entitlement logic per CAP-PAY, playback per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Catalog performs at full library scale\n  Given the catalog contains 500 published titles\n  When a viewer opens the browse view\n  Then titles load through pagination or progressive loading without requesting the full catalog in a single response\n\nScenario: Browsing does not require sign-in\n  Given a viewer who is not signed in\n  When they open the catalog browse view\n  Then they can browse titles and open title details without authenticating","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"B-DISC-02","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Genre taxonomy and genre browse","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to browse the catalog by genre, so that I can narrow the library to the kinds of films I enjoy."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"browse by genre\") + Allion scoping decision (flat operator-managed taxonomy)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC-01, CAP-CON (genre assignment per title)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build on top of the catalog service; low algorithmic complexity (static taxonomy, no tagging intelligence); data factor (titles carry one or more genres)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Genre list shows only populated genres\n  Given the operator has defined a flat list of genres in the content console\n  When a viewer opens genre browse\n  Then only genres containing at least one published title are listed\n\nScenario: Browsing a genre\n  Given a genre contains published titles\n  When the viewer selects that genre\n  Then every published title assigned to that genre is shown\n  And no title outside that genre is shown\n\nScenario: A title in multiple genres appears under each\n  Given a published title is assigned to two genres\n  When the viewer browses either genre\n  Then the title appears in both genre views\n\nScenario: Default ordering within a genre\n  Given a viewer is browsing a genre\n  When the genre view loads\n  Then titles are ordered newest release first (default ordering is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Genre changes propagate without an app release\n  Given the operator renames a genre or reassigns a title's genres in the content console\n  When clients next load genre browse\n  Then the updated taxonomy and assignments are reflected with no client app update required","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"B-DISC-03","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Text search across the catalog","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to search the catalog by text, so that I can find a specific film quickly instead of scrolling the library."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"basic search\") + Allion scoping decision (searchable fields: title, synopsis, credits; simple relevance, no machine learning)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build or managed search component (build vs integrate decision); simple relevance only, no ML ranking; data/volume factor is modest at 500 titles; index freshness tied to publish events."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search matches title, synopsis, and credits\n  Given a published title whose name, synopsis, or credits contain the word \"orbit\"\n  When the viewer searches for \"orbit\"\n  Then that title appears in the results\n\nScenario: Partial matching on title\n  Given a published title named \"Starfall\"\n  When the viewer searches for \"star\"\n  Then \"Starfall\" appears in the results\n\nScenario: Case-insensitive matching on title\n  Given a published title named \"Starfall\"\n  When the viewer searches for \"STAR\"\n  Then \"Starfall\" appears in the results\n\nScenario: Simple relevance ordering\n  Given the search term matches one title by name and another title only by synopsis\n  When results are returned\n  Then the title-name match ranks above the synopsis-only match\n  And no personalized or ML-based ranking is applied\n\nScenario: Only published titles are searchable\n  Given a title is unpublished\n  When any search term matching it is entered\n  Then it does not appear in the results\n\nScenario: Search responds within the platform latency target\n  Given the catalog contains 500 published titles\n  When a search is executed\n  Then results return within the assumed p95 API latency target of 500 ms (QoE target is an Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"B-DISC-04","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Operator-curated rows on the home screen","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want the home screen to surface curated rows such as featured, top 10, and new this week, so that I can quickly see what is worth watching without a recommendation engine."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 \"here are like the top 10 things\", weekly big release, no rec engine) + Allion scoping decision (row set: featured, top 10, new this week)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (curated row management), B-DISC-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration with CAP-CON row configuration; rendering multiplier across six client platforms (capability ACs here, presentation in PLAT epics); no algorithmic work (rows are manually curated, not computed)."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Configured rows render on the home screen\n  Given the operator has configured featured, top 10, and new this week rows in the content console\n  When a viewer opens the home screen\n  Then each configured row renders with its titles in the operator-defined order\n\nScenario: Rows are identical for all viewers\n  Given two different signed-in viewers\n  When both open the home screen at the same time\n  Then both see the same curated rows with the same titles in the same order\n  And no personalized or algorithmic reordering is applied\n\nScenario: Unpublished titles drop out of rows\n  Given a title in a curated row is unpublished by the operator\n  When a viewer next loads the home screen\n  Then the title is omitted and the row renders without error\n\nScenario: Empty rows are hidden\n  Given a curated row contains no published titles\n  When a viewer opens the home screen\n  Then that row is not displayed\n\nScenario: Row changes reach clients without an app release\n  Given the operator reorders or replaces titles in a curated row\n  When clients next load the home screen\n  Then the updated row content is shown with no client app update required","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","allion"]},{"id":"B-DISC-05","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Continue-watching rail","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want a continue-watching rail showing films I have started but not finished, so that I can resume any of them from where I left off on any of my devices."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 13, cross-device rail), building on the pause and resume expectation John set on the Jul 1 call (39:34)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-PLAY (resume points), CAP-ID (account sign-in)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (consumes CAP-PLAY resume points, does not create them); cross-device state sync; per-account data at the assumed 100K concurrent premiere bar (load bar for B is an Assumption - client to confirm, per CAP-INF), read-heavy at premiere spikes."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Started titles appear in the rail\n  Given a signed-in viewer has started a purchased title and stopped partway through\n  When they open the home screen\n  Then the title appears in the continue-watching rail with its resume position indicated\n\nScenario: Resuming from the rail\n  Given a title appears in the viewer's continue-watching rail\n  When the viewer selects it\n  Then playback resumes from the stored resume point (resume behavior per CAP-PLAY)\n\nScenario: Cross-device continuity\n  Given a viewer paused a title on one device\n  When they sign in on a different supported device and load the home screen\n  Then the same title appears in the continue-watching rail with the same resume position\n\nScenario: Ordering by recency\n  Given a viewer has multiple titles in progress\n  When the home screen loads\n  Then the rail orders titles most recently watched first\n\nScenario: Finished titles leave the rail\n  Given a viewer watches a title to completion\n  When they next load the home screen\n  Then that title no longer appears in the continue-watching rail\n  And the completion threshold is reaching 95 percent of runtime (threshold value is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Signed-out viewers see no rail\n  Given a viewer who is not signed in\n  When they open the home screen\n  Then no continue-watching rail is displayed","scenarioCount":6,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","allion","decision"]},{"id":"B-DISC-06","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Watchlist","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to add titles to and remove titles from a watchlist, so that I can save films I intend to watch and find them again on any of my devices."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (register decision 13)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (account sign-in), B-DISC-01"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New build (per-account list service plus client touchpoints on every surface); cross-device sync; write bursts possible around weekly releases."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Adding a title to the watchlist\n  Given a signed-in viewer is on a published title's detail view\n  When they select add to watchlist\n  Then the title appears in their watchlist\n\nScenario: Removing a title from the watchlist\n  Given a title is on the viewer's watchlist\n  When they select remove from watchlist\n  Then the title no longer appears in their watchlist\n\nScenario: Watchlist is per account and cross-device\n  Given a viewer added a title to their watchlist on one device\n  When they sign in on a different supported device\n  Then the same watchlist contents are shown\n\nScenario: Adding requires sign-in\n  Given a viewer who is not signed in\n  When they attempt to add a title to a watchlist\n  Then they are prompted to sign in\n\nScenario: Add completes after sign-in\n  Given a viewer was prompted to sign in after attempting a watchlist add\n  When they complete sign-in successfully\n  Then the title they attempted to add appears in their watchlist (deferred add behavior is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Duplicate adds are idempotent\n  Given a title is already on the viewer's watchlist\n  When they attempt to add it again\n  Then the watchlist still contains exactly one entry for that title and no error is shown\n\nScenario: Unpublished titles are hidden from the watchlist\n  Given a title on the viewer's watchlist is unpublished by the operator\n  When the viewer opens their watchlist\n  Then the title is not displayed and the list renders without error","scenarioCount":7,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","decision"]},{"id":"B-DISC-07","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Publish-to-discovery freshness for weekly releases","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a platform team, I want a newly published title to reach every discovery surface quickly and consistently, so that the weekly big release is fully findable at the moment its premiere marketing lands."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 39:34 weekly big release driving the spike) + Assumption - client to confirm (freshness target of 5 minutes)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (publish event), B-DISC-01, B-DISC-03, B-DISC-04"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration (publish event fan-out to catalog, search index, and rows); consistency across surfaces under premiere load; cache invalidation across CDN and clients."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: A new release becomes browsable after publish\n  Given the operator publishes a new title\n  When 5 minutes have elapsed (freshness target is an Assumption - client to confirm)\n  Then the title appears in catalog browse and its assigned genre views\n\nScenario: A new release becomes searchable after publish\n  Given the operator publishes a new title\n  When the freshness target has elapsed\n  Then searching its title name returns it in the results\n\nScenario: A new release appears in its configured rows\n  Given the operator has placed the new title in the featured and new this week rows before publishing\n  When the title is published and the freshness target has elapsed\n  Then the title renders in those rows on the home screen\n\nScenario: Discovery surfaces stay consistent under premiere load\n  Given a premiere-scale audience is loading the home screen (load bar per CAP-INF)\n  When a newly published title has passed the freshness target\n  Then browse, search, and curated rows all return the title (no surface lags the others beyond the freshness target)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"B-DISC-08","epicId":"B-DISC","doc":13,"title":"Discovery empty and edge states","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want clear empty and unavailable states across search, watchlist, and rails, so that the experience never looks broken when there is nothing to show."},{"label":"Source","value":"Allion scoping decision (empty and edge state coverage) + Assumption - client to confirm (purchased titles remain resumable after unpublish, per permanent-access model)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-DISC-03, B-DISC-04, B-DISC-05, B-DISC-06"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Low technical complexity, high surface multiplier (each state must render correctly on all six client platforms); copy and design input needed for each state."},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Scenario: Search with no results\n  Given no published title matches a search term\n  When a viewer searches for that term\n  Then a no-results state is shown with the search term echoed back\n  And no error is raised\n\nScenario: Empty watchlist\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no watchlist entries\n  When they open their watchlist\n  Then an empty state is shown with a route back to browsing the catalog\n\nScenario: No in-progress titles\n  Given a signed-in viewer has no started, unfinished titles\n  When they open the home screen\n  Then the continue-watching rail is not displayed (no empty rail shell)\n\nScenario: Stale in-app reference to an unpublished title\n  Given a viewer opens a stored in-app reference (watchlist entry, rail entry, or platform deep link) to a title that is no longer published\n  When the client requests that title\n  Then a title-unavailable state is shown and the client does not crash or show a raw error\n\nScenario: Purchased title unpublished from the catalog\n  Given a viewer purchased a title that the operator later unpublishes\n  When the viewer opens the home screen\n  Then the title remains in their continue-watching rail and remains playable (permanent access per the buy-to-own model; retention behavior is an Assumption - client to confirm)","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["allion","assumption"]},{"id":"B-SUB-01","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Subscribe to one of two tiers via Stripe recurring billing","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a viewer, I want to subscribe to one of two subscription tiers billed on a recurring basis, so that I can watch tier-included titles without paying per film."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (John, 33:15-34:06, two tiers with rules baked in; 31:58, Stripe handles transactional plus subscription) + Jul 1 call (John, 23:02, MVP can be PPV-only, subscription left open) + register #4"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-VS-03 (subscription portion of the pre-call payment story; the PPV portion stays with CAP-PAY)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (viewer account and sign-in), CAP-PAY (Stripe integration and entitlement service), B-SUB-02 (tier entitlement rules)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Integration on top of the existing one-time PPV checkout (Stripe Billing recurring products added alongside one-time payments); tier names, prices, and billing cadence are client decisions carried as configuration placeholders (monthly assumed); web subscribe flow assumed as the baseline for mobile and TV apps (Assumption - client to confirm); a client decision requiring native in-app purchase on iOS or Android (store billing, store fees, receipt validation, restore flows) would materially increase this epic's estimate and is plausibly the largest cost swing in the variant; geo gate at payment applies (register #10)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Successful subscription to a tier\n  Given a signed-in viewer with no active subscription\n  When they select a tier and complete Stripe recurring checkout with a valid payment method\n  Then a Stripe subscription is created for that tier\n  And the tier's entitlements are active on the account immediately after payment confirmation\n\nScenario: Exactly two tiers offered\n  Given a viewer on the subscription selection screen\n  When the available plans are displayed\n  Then exactly two tiers are shown, Tier 1 (placeholder: Individual) and Tier 2 (placeholder: Family)\n  And tier names and prices are rendered from configuration values, not hard-coded copy\n\nScenario: Failed initial payment grants nothing\n  Given a viewer attempting to subscribe\n  When the initial Stripe payment fails or is cancelled\n  Then no subscription is created\n  And no tier entitlement is granted\n  And the viewer sees a clear failure message with a retry path\n\nScenario: Billing starts from day one, no free trial\n  Given a viewer completing a new subscription\n  When the subscription is created\n  Then the first billing charge is taken immediately\n  And no trial period is applied (inherited from the base no-free-trial decision, register #3 and #19; a subscription trial would be a scope change, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Geo gate applies to subscription purchase\n  Given a viewer whose IP resolves outside the US\n  When they attempt to start a subscription checkout\n  Then the purchase is blocked with a US-only message, consistent with the PPV geo gate\n\nScenario: Subscribe entry point on mobile apps\n  Given a signed-in viewer on the iOS or Android app with no active subscription\n  When they select a tier-included title\n  Then the app directs them to complete subscription via the web flow (baseline assumption, client to confirm; native in-app purchase would be additional, separately priced scope)\n\nScenario: Subscribe entry point on TV platforms\n  Given a signed-in viewer on a TV app with no active subscription\n  When they select a tier-included title\n  Then the app directs them to complete subscription on the web flow (baseline assumption, client to confirm in-app purchase policy position)","scenarioCount":7,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-02","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Tier entitlement rules baked into configuration","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want tier-based entitlement rules baked into configuration, so that each tier unlocks the correct titles and playback quality without a dynamic admin layer."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (John, 34:06-34:46, bake the rules in, user-based rule sets, no control center to manage content bundles) + Jun 22 call (Windana, 32:39, tier-gated 4K raised as a rule-engine concern) + register #4"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-01 (active subscriptions), CAP-PAY (shared entitlement service), CAP-PLAY (quality ladder enforcement)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"New rule layer inside the existing entitlement service rather than a separate system; rules are configuration-driven with no admin UI (deliberate scope cut per Jun 22); per-title tier assignment (B-SUB-08) is the single console-side input the rules consume; whether 4K is gated by tier is an open client question and changes player and packaging behaviour if confirmed; entitlement checks must behave identically across all six platform surfaces"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Tier-included title plays for a subscriber\n  Given a viewer with an active Tier 2 subscription\n  And a published title assigned to Tier 2\n  When the viewer starts playback\n  Then the entitlement check passes and playback starts\n\nScenario: Title outside the tier is not unlocked by the subscription\n  Given a viewer with an active Tier 1 subscription\n  And a published title not assigned to Tier 1\n  When the viewer opens that title\n  Then playback is not available through the subscription\n  And the PPV purchase option for that title is offered instead\n\nScenario: Quality rule per tier is honoured (4K gating is an open client question)\n  Given the baked-in rules define a maximum playback quality per tier (placeholder: both tiers include 4K, pending client decision on whether 4K is tier-gated)\n  When a subscriber on a given tier starts playback\n  Then the adaptive ladder offered to the player is capped at that tier's configured maximum quality\n\nScenario: Rules are configuration, not an admin surface\n  Given the deployed platform\n  When the content console and all operator screens are inspected\n  Then no screen exists for editing tier definitions, entitlement rules, or tier pricing\n  And per-title tier assignment (B-SUB-08) is the only subscription-related console control\n  And tier rules are loaded from versioned configuration only\n\nScenario: Entitlement rules are consistent across platforms\n  Given the same subscriber account\n  When the same title is opened on web, mobile, and TV surfaces\n  Then the entitlement outcome (play or offer PPV) is identical on every surface","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":false,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-03","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Upgrade or downgrade between tiers","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a subscriber, I want to move between the two tiers, so that I can change my plan as my needs change without cancelling and rejoining."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (standard plan-change behaviour implied by the Jun 22 two-tier model; neither call specified change mechanics)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-01 (subscription in place), B-SUB-02 (tier rules), CAP-PAY (Stripe integration)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Mostly Stripe-native (plan change with proration handled by Stripe Billing); the platform work is entitlement switching at the effective moment; timing rules (immediate vs end of period) are assumptions carried as configuration"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Upgrade takes effect immediately\n  Given a subscriber on Tier 1\n  When they upgrade to Tier 2 and Stripe confirms the prorated charge\n  Then Tier 2 entitlements are active immediately (Assumption - client to confirm timing)\n\nScenario: Downgrade takes effect at the end of the paid period\n  Given a subscriber on Tier 2\n  When they request a downgrade to Tier 1\n  Then Tier 2 entitlements remain active until the current billing period ends\n  And Tier 1 entitlements and billing apply from the next period (Assumption - client to confirm timing)\n\nScenario: Failed upgrade payment leaves the current tier untouched\n  Given a subscriber on Tier 1 attempting an upgrade\n  When the prorated Stripe charge fails\n  Then the subscriber remains on Tier 1 with entitlements unchanged\n  And a clear failure message is shown\n\nScenario: Plan change is visible in account settings\n  Given a subscriber who has requested a tier change\n  When they open their account subscription view (B-SUB-10)\n  Then the current tier, the pending tier (if any), and the effective date are displayed","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]},{"id":"B-SUB-04","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Cancel subscription","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a subscriber, I want to cancel my subscription from my account, so that I stop future charges while keeping what I have already paid for."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (cancellation mechanics not discussed on either call; permanence of PPV purchases per register #3)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-01 (subscription in place), CAP-PAY (Stripe integration; PPV permanence comes from the base entitlement model per register #3)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Stripe-native cancellation; platform work is entitlement expiry at period end and the resubscribe path; no retention or win-back flows are scoped"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Cancel stops future billing\n  Given a subscriber with an active subscription\n  When they cancel from their account settings\n  Then the Stripe subscription is set to end at the close of the current billing period\n  And no further recurring charges are taken\n\nScenario: Access continues until the paid period ends\n  Given a subscriber who has cancelled mid-period\n  When they play a tier-included title before the period end\n  Then playback works as normal\n  And no partial-period refund is issued (Assumption - client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Entitlements end when the paid period ends\n  Given a cancelled subscription whose billing period has ended\n  When the viewer opens a tier-included title\n  Then subscription playback is refused\n  And the PPV purchase option is offered instead\n\nScenario: PPV purchases survive cancellation\n  Given a viewer who cancelled their subscription\n  And a title they previously bought via PPV\n  When they play that purchased title\n  Then playback works, because PPV purchases are permanent buy-to-own access (register #3, enforced by the base CAP-PAY entitlement model)\n\nScenario: Resubscribe after cancellation\n  Given a viewer whose subscription has fully ended\n  When they subscribe again to either tier\n  Then a new subscription is created and tier entitlements are restored immediately","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-05","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Lapsed payment handling with grace period and dunning","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want failed renewal payments handled through Stripe dunning with a defined grace period, so that involuntary churn is minimised without granting indefinite free access."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (renewal failure handling not discussed on either call; Stripe as the payment provider per Jul 1 call and register #3)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-01 (subscription in place), B-SUB-02 (entitlement suspension), CAP-PAY (Stripe webhooks)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Dunning and retry scheduling delegated to Stripe (integration, not build); platform work is webhook-driven entitlement state changes (active, grace, suspended, reinstated); grace period length is an assumption carried as configuration, stated against the assumed monthly billing cadence (cadence is a client placeholder, see epic intro)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Renewal failure starts the grace period\n  Given a subscriber whose renewal charge fails\n  When Stripe reports the failed payment\n  Then the account enters a grace state for the configured grace period (placeholder: 7 days, Assumption - client to confirm)\n  And tier entitlements remain active during grace\n\nScenario: Dunning retries run through Stripe\n  Given an account in the grace state\n  When Stripe's configured retry schedule runs\n  Then retry attempts and payment-update emails are handled by Stripe\n  And no separate dunning system is built by the platform\n\nScenario: Viewer is prompted to fix payment during grace\n  Given a subscriber in the grace state\n  When they open the app or start playback\n  Then a non-blocking prompt asks them to update their payment method\n\nScenario: Grace expiry suspends subscription entitlements\n  Given an account whose grace period has expired without successful payment\n  When the viewer attempts to play a tier-included title\n  Then subscription playback is refused with a payment-update message\n  And previously purchased PPV titles remain fully playable\n\nScenario: Successful payment reinstates entitlements\n  Given a suspended account\n  When the viewer updates their payment method and Stripe collects the outstanding charge\n  Then tier entitlements are reinstated immediately without creating a new subscription","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-06","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"PPV coexistence: subscribers can buy titles outside their tier","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a subscriber, I want to buy a pay-per-view title that my tier does not include, so that my subscription never blocks me from watching anything in the catalog."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (John, 33:15, transactional pay-per-view plus a simple subscription model operating together) + register #3 (PPV is permanent buy-to-own) + register #4"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-02 (tier rules determine what is outside the tier), CAP-PAY (PPV checkout and entitlements)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Two entitlement types (recurring tier grant and permanent PPV grant) coexisting on one account; correct precedence so a viewer is never charged PPV for something their tier already includes; single Stripe customer carrying both one-time and recurring payment objects"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Subscriber buys a title outside their tier\n  Given a subscriber on Tier 1\n  And a published title not included in Tier 1\n  When they complete a one-time PPV purchase for that title\n  Then a permanent PPV entitlement is added to the account\n  And playback of that title starts successfully\n\nScenario: PPV option hidden for tier-included titles\n  Given a subscriber whose tier includes a given title\n  When they open that title's detail page\n  Then no PPV purchase option is shown for it (Assumption - client to confirm)\n  And playback is available through the subscription\n\nScenario: PPV purchase is billed separately from the subscription\n  Given a subscriber buying a PPV title\n  When the Stripe payment completes\n  Then the charge is a one-time payment, separate from the recurring subscription invoice\n\nScenario: PPV entitlement outlives the subscription\n  Given a subscriber who bought a PPV title outside their tier\n  When their subscription later ends for any reason\n  Then the PPV title remains permanently playable on the account\n\nScenario: One account, both entitlement types enforced consistently\n  Given an account holding both an active tier and PPV purchases\n  When entitlement checks run on any platform surface\n  Then tier-included titles resolve via the subscription and purchased titles resolve via PPV, with no title wrongly blocked","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-07","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Per-tier concurrent screen limits","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want the concurrent-screens limit to be configurable per tier, so that the tiers can differ by how many screens can watch at once."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Windana and John, 33:15-34:06, tier examples: single vs family, members and devices floated) + register #9 (configurable screen limit, pass/fail enforcement at playback start) + Assumption - client to confirm (tier differentiators are a client decision; concurrent screens assumed as the differentiator)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-ID (account and session tracking), CAP-PLAY (playback-start enforcement from the base screen-limit capability), B-SUB-01 (tier on the account)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Extension of the existing single configurable limit (register #9) into a per-tier configuration lookup; enforcement mechanics unchanged (simple pass/fail at playback start, deter casual sharing only, no hard anti-circumvention); limit values are client decisions carried as placeholders; household member profiles were floated on Jun 22 as another possible family-tier differentiator and are NOT scoped in this variant (if the client wants profiles, that is additional, separately priced scope)"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Tier 1 screen limit enforced\n  Given a Tier 1 subscriber with a configured limit (placeholder: 1 concurrent screen, client to confirm)\n  When a second concurrent playback is started on the same account\n  Then the new playback is refused with a clear concurrent-screens message\n\nScenario: Tier 2 screen limit enforced\n  Given a Tier 2 subscriber with a configured limit (placeholder: 4 concurrent screens, client to confirm)\n  When playback starts on up to the configured number of screens\n  Then all permitted streams play\n  And one further concurrent playback is refused\n\nScenario: Non-subscribers keep the base limit\n  Given a PPV-only viewer with no subscription\n  When concurrent playbacks are started on the account\n  Then the base configurable account limit applies (default 2, per the base scope)\n\nScenario: Limits are configuration values\n  Given the per-tier screen limit configuration\n  When a limit value is changed in configuration\n  Then enforcement at playback start reflects the new value without a code change\n\nScenario: Enforcement is pass/fail only\n  Given any account at its screen limit\n  When an additional playback is refused\n  Then no device-fingerprinting or anti-circumvention measures beyond the session count are applied","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-08","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Operator assigns titles to tiers in the content console","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As an operator, I want to assign each title to a subscription tier, both tiers, or PPV-only while managing it in the console, so that the catalog sells each title the way the business intends."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jun 22 call (Windana and John, 34:38-34:46, the administrator decides how titles are bundled, but there are only two tiers and no dynamic control center) + register #12 (single-user console)"},{"label":"Supersedes","value":"V1-OP-02 (the subscription-tier assignment portion of the pre-call operator pricing story; the PPV pricing portion stays with CAP-CON)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-CON (console title management), B-SUB-02 (tier rules consume the assignment)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Small additive field set on the existing console title form (new build, low); single-user console constraint unchanged; per-title tier assignment sits deliberately inside the Jun 22 no-control-center boundary, while tier definition, rule, and pricing editing sit outside it and are excluded (see B-SUB-02); deliberate exclusion of any bundle-management or rule-editing surface keeps this thin"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Assign a title to a tier\n  Given the operator editing a title in the console\n  When they set the title's availability to Tier 2\n  Then the saved assignment is used by the entitlement rules for that title\n\nScenario: Assign a title to both tiers\n  Given the operator editing a title\n  When they set availability to both tiers\n  Then subscribers on either tier can play the title\n\nScenario: Default is PPV-only\n  Given a newly created title with no tier assignment\n  When the title is published\n  Then it is sellable via PPV only and no subscription unlocks it (Assumption - client to confirm the default catalog policy)\n\nScenario: Assignment changes apply to the live catalog\n  Given a published title assigned to Tier 1\n  When the operator removes the tier assignment and saves\n  Then new playback attempts by Tier 1 subscribers resolve to the PPV offer\n\nScenario: No bundle control center exists\n  Given the console as deployed\n  When all console screens are inspected\n  Then tier assignment is the only subscription control exposed, and tier definitions, rules, and pricing are not editable in the console","scenarioCount":5,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-09","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Subscription metrics in the metering view","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As the platform team, I want subscription revenue and usage broken out in the metering view, so that per-stream unit economics stay meaningful when revenue is no longer purely per-title."},{"label":"Source","value":"Jul 1 call (John, 31:02, unit economics framing rests on PPV, so adding subscription changes cost and revenue attribution) + register #15 (minimal metering epic) + Assumption - client to confirm"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"CAP-MET (playback sessions and GB-delivered metering), B-SUB-01 (subscription data)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Extension of the minimal metering views, not a new analytics build; attribution logic to split delivery cost between subscription playback and PPV playback; recurring revenue figures come from Stripe reporting data rather than a new billing store; billing cadence is a client placeholder (monthly assumed, see epic intro), so revenue views report per billing period rather than hard-coding a monthly cycle"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Active subscribers per tier\n  Given the metering view\n  When the operator opens the subscription summary\n  Then the count of active subscriptions is shown per tier, including accounts in grace\n\nScenario: Recurring revenue reported from Stripe\n  Given active subscriptions billed through Stripe\n  When the subscription summary is viewed\n  Then recurring revenue for the reporting period is calculated from Stripe subscription data and displayed\n  And Stripe is the source of truth for billed amounts, with configured placeholder prices used only until the client sets pricing\n\nScenario: Revenue split between subscription and PPV\n  Given a period containing both PPV purchases and subscription billing\n  When the revenue view is opened for that period\n  Then subscription revenue and PPV revenue are reported as separate lines\n\nScenario: Delivery attribution by entitlement type\n  Given playback sessions metered per title\n  When GB delivered is reported for a period\n  Then GB is attributable to subscription playback vs PPV playback, so per-stream cost can be compared against each revenue type","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption","decision"]},{"id":"B-SUB-10","epicId":"B-SUB","doc":13,"title":"Subscription management view in account settings","options":"B only","fields":[{"label":"Options","value":"B only"},{"label":"Story","value":"As a subscriber, I want one place in my account to see and manage my subscription, so that I can check my plan, billing, and payment method without contacting support."},{"label":"Source","value":"Assumption - client to confirm (self-service management not discussed on either call; standard companion to any recurring billing offering)"},{"label":"Dependencies","value":"B-SUB-01 (subscription in place), B-SUB-03 (plan change actions), B-SUB-04 (cancel action), B-SUB-05 (payment-method update during grace), CAP-ID (account settings surface)"},{"label":"Complexity drivers","value":"Stripe Customer Portal assumed as the baseline for web (integration, not build); mobile and TV apps show subscription status and link out to the web management flow rather than rebuilding management screens on each surface (Assumption - client to confirm); a custom-built management surface across all six platform surfaces would be additional, separately priced scope"},{"label":"T-shirt size","value":"_dev to fill_"},{"label":"Acceptance criteria","value":""}],"gherkin":"Background:\n  Given the client has added the subscription variant to Option B\n\nScenario: Subscription overview is available\n  Given a signed-in subscriber on the web app\n  When they open the subscription section of account settings\n  Then the current tier, renewal or end date, and next billing amount are displayed\n\nScenario: Management actions reachable from one place\n  Given a subscriber on the subscription management view\n  When they choose to change plan, cancel, or update their payment method\n  Then each action is reachable from that view via the Stripe-hosted portal (baseline assumption, client to confirm)\n\nScenario: Invoices and receipts are accessible\n  Given a subscriber with past subscription charges\n  When they open their billing history\n  Then invoices and receipts for subscription charges are available via the Stripe-hosted portal\n\nScenario: Mobile and TV apps link to the web management flow\n  Given a signed-in subscriber on a mobile or TV app\n  When they open subscription settings\n  Then the app shows subscription status and directs management actions to the web flow (baseline assumption, client to confirm)","scenarioCount":4,"assumptionFlagged":true,"sourceTypes":["call","assumption"]}],"assumptions":{"crossCutting":[{"n":1,"assumption":"App store billing: Apple, Google, Roku, Amazon, and Samsung storefront policies may require platform billing (with a platform commission) for in-app purchase of digital content. Both paths are scoped per platform: (1) native store billing, (2) purchase on web, watch in app. The client selects a path per platform.","impact":"Largest single swing on both build cost and unit economics. A platform commission on in-app sales materially changes per-sale margin; the web-purchase path avoids commission but adds funnel friction on TV and mobile."},{"n":2,"assumption":"Option B load bar: the 100,000-concurrent premiere profile is applied to Option B weekly releases. The client stated 100,000 for the one-film scenario only.","impact":"Sizing of infrastructure, load-test scope, and managed-platform tier for Option B."},{"n":3,"assumption":"Managed video platform: scoped vendor-agnostic with Bunny Stream as the reference. A timeboxed validation spike (CAP-PIPE) must confirm 4K, 100,000-concurrent delivery, multi-DRM, watermarking, and caption support, with written vendor confirmation, before build month 2.","impact":"A failed spike moves the pipeline to a Mux-class alternative at a higher run rate, or to a build path with more build time."},{"n":4,"assumption":"Quality-of-experience targets are proposed, not client-set: video start under 4 s, rebuffer under 1% of watch time, p95 API under 500 ms, payment confirmation under 10 s, error rate under 0.5% at peak.","impact":"These drive load-test pass/fail and alerting thresholds; they need client sign-off before the month 4-5 stress-test window."},{"n":5,"assumption":"Concurrent-screens limit: configurable, default 2, simple pass/fail at playback start. Abandoned sessions release their slot after a timeout (default 2 minutes).","impact":"Final values are client decisions; enforcement strictness affects perceived sharing tolerance."},{"n":6,"assumption":"US-only: geo-IP gate at purchase and playback, no VPN countermeasures. US sales tax via Stripe Tax.","impact":"Stronger geo enforcement or non-US expansion is new scope."},{"n":7,"assumption":"Single-operator console for both options, including Option B's 100-500 title catalog and weekly releases.","impact":"If operations need more than one person, multi-user console work returns to scope."},{"n":8,"assumption":"Buy-to-own: purchase grants permanent access, survives later unpublish of the title; refunds and chargebacks are operated in the Stripe dashboard (no in-app tooling) and revoke the entitlement.","impact":"Behavior confirmations only; small build impact, notable policy impact."},{"n":9,"assumption":"Subscription is not in either base scope. B-SUB prices a 2-tier variant separately; tier names, prices, differentiators, and 4K gating are client decisions carried as placeholders.","impact":"Adding subscription pulls B-SUB into scope at its separately stated estimate."},{"n":10,"assumption":"Watermarking technology and vendor are not selected; a manual leak-trace workflow is scoped, no automated piracy monitoring.","impact":"Vendor choice sets robustness and cost; automation would be new scope."},{"n":11,"assumption":"LG and Apple tvOS apps are excluded from both base scopes and carried as a flagged option line under Option B.","impact":"Adding either platform adds a per-platform delivery epic to the estimate."},{"n":12,"assumption":"A trailer plays on the film detail page without sign-in. If confirmed, a trailer upload and hosting story is added to the content console (not yet scoped in CAP-CON).","impact":"Small build addition; noted because it is currently the only user-facing element without a matching console story."},{"n":13,"assumption":"Timeline anchor: roughly 6 months to launch, build scoped at 4-5 months, 100,000-concurrent stress testing from month 4-5. Store certification cycles (Apple, Google, Roku, Amazon, Samsung) sit inside this window as external dependencies.","impact":"Certification resubmissions or a different Option B timeline shift the stress-test window proportionally."}],"perEpic":[{"epicId":"CAP-ID","assumptions":["Baseline password rules are a configurable set defaulting to minimum length 8 with no other composition rules, client to confirm (owned by CAP-ID-01, referenced by CAP-ID-04 and CAP-ID-07).","When an Apple or Google sign-in email matches an existing email account, the accounts are linked only after the viewer confirms ownership; exact linking rule, client to confirm.","TV activation codes expire after a configurable period, default 15 minutes, client to confirm.","Password reset revokes all existing sessions for the account by default, client to confirm (owned by CAP-ID-06, referenced by CAP-ID-04).","Session and token lifetime defaults, client to confirm.","Sign out everywhere revokes every session including the current one, client to confirm.","Account deletion (CAP-ID-09) is scoped because App Store certification requires in-app account deletion where account creation is offered; wider US state privacy obligations are assumed, client to confirm.","Data retention rules for payment and tax records after account deletion are a client and legal decision, client to confirm.","Multi-user profiles under one account are excluded from base scope, client to confirm; multi-member account concepts appeared only in the Jun 22 subscription-tier discussion and sit in the separately estimated B-SUB variant."],"openQuestions":["Account-linking rule when a social sign-in email matches an existing email account needs a client decision before build.","Whether password reset should revoke all active sessions (yes/no) needs client confirmation; CAP-ID-04 and CAP-ID-06 both hinge on it.","Session and token lifetimes and the activation-code expiry default need client sign-off as configurables.","Password rule baseline (minimum length only vs additional composition rules) needs client confirmation.","Account deletion scope and payment/tax record retention rules need client and legal input; the story is a certification gate for iOS either way.","Confirm multi-user profiles stay out of V1 base scope, with multi-member concepts deferred to the separately estimated B-SUB subscription variant."]},{"epicId":"CAP-PAY","assumptions":["On mobile and TV storefronts where store billing policy prohibits Stripe checkout for digital goods, purchase completes on the web surface and the entitlement syncs to the device, client to confirm.","Payment confirmation is shown within 10 seconds of a delayed outcome resolving (QoE target), client to confirm.","Default concurrent-screens limit of 2, client to confirm.","Abandoned playback sessions release their screen-limit slot after a configurable timeout, default 2 minutes, client to confirm.","US sales tax is calculated and collected via Stripe Tax at checkout, client to confirm.","Refunds and chargebacks are handled in the Stripe dashboard with no in-app refund tooling for V1, client to confirm.","A refund or chargeback revokes the entitlement for that film, client to confirm.","A purchased film remains playable for its owner if the operator later unpublishes it from the catalog, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Store billing policies for digital goods on iOS, Android, Roku, Fire TV, and Samsung storefronts may prohibit in-app Stripe checkout; this needs per-storefront verification and materially affects both the A and B estimates. Each platform epic carries a purchase-path decision story for this.","Final concurrent-screens limit value is a client decision (default of 2 is a placeholder).","Final session-timeout value for releasing abandoned streams is a client decision (default of 2 minutes is a placeholder).","Whether refunds and chargebacks should revoke access to the purchased film needs client confirmation.","Whether owners keep playback access to a title after it is unpublished from the catalog needs client confirmation."]},{"epicId":"CAP-PLAY","assumptions":["Default concurrent-screens limit of 2 per account, client to confirm.","Caption language preference persists across sessions on the same account, client to confirm.","Heartbeat interval default of 60 seconds, client to confirm.","A playback session is marked ended after 3 consecutive missed heartbeats, client to confirm.","When a stream cannot start, a retry message appears within 10 seconds (assumed target, client to confirm).","Quality-of-experience targets are proposed values pending client confirmation: video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1% of watch time, playback error rate under 0.5% of sessions at peak.","Continue-watching feed returns at most the 20 most recent in-progress titles (Option B only), client to confirm.","Automatic quality step-up on network recovery is included as standard adaptive-player behavior (Allion scoping decision, not client-stated)."],"openQuestions":["With the default 60-second heartbeat and 3-missed-heartbeat timeout, a killed app can hold a screen-limit slot for roughly 3 minutes; client should confirm whether that hold time is acceptable or the values should be tightened.","QoE target values need client sign-off before the month 4-5 stress-test window so pass/fail criteria are agreed ahead of verification.","4K delivery depends on the managed-platform validation spike in CAP-PIPE; if the spike fails, the top ladder tier and the 4K acceptance scenario need revisiting."]},{"epicId":"CAP-DRM","assumptions":["Stream quality caps tied to each device's DRM security level (standard multi-DRM practice), client to confirm.","HDCP output protection applied as the managed platform default only, with no custom anti-circumvention hardening, client to confirm.","Exact forensic watermarking technology and vendor not yet selected, client to confirm.","Watermark robustness bar for re-encoded and screen-captured copies to be set at technology selection, client to confirm.","Minimum leaked-sample length required for watermark extraction to be set at technology selection, client to confirm.","A manual, on-request leak-trace investigation workflow is in scope (no automated piracy monitoring), client to confirm.","The 100,000 concurrent premiere load bar applies to Option B as well as Option A, client to confirm.","Peak error rate target below 0.5 percent at premiere load, client to confirm.","Video start time under 4 seconds with watermarking active, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["The managed platform (Bunny Stream reference) must be confirmed for multi-DRM, forensic watermarking, and premiere-scale license capacity; the CAP-PIPE validation spike resolves this before estimates firm up.","Whether the 100K concurrent premiere bar applies to Option B's weekly big releases, or a lower Option B bar is acceptable.","Watermarking technology and vendor selection is open; it determines the robustness bar and the minimum sample length for leak tracing.","The default HDCP behavior per DRM system and platform (quality capped vs playback blocked on non-compliant outputs) needs to be documented and accepted by the client before test.","Whether capping software-only DRM devices below 4K is an acceptable viewer experience for the client."]},{"epicId":"CAP-CON","assumptions":["A single operator is sufficient to run content operations, including the Option B catalog of 100-500 titles plus weekly releases, client to confirm.","Scheduled publish executes within 1 minute of the scheduled time, client to confirm.","Curated row changes reach viewers within 5 minutes of saving, client to confirm.","Required-before-publish metadata fields are name, description, and category, with credits optional, client to confirm.","The category list is a simple operator-managed list in the console rather than a fixed seeded list, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Client to confirm single-operator staffing is acceptable for Option B content operations (100-500 titles plus weekly releases).","Client to confirm the scheduled-publish execution window (1 minute assumed).","Client to confirm the catalog propagation window for curated row changes (5 minutes assumed).","Client to confirm which metadata fields are required before publish (name, description, category assumed; credits optional).","Client to confirm how the category list is managed (operator-editable list assumed; feeds Option B genre browse in B-DISC).","Title price values are a client decision; the console holds a configurable USD field only.","Client to confirm that internal re-provisioning (no self-service reset) is acceptable as the only recovery path for the operator account."]},{"epicId":"CAP-PIPE","assumptions":["Validation spike timebox of two weeks, client to confirm.","4K tier encoded in HEVC only, with H.264 renditions up to 1080p; V1 devices without HEVC support receive 1080p as their quality ceiling, client to confirm.","Resumable upload for interrupted 4K master transfers is expected behaviour, client to confirm (not discussed on either call).","An operator can replace a processed master with a new one that supersedes it after successful processing, client to confirm (not discussed on either call).","The 100,000 concurrent premiere bar applies to Option B as well as Option A, client to confirm (John stated 100K for the one-film scenario only).","QoE targets (video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent, error rate under 0.5 percent at peak) are assumed, client to confirm.","Delivery and QoE metrics are available in our observability stack within 15 minutes of the platform reporting them, client to confirm.","The full 500-title library can be ingested and verified within the 4 weeks before launch, client to confirm (Option B only)."],"openQuestions":["Spike timebox length: is two weeks enough given the go/no-go must land before build month 2?","4K codec strategy: confirm HEVC-only 4K is acceptable, or whether an H.264 4K rendition is required so every V1 device has a 4K path.","Does the 100K concurrent premiere bar also apply to Option B's weekly-release spike, or should B carry a different bar?","QoE targets need client sign-off before they drive alerting thresholds and load-test pass/fail.","Pre-launch bulk ingest window for the 100 to 500 title library: confirm the 4-week assumption (Option B).","Master replacement and resumable upload were not discussed on either call; confirm both are wanted in V1.","Metrics freshness: confirm 15 minutes is fast enough for premiere-night monitoring.","Written vendor confirmation of 100K delivery capacity is an external dependency; if the vendor cannot confirm it in the spike, the go/no-go points to a Mux-class alternative."]},{"epicId":"CAP-MET","assumptions":["Playback sessions auto-close after 30 minutes without a heartbeat (configurable), client to confirm.","Per-title GB usage is available within a 24 hour maximum latency, client to confirm.","Rendition times per session sum to watched duration within a 1 percent tolerance, client to confirm.","Monthly usage reconciles with the managed platform's reported usage within 5 percent, client to confirm.","Monthly reconciliation against vendor-reported usage is an added data-quality control (Allion scoping decision), not a client request.","Seeded default cost lines (delivery per GB as variable, managed platform base fee as fixed) and their rates, client to confirm.","CSV as the export format and the proposed column sets, client to confirm.","At least 99 percent of playback sessions captured completely at 100,000 concurrent load, client to confirm.","Metering events are buffered for at least 6 hours during ingestion outages and the backlog drains within 6 hours after a spike, client to confirm.","The 100,000 concurrent premiere load bar also applies to Option B, client to confirm.","Catalog rollup renders within 5 seconds at 500 titles, client to confirm.","The catalog-wide economics rollup is a scoping extension of the per-title view to catalog scale (Allion scoping decision), not a direct client request.","Session exports use a pseudonymous account reference with no direct identifiers, pending US video-privacy review, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Treatment of account-level identifiers in accounting exports is subject to US video-privacy review (VPPA/CCPA), already an open V1 question (docs/08-questions-for-john.md, 15.2).","Whether the managed platform exposes per-session usage data or only account-level aggregates; determined by the CAP-PIPE validation spike, with bitrate-based estimation as fallback.","Client to confirm CSV format and column sets with their accounting team before build.","Client to confirm all assumed numeric thresholds: 30 min heartbeat timeout, 24 h data latency, 1 percent rendition tolerance, 5 percent reconciliation tolerance, 99 percent capture completeness, 6 h buffer and drain windows, 5 s rollup render time.","Client to confirm the seeded default cost lines and rates in the cost register.","Client to confirm that the 100K concurrent premiere load bar applies to Option B (John stated 100K for the one-film scenario only)."]},{"epicId":"CAP-INF","assumptions":["Production rollback completes within 15 minutes, client to confirm.","p95 API response under 500 ms at peak, assumed target, client to confirm.","Platform error rate under 0.5 percent at peak, assumed target, client to confirm.","Health metrics available with at most 1 minute lag, assumed target, client to confirm.","Alerts reach the on-call channel within 5 minutes, assumed target, client to confirm.","Log and metric retention period after a premiere event, client to confirm.","Surge protection mechanism (queue vs waiting room) and its viewer-facing behaviour, client to confirm.","The 100,000 concurrent premiere bar also applies to Option B weekly releases, client to confirm.","Load-test soak window duration, client to confirm.","Managed video platform vendor supports and permits high-volume (100,000 concurrent) test traffic, client to confirm with vendor.","Stress-test pass thresholds (video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent, payment confirmation under 10 seconds) are assumed targets, client to confirm.","The month 4 to 5 stress-test window is anchored to the roughly 6 month timeline; if the Option B timeline lands differently, the window shifts proportionally, client to confirm for Option B.","Weekly release spike size per title is an assumed profile, unproven until Option B releases run."],"openQuestions":["Does the 100,000 concurrent premiere bar apply to Option B weekly releases, or should B carry a different sizing bar?","Client sign-off needed on all assumed operational and quality targets: video start time, rebuffer ratio, p95 API latency, payment confirmation time, error rate, metric lag, alert notification time, rollback time, and observability retention period.","Which surge mechanism does the client prefer (rate limiting only, request queueing, or a full waiting room), and what should queued viewers see?","The managed video platform vendor must confirm it permits and supports 100,000 concurrent test-traffic runs before the load-test harness design is locked.","Option B timeline is a scoping output (John asked for two numbers and two timelines); the month 4 to 5 stress-test window for Option B moves with whatever timeline is agreed.","Soak duration for the full-scale 100,000 concurrent load test needs to be agreed with the client."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-WEB","assumptions":["Unsupported browsers show a clear message listing the supported set, client to confirm.","A trailer plays on the film detail page without payment or sign-in, client to confirm.","The TV activation page uses a short memorable web address, client to confirm.","Browser support policy is the current and previous major versions of Chrome, Edge, Safari, and Firefox, client to confirm.","A 15-second forward skip accompanies the sourced 15-second rewind; carried as a scoping addition in CAP-PLAY, client to confirm.","Genre pages have their own direct web addresses for deep linking; Allion scoping decision, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Browser-to-DRM mapping is not fixed by any source: CAP-DRM packages all three systems (Widevine, FairPlay, PlayReady) but does not assign them per browser. Confirm the per-browser variant with the managed platform vendor and record it in CAP-DRM; PLAT-WEB no longer hardcodes a mapping.","If the trailer element is confirmed, a trailer asset upload and hosting story is added to CAP-CON (see cross-cutting assumption 12).","Browser version certification policy needs client confirmation before the month 4-5 stress-test window so the PLAT-WEB-08 matrix is stable for the repeat pass."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-IOS","assumptions":["Supported iOS versions are the current and previous major iOS release, client to confirm.","iPhone-first delivery with iPad running in compatibility mode (no dedicated iPad layouts); the whole form-factor split is an assumption, client to confirm.","In-app account deletion is included as an App Store policy requirement (a platform-driven addition, not a client request); the matching backend deletion work is carried in CAP-ID (CAP-ID-09).","Search results refresh automatically once the viewer stops typing, rather than on explicit submit; client to confirm the interaction model."],"openQuestions":["Purchase path on iOS is an open client scoping decision: Apple In-App Purchase (Apple commission on iOS-originated sales) versus purchase on web only (iOS app plays already-purchased content). Both paths are scoped; the pack does not decide.","iPad support level (compatibility mode versus native iPad layouts) affects the estimate and needs client confirmation.","If the purchase-on-web path is chosen, the unentitled-viewer wording must be agreed and reviewed as part of App Store certification (owned by PLAT-IOS-06, Apple-review external dependency).","Apple tvOS remains a flagged option line in Option B only, open with the client per register decision 1."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-AND","assumptions":["Minimum supported Android OS version and tablet layout support, client to confirm.","Google Play billing policy path (Play Billing in-app vs web purchase pattern) is an open client decision; both paths are scoped for costing and the Play policy position must be re-verified at build time.","Google Play service fee rate per transaction is per Google's current fee schedule, to confirm.","Quality cap level for devices below Widevine L1, client to confirm.","QoE targets (video start, rebuffer ratio, API latency, error rate) are assumed pending client confirmation, and set the test network profile for the 4K playback scenario and the catalog scroll and rendering bar.","Google Play store policy requirements are taken as at submission time and may change before release.","Applying the 100,000 concurrent full-journey load bar to Option B is an assumption, client to confirm.","Concurrent-screens limit is a configurable field with a default of 2, final value client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Billing path selection (Path 1 Play Billing vs Path 2 web purchase) is unresolved; it changes build scope, per-transaction cost, refund handling, and store compliance work.","Under Path 1, geo enforcement relies on Play store-country controls rather than the geo-IP gate at checkout; whether that satisfies the US-only requirement needs validation.","Under Option B with Path 1, per-title in-app product creation and price management in Play Console for the full catalog and each weekly release adds recurring operating cost; this should inform the path decision.","Google review approval is Google's decision and is tracked as the release milestone, not a pass/fail acceptance criterion; review timelines are an external dependency on the launch date.","Minimum Android version and tablet support decisions affect the device test matrix and should be confirmed before sizing is finalized."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-ROKU","assumptions":["Roku platform policy is understood to require Roku Pay for purchases completed inside a channel; client to confirm against current Roku policy at design lock.","Roku is understood to apply a platform revenue share to in-channel transactions; rate and applicability to confirm against current Roku terms.","Roku certification lead times and criteria are assumed from Roku's published checklist; client to confirm, validated at submission.","Deep-link launch support is included pending confirmation of whether Roku certification requires deep linking for this channel type.","Lowest supported Roku model and the supported device set, client to confirm at design lock."],"openQuestions":["Purchase path on Roku is an open client decision: in-channel Roku Pay (Path 1) vs purchase on web, watch on Roku (Path 2); both paths carry acceptance criteria and both are to be estimated.","Whether Roku certification requires deep linking for this channel type; if not required, the PLAT-ROKU-01 deep-link scenario and the matching clause in the PLAT-ROKU-07 pre-submission check can be dropped.","Roku submission scheduling should carry contingency for at least one resubmission cycle in the delivery timeline."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-FTV","assumptions":["Cold start budget: the Fire TV landing screen is interactive within 5 seconds of app launch, client to confirm.","Supported device baseline: Fire OS versions covering the top-selling Fire TV Stick generations and Fire TV Edition televisions needed to meet the 80 percent US market coverage target; the concrete device and OS-version list will be proposed at estimation, client to confirm.","Alexa voice search is excluded from Fire TV scope in both options, client to confirm.","Amazon Appstore monetization policy governs which purchase pattern is viable; both patterns are priced in the estimate pending the client decision.","Amazon Appstore review lead times are outside project control; the schedule assumes at least one review cycle fits inside the launch window, client to confirm.","Trick-play recovery: playback resumes within 5 seconds after repeated scrubbing, skipping, and pausing, without an app restart, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Purchase pattern on Fire TV (Amazon In-App Purchasing vs web purchase through Stripe) is an open client decision carried in PLAT-FTV-06; both patterns are priced and neither is recommended by the pack.","The Fire OS DRM variant (Widevine or PlayReady, served by the managed platform) is unconfirmed and is to be validated in the CAP-PIPE validation spike.","The supported Fire TV device and Fire OS version list must be agreed with the client at estimation; three stories (PLAT-FTV-01, -04, -07) depend on it.","Cold start and trick-play recovery budget values (both set at 5 seconds) need client confirmation."]},{"epicId":"PLAT-SAM","assumptions":["Samsung app landing screen interactive within 5 seconds of launch, client to confirm.","QoE targets are assumed pending client confirmation: video start under 4 seconds, rebuffer ratio under 1 percent, payment confirmation within 10 seconds.","Samsung store billing policy: Samsung Checkout may be required for in-app purchases on Tizen; both purchase paths are scoped and the client selects one before build.","Samsung Checkout is expected to carry a platform commission; the rate must be confirmed against Samsung's current published terms before unit economics are finalized.","Supported Tizen version floor proposed as recent model years covering the large majority of installed Samsung TVs, client to confirm.","Default concurrent-screens limit of 2 per account, configurable, client to confirm the final value.","The 100K concurrent full-journey load bar applies to both options; the client stated 100K for the one-film launch, so extending it to Option B is an assumption."],"openQuestions":["Samsung billing policy: does Samsung permit an off-store Stripe purchase flow for this app category, or is Samsung Checkout mandatory? Client decision needed before build; it affects per-sale cost and certification scope.","If Samsung Checkout is chosen, the commission rate needs confirmation and must be reflected in the unit economics model.","Supported Tizen version floor (device test matrix) to be agreed with the client.","QoE targets, including the proposed 5-second app-launch budget, need client confirmation.","Widevine support on Tizen varies by model year; PlayReady is the baseline and Widevine availability is validated under the CAP-PIPE spike.","LG webOS and Apple tvOS remain a flagged option line under Option B, open with the client; they are not scoped in this epic."]},{"epicId":"B-DISC","assumptions":["Catalog browsing and title details available without sign-in, client to confirm.","Title detail metadata field set including runtime and release date, client to confirm (canonical schema owned by CAP-CON).","Default genre ordering is newest release first, client to confirm.","Search meets the assumed p95 API latency target of 500 ms, client to confirm (QoE target).","Continue-watching completion threshold of 95 percent of runtime, client to confirm.","Publish-to-discovery freshness target of 5 minutes, client to confirm.","Purchased titles remain in the continue-watching rail and stay playable after unpublish, per the buy-to-own permanent-access model, client to confirm.","Option B premiere load bar of 100K concurrent is assumed (John stated 100K for the one-film scenario only), client to confirm per CAP-INF.","A watchlist add attempted while signed out completes automatically after successful sign-in, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Unpublish behavior for entitled viewers: confirm purchased titles remain playable and visible in the owner's rail after operator unpublish, since this drives an entitlement-aware catalog build.","Shareable deep links are scoped nowhere in the pack; only stored in-app references are covered. If shareable links are wanted, that is a separate story.","Whether the catalog must be browsable before sign-in (currently assumed yes).","Canonical title metadata field set: runtime and release date are unsourced, and genre newest-first ordering depends on release date being in the CAP-CON schema.","Option B load bar: 100K concurrent full-journey profile is carried over from the one-film scenario as an assumption.","Deferred watchlist add after sign-in: confirm the post-sign-in completion flow, or drop it and require the viewer to retry."]},{"epicId":"B-SUB","assumptions":["Web subscribe flow is the baseline on mobile and TV apps; native in-app purchase would be additional, separately priced scope, client to confirm.","Tier names and prices are configuration placeholders (Individual, Family); naming and pricing remain client decisions.","Billing cadence assumed monthly as a placeholder; cadence is part of the client-owned tier definition.","Concurrent screens assumed as the tier differentiator; tier differentiators are a client decision.","Per-tier screen limit placeholders of 1 (Tier 1) and 4 (Tier 2), client to confirm.","Upgrades take effect immediately and downgrades at the end of the paid period, client to confirm timing.","No partial-period refund on cancellation, client to confirm.","7-day grace period on failed renewals, with dunning retries and payment-update emails delegated to Stripe, client to confirm.","PPV purchase option hidden for titles already included in a subscriber's tier, client to confirm.","Newly created titles default to PPV-only with no tier assignment, client to confirm the default catalog policy.","No subscription free trial, inherited from the base no-free-trial decision (register #3 and #19); a subscription trial would be a scope change, client to confirm.","Subscription self-service delivered via the Stripe-hosted Customer Portal on web, with mobile and TV apps linking out; a custom-built management surface across all six platform surfaces would be additional scope.","Subscription metrics are an extension of the minimal metering view (register #15), not a new analytics build, client to confirm."],"openQuestions":["Household member profiles were floated on the Jun 22 call as a possible family-tier differentiator; they are NOT scoped in this variant and would be additional, separately priced scope if the client wants them.","Whether 4K playback is tier-gated is an open client question; if confirmed it changes player and packaging behaviour (B-SUB-02).","Native in-app subscription purchase on iOS and Android (and TV app store billing policy) vs the web subscribe flow: a client decision requiring native IAP materially increases this epic's estimate and is plausibly its largest cost swing.","Tier definitions overall (names, prices, billing cadence, differentiators, what each tier includes) remain with the client and are carried only as configuration placeholders.","Grace period length, plan-change timing rules, and the no-refund-on-cancellation position all need client confirmation before estimation is finalised."]}]}};
